0/15405702.2010.514177}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Aftab|first1=Kaleem|title=Brown: the new black! Bollywood in Britain|journal=Critical Quarterly|volume=44|issue=3|year=2002|pages=88\u201398|issn=0011-1562|doi=10.1111/1467-8705.00435}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Jha|first1=Priya|title=Lyrical Nationalism: Gender, Friendship, and Excess in 1970s Hindi Cinema|journal=The Velvet Light Trap|volume=51|issue=1|year=2003|pages=43\u201353|issn=1542-4251|doi=10.1353/vlt.2003.0007}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Jones|first1=Matthew|title=Bollywood, Rasa and Indian Cinema: Misconceptions, Meanings and Millionaire|journal=Visual Anthropology|volume=23|issue=1|year=2009|pages=33\u201343|issn=0894-9468|doi=10.1080/08949460903368895}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Garwood|first1=Ian|title=The Songless Bollywood Film|journal=South Asian Popular Culture|volume=4|issue=2|year=2006|pages=169\u2013183|issn=1474-6689|doi=10.1080/14746680600797210}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscatinline}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://srbachchan.tumblr.com/ Amitabh Bachchan's official blog]\n* {{IMDb name|0000821}}\n* {{Bollywood Hungama|id=325}}\n* {{Twitter|SrBachchan|name=Amitabh Bachchan}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121011170246/http://static.bafta.org/files/amitabhbachchanbrochure-82.pdf British Academy of Film and Television Arts brochure]\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Amitabh Bachchan\n| list =\n{{Padma Vibhushan Awards}}\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 2000\u201309}}\n{{Dadasaheb Phalke Award}}\n{{NationalFilmAwardBestActor}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestActor}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestSupportingActor}}\n{{FilmfareCriticsAwardBestActor}}\n{{FilmfareLifetimeAchievementAward}}\n{{IIFAAwardBestActor}}\n{{IIFAAwardBestSupportingActor}}\n{{Indian Telly Award Best Television Personality}}\n{{Indian Telly Award Best Anchor}}\n{{ProducersGuildFilmAwardBestActor}}\n{{ScreenAwardBestActor}}\n{{StardustAwardBestActor}}\n{{StardustAwardMaleStar}}\n{{ZeeCineAwardBestActorMale}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bachchan, Amitabh}}\n[[Category:Amitabh Bachchan| ]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Indian actor-politicians]]\n[[Category:Indian amateur radio operators]]\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Hindi film producers]]\n[[Category:Indian male singers]]\n[[Category:Bollywood playback singers]]\n[[Category:Indian television presenters]]\n[[Category:Indian male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Best Actor National Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Allahabad]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Bhushan in arts]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in arts]]\n[[Category:Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]\n[[Category:8th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Vibhushan in arts]]\n[[Category:Indian male film singers]]\n[[Category:People named in the Panama Papers]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi television]]\n[[Category:Indian male television actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Allahabad]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Allahabad]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Residents of New Alipore]]\n[[Category:Filmfare Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindus]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:Dadasaheb Phalke Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Actors from Mumbai]]\n", "name_user": "Fylindfotberserk", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amitabh_Bachchan"}
{"title_page": "Gopakapattana", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Cleanup reorganize|date=June 2016}}\n'''Gopakapattana''' or '''Gopakpatna''' (also known as {{IAST|Gov\u0101pur\u012b}}, {{IAST|Gopakapur\u012b}} in [[Sanskrit]], {{IAST|Goy}} in [[Konkani language|Konkani]], {{IAST|Gov\u0101}} in [[Marathi language|Marathi]], {{IAST|Gove}} in [[Kannada language|Kannada]]) was a prosperous ancient port city in the west coastal Indian state of [[Goa]], that served as capital under the reign of different Hindu dynasties extending from 100 BC to 1469 AD which ruled ancient Goa (which included Modern Goa and South Konkan).<ref name=gove>{{cite book|last=da Fonseca|first=Jos\u00e9 Nicolau|title=Historical and Archaeological Sketch of the City of Goa|year=1878|publisher=Asian Educational Services|isbn=978-81-206-0207-6|pages=348 pages}}</ref>{{rp|p.119}} <ref name=dyna>{{cite book|last=India. Study Team on Administration of Union Territories and NEFA., R. R. Morarka|title=Report, Volume 1|year=1972|publisher=Administrative Reforms Commission}}</ref>{{rp|p.171}}\n\nIn a certain Hindu scripture ''Suta Samhita'', Govapuri is associated with spiritually cleansing touch: ''...The very sight of Govapuri destroys any sin committed in former existence just as sunrise dispels darkness ...Certainly there is no other kshetra equal to Govapuri\n\nA similar hymn praising Govapuri city is found in [[Sahyadrikhanda]] of [[Skanda Purana]], which says the extent of Govapuri was about seven ''[[Yojana]]s''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Esteves|first=Sarto|title=Goa and its features|year=1966|publisher=Manaktalas|location=Mumbai}}</ref>{{rp|p.8}}\n{{cquote|\u0917\u094b\u0915\u0930\u094d\u0923\u093e\u0926\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0924\u0930\u0947 \u092d\u093e\u0917\u0947 \u0938\u092a\u094d\u0924\u092f\u094b\u091c\u0928\u0935\u093f\u0938\u094d\u0924\u0943\u0924\u0902 <br> \u0924\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0917\u094b\u0935\u093e\u092a\u0941\u0930\u0940 \u0928\u093e\u092e \u0928\u0917\u0930\u0940 \u092a\u093e\u092a\u0928\u093e\u0936\u093f\u0928\u0940 }}\nGopakapattana is today a sleepy blink-and-miss village of Tiswadi. Except for the stray wanderer who drives off the bustling National Highway 17 (66), the significance of this village and its history is all but lost.\n\nWhat may appear like just any other Goan roadside village, strewn across the paddy fields barely 10km from Panaji was, until the emergence of Ela or today's Old Goa, India's wealthiest city and busiest port on the southwest coast.\n\nGoa Velha literally means Old Goa. This is often the reason for the village being confused for the other historically rich village of Old Goa or Velha Goa which was then still nascent.\n\nGopakapattana is said to be built by Sanapulla, the founder of the south Konkan Silahara dynasty, who reigned from 765 AD. The Silaharas ruled from 765 AD to 1020 AD, when they were overthrown by the Kadambas.\n\nAccording to the famous historian Dr A S Altekar, Gopakapattana finds mention in the epic, Mahabharata. It was also known as Govapuri or Gove in the Ramayana, which adds that whoever casts a glance over the holy city of Govapuri gets his sins cleansed.\n\nAs the Kadamba dynasty prospered, they built a navy that was formidable. With Chandor being too small to accommodate his fleet of ships, Kadamba ruler Jayakeshi I moved to Goa Velha or Gopakapattana which had natural breakwaters, a safe cove and was open to the seas, historians recount.\n\nToday, all that remains of that historic city are the ruins of the laterite brick wall of the ancient port, the site of the Kadamba palace, the 8km-long royal passage known as Raj Bidd from Agasaim to Old Goa, and some centuries-old water tanks.\n\nA predominantly Catholic village, Goa Velha is marked by many crosses and chapels besides the striking church of St Andrew.\n\nThe village also holds a special significance for the Hindu brethren. Chamunda Devi is worshipped as the gramdevi or village goddess and this is seen in the number of stores that are named after the deity. While the main temple dedicated to Chamunda Devi is at Bicholim, a small idol of the goddess remains housed in the Zuwarkar family home for daily dharshan.\n\nOn Akshaya tritiya, the deity kept in the Zuwarkar household is put on an assembled palki (palanquin) and taken in a procession to the building of the Marathi school of the Chemunda Samaj in Goa Velha. It is followed by a three-day cultural programme.\n\nAmong the prominent families of the village are the Kenis, Zuwarkars and the Menezes\u2019. The few large and old houses scattered about in the village are reportedly owned by these families. The beautiful colonial-style architecture of the houses that belong to the Menezes family, specifically Solar-Menezes or Menezes Mansion, the main ancestral house of the family is very impressive.\n\nThe 350-year old home of the Zuwarkar's commands a note. It is said that the surname Zuwarkar originates from this village. Walk through the centuries-old wooden door frame on an evening and you maybe lucky to bump into the Zuwarkar cousins. Ask nicely and they will happily show you their family tree drawn on parched paper.\n\nToday, the vestiges of Goa Velha are fading away. Once famed for its sweet potatoes and saltpans, traditional trade is dying out. With 65% of its population, especially the younger generation, trading in their Indian passports for the sought-after Portuguese passport, the identity of the village is changing, says Dr Carmo Pegado.\n\nThe vacuum created by the migration to British shores is slowly being filled up by migrants from neighbouring states.\n\nIn the past, Goa Velha was famous for Ayurveda. In fact, one of the village wards, Zuari, comprised mostly experts in Ayurvedic medicines and the treatment of broken bones and hence they were known as Zuarioilo doctor. Not much is left of this trade today.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Kadambas of Goa]]\n*[[History of Goa]]\n*[[Saptakoteshwar]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of Goa]]\n[[Category:History of Goa]]\n[[Category:Kadambas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Cleanup reorganize|date=June 2016}}\n'''Gopakapattana''' or '''Gopakpatna''' (also known as {{IAST|Gov\u0101pur\u012b}}, {{IAST|Gopakapur\u012b}} in [[Sanskrit]], {{IAST|Goy}} in [[Konkani language|Konkani]], {{IAST|Gov\u0101}} in [[Marathi language|Marathi]], {{IAST|Gove}} in [[Kannada language|Kannada]]) was a prosperous ancient port city in the west coastal Indian state of [[Goa]], that served as capital under the reign of different Hindu dynasties extending from 100 BC to 1469 AD which ruled ancient Goa (which included Modern Goa and South Konkan).<ref name=gove>{{cite book|last=da Fonseca|first=Jos\u00e9 Nicolau|title=Historical and Archaeological Sketch of the City of Goa|year=1878|publisher=Asian Educational Services|isbn=978-81-206-0207-6|pages=348 pages}}</ref>{{rp|p.119}} <ref name=dyna>{{cite book|last=India. Study Team on Administration of Union Territories and NEFA., R. R. Morarka|title=Report, Volume 1|year=1972|publisher=Administrative Reforms Commission}}</ref>{{rp|p.171}}\n\nIn a certain Hindu scripture ''Suta Samhita'', Govapuri is associated with spiritually cleansing touch: ''...The very sight of Govapuri destroys any sin committed in former existence just as sunrise dispels darkness ...Certainly there is no other kshetra equal to Govapuri\n\nA similar hymn praising Govapuri city is found in [[Sahyadrikhanda]] of [[Skanda Purana]], which says the extent of Govapuri was about seven ''[[Yojana]]s''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Esteves|first=Sarto|title=Goa and its features|year=1966|publisher=Manaktalas|location=Mumbai}}</ref>{{rp|p.8}}\n{{cquote|\u0917\u094b\u0915\u0930\u094d\u0923\u093e\u0926\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0924\u0930\u0947 \u092d\u093e\u0917\u0947 \u0938\u092a\u094d\u0924\u092f\u094b\u091c\u0928\u0935\u093f\u0938\u094d\u0924\u0943\u0924\u0902 <br> \u0924\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0917\u094b\u0935\u093e\u092a\u0941\u0930\u0940 \u0928\u093e\u092e \u0928\u0917\u0930\u0940 \u092a\u093e\u092a\u0928\u093e\u0936\u093f\u0928\u0940 }}\nGopakapattana is today a sleepy blink-and-miss village of Tiswadi. Except for the stray wanderer who drives off the bustling National Highway 17 (66), the significance of this village and its history is all but lost.\n\nWhat may appear like just any other Goan roadside village, strewn across the paddy fields barely 10km from Panaji was, until the emergence of Ela or today's Old Goa, India's wealthiest city and busiest port on the southwest coast.\n\nGoa Velha literally means Old Goa. This is often the reason for the village being confused for the other historically rich village of Old Goa or Velha Goa which was then still nascent.\n\nGopakapattana is said to be built by Sanapulla, the founder of the south Konkan Silahara dynasty, who reigned from 765 AD. The Silaharas ruled from 765 AD to 1020 AD, when they were overthrown by the Kadambas.\n\nAccording to the famous historian Dr A S Altekar, Gopakapattana finds mention in the epic, Mahabharata. It was also known as Govapuri or Gove in the Ramayana, which adds that whoever casts a glance over the holy city of Govapuri gets his sins cleansed.\n\nAs the Kadamba dynasty prospered, they built a navy that was formidable. With Chandor being too small to accommodate his fleet of ships, Kadamba ruler Jayakeshi I moved to Goa Velha or Gopakapattana which had natural breakwaters, a safe cove and was open to the seas, historians recount.\n\nToday, all that remains of that historic city are the ruins of the laterite brick wall of the ancient port, the site of the Kadamba palace, the 8km-long royal passage known as Raj Bidd from Agasaim to Old Goa, and some centuries-old water tanks.\n\nA predominantly Catholic village, Goa Velha is marked by many crosses and chapels besides the striking church of St Andrew.\n\nThe village also holds a special significance for the Hindu brethren. Chamunda Devi is worshipped as the gramdevi or village goddess and this is seen in the number of stores that are named after the deity. While the main temple dedicated to Chamunda Devi is at Bicholim, a small idol of the goddess remains housed in the Zuwarkar family home for daily dharshan.\n\nOn Akshaya tritiya, the deity kept in the Zuwarkar household is put on an assembled palki (palanquin) and taken in a procession to the building of the Marathi school of the Chemunda Samaj in Goa Velha. It is followed by a three-day cultural programme.\n\nAmong the prominent families of the village are the Kenis, Zuwarkars and the Menezes\u2019. The few large and old houses scattered about in the village are reportedly owned by these families. The beautiful colonial-style architecture of the houses that belong to the Menezes family, specifically Solar-Menezes or Menezes Mansion, the main ancestral house of the family is very impressive.\n\nThe 350-year old home of the Zuwarkar's commands a note. It is said that the surname Zuwarkar originates from this village. Walk through the centuries-old wooden door frame on an evening and you maybe lucky to bump into the Zuwarkar cousins. Ask nicely and they will happily show you their family tree drawn on parched paper.\n\nToday, the vestiges of Goa Velha are fading away. Once famed for its sweet potatoes and saltpans, traditional trade is dying out. With 65% of its population, especially the younger generation, trading in their Indian passports for the sought-after Portuguese passport, the identity of the village is changing, says Dr Carmo Pegado.\n\nThe vacuum created by the migration to British shores is slowly being filled up by migrants from neighbouring states.\n\nIn the past, Goa Velha was famous for Ayurveda. In fact, one of the village wards, Zuari, comprised mostly experts in Ayurvedic medicines and the treatment of broken bones and hence they were known as Zuarioilo dotor. Not much is left of this trade today.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Kadambas of Goa]]\n*[[History of Goa]]\n*[[Saptakoteshwar]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of Goa]]\n[[Category:History of Goa]]\n[[Category:Kadambas]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: dotor\u2192doctor", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gopakapattana"}
{"title_page": "List of First Nations peoples", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Indigenous Peoples of Canada}}\nThe following is a partial '''list of First Nations peoples''' of [[Canada]], organized by linguistic-cultural area. It only includes [[First Nations]] people, which by definition excludes \u2018\u2019\u2019[[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)|Metis]]\u2019\u2019\u2019 and Canadian [[Inuit]] groups. The areas used here are in accordance to those developed by the ethnologist and linguist [[Edward Sapir]], and used by the [[Canadian Museum of Civilization]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://www.historymuseum.ca/cmc/exhibitions/tresors/ethno/etb0101e.html\n| title = Canadian Museum of Civilization: Gateway to Aboriginal Heritage\n| accessdate = 2019-01-29\n}}</ref>\n\n==Northwest Coast==\nThese people traditionally eat fish, primarily [[salmon]] and [[eulachon]] from the ocean, as well as fish from lakes and rivers, and roots and berries. Recently discovered [[clam garden]]s suggest that they were not limited only to hunting and gathering. They made use of the forests of the Pacific to build dug-out [[canoe]]s, and houses made of evenly split planks of wood. They used tools made of stone and wood. The native peoples of the Pacific coast also made [[totem pole]]s, a trait attributed to other tribes as well.  In 2000 a [[Aboriginal land claims|land claim]] was settled between the [[Nisga'a]] people of [[British Columbia]] and the provincial government, resulting in the transfer of over 2,000 square kilometres of land to the Nisga'a. Major ethnicities include the:\n*[[Coast Salish peoples]]\n**[[Nuxalk Nation|Nux\u00e1lk]] (''Bella Coola''; not linguistically Coast Salish)\n***[[Kimsquit]]\n***[[Tallheo]]\n***[[Stuie]]\n***[[Kwatna]]\n**[[Shishalh]] ([[Sechelt]])\n**[[Squamish people|Squamish]]\n**[[Pentlatch language|Pentlatch]] (a.k.a. Puntledge, extinct)\n**[[Qualicum First Nation|Qualicum]]\n**Comox-speaking:\n**[[K'omoks]] (Kwak'wala speaking today)\n**[[Sliammon]] \n**[[Homalco]]\n**[[Klahoose First Nation|Klahoose]]\n**[[Halkomelem|Halkomelem-speaking]]\n***Hulqiminum (Island Halkomelem):\n****[[Snuneymuxw]] (Nanaimo)\n****[[Cowichan peoples|Cowichan]]\n*****[[Somena]] (S\u2019amuna\u2019)\n*****[[Quw'utsun]]\n*****[[Quamichan]]\n*****[[Clemclemaluts]] (L\u2019uml\u2019umuluts)\n*****[[Comiaken people|Comiaken]] (Qwum\u2019yiqun\u2019)\n*****[[Khenipsen]] (Hinupsum)\n*****[[Kilpahlas]] (Tl\u2019ulpalus)\n*****[[Koksilah people|Koksilah]] (Hwulqwselu)\n***[[Penelakut]]\n***[[Hwlitsum]] (Lamalcha or Lamalchi)\n***Hunquminum (Downriver Halkomelem)\n****[[Musqueam]]\n****[[Tsleil-Waututh First Nation|Tsleil-Waututh]] (Burrard)\n****[[Katzie]]\n****[[Kwantlen First Nation|Kwantlen]]\n****[[Kwikwetlem]] (Coquitlam)\n****[[Snokomish]] (extinct)\n****[[Tsawwassen]]\n****Halqemeylem (Upriver Halkomelem)\n***[[Sts'Ailes]] (Chehalis)\n***[[Sto:lo]] (Fraser River Salish)\n****[[Aitchelitz First Nation|Aitchelitz]]\n****[[Leq' a: mel First Nation|Leq' a: mel]]\n****[[Matsqui First Nation|Matsqui]]\n****[[Popkum First Nation|Popkum]]\n****[[Skway First Nation|Skway]]\n****[[Skawahlook First Nation|Skawahlook]]\n****[[Skowkale First Nation|Skowkale]]\n****[[Squiala First Nation|Squiala]]\n****[[Sumas First Nation|Sumas]]\n****[[Tzeachten First Nation|Tzeachten]]\n****[[Yakweakwioose First Nation|Yakweakwioose]]\n****[[Chawathil First Nation|Chawathil]]\n****[[Cheam Indian Band|Cheam]]\n****[[Kwaw-kwaw-Apilt First Nation|Kwaw-kwaw-Apilt]]\n****[[Scowlitz First Nation|Scowlitz]] (Scaulits)\n****[[Seabird Island First Nation|Seabird Island]]\n****[[Shxw'ow'hamel First Nation|Shxw'ow'hamel]]\n****[[Soowahlie First Nation|Soowahlie]]\n**[[North Straits Salish|North Straits Salish-speaking]]\n***[[Songhees]] (a.k.a. ''Songish'', a.k.a. ''Lekwungen'')\n***[[T'Souke]] ([[Sooke]])\n***[[Semiahmoo people|Semiahmoo]]\n***[[Malahat First Nation|Malahat]]<!--Halkomelem?-->\n***[[Lummi]]\n***[[Klallam]]\n***[[Tsartlip]]\n***[[Tsawout First Nation|Tsawout]]\n***[[Tseycum]]\n***[[Pauquachin]]\n***[[Esquimalt]]\n*[[New Westminster First Nation|New Westminster]] (no language affiliation)\n*[[Tsimshianic languages|Tsimshianic peoples]] (Northern Mainland)\n**[[Tsimshian]] (Sm'algyax speaking)\n**[[Gitxsan]] (Gitxsanimaax speaking)\n**[[Nisga'a]]\n*[[Haida people|Haida]] (Haad kil speaking)\n*Southern Wakashan peoples\n**[[Nuu-chah-nulth people|Nuu-chah-nulth]] (incorrectly called ''Nootka'')\n***[[Tla-o-qui-aht]] (''Clayoquot'')\n***[[Mowachaht]]-[[Mowachaht/Muchalaht First Nations|Muchalaht]]\n***[[Ahousaht First Nation|Ahousaht]] (formed from the merger of the Ahousaht and [[Kelsemeht]] bands in 1951)\n***[[Ehattesaht First Nation|Ehattesaht]]\n***[[Hesquiaht First Nation|Hesquiaht]]\n***[[Kyuquot/Cheklesahht First Nation|Cheklesahht]]\n***[[Kyuquot/Cheklesahht First Nation|Kyuquot]]\n***[[Nuchatlaht First Nation|Nuchatlaht]]\n***[[Huu-ay-aht First Nation|Huu-ay-aht]] (formerly Ohiaht)\n***[[Hupacasath First Nation|Hupacasath]] (formerly Opetchesaht)\n***[[Toquaht First Nation|Toquaht]]\n***[[Tseshaht First Nation|Tseshaht]]\n***[[Uchucklesaht First Nation|Uchucklesaht]]\n***[[Ucluelet First Nation|Yuu\u0142u\u0294i\u0142\u0294at\u1e25]] (Ucluelet)\n**[[Ditidaht]]\n**[[Pacheedaht]]\n*Northern Wakashan peoples (Central Coast)\n**[[Kwakwaka'wakw]]\n***[[Laich-kwil-tach]] (Euclataws/Yuculta a.k.a. Southern Kwakiutl)\n****[[Weewaikai]] ([[Cape Mudge]])\n****[[Wewaykum]] ([[Campbell River, British Columbia|Campbell River]])\n****[[Kwiakah]]\n***[[Koskimo]]\n***[['Namgis]] (Nimpkish)\n**[[Haisla people|Haisla]] ([[Kitimaat Village|Kitamaat]])\n***[[Henaksiala]]\n**[[Heiltsuk people|Heiltsuk]] ([[Bella Bella, British Columbia|Bella Bella]], at the community of the same name)\n**[[Wuikinuxv]] (Owekeeno)\n*[[Tsetsaut]] (extinct Athapaskan-speakers)\n\n==British Columbia Interior==\n*[[Tlingit people|Inland Tlingit]]\n**[[Taku River Tlingit First Nation|\u00c1a Tlein Kw\u00e1an (Atlin people)]]\n**[[Teslin Tlingit Council|Deisleen Kw\u00e1an (Teslin people)]]\n*[[Athabascan]]\n**[[Dakelh]] (Carrier)\n***[[Wet'suwet'en]]\n***[[Lheidli T'enneh]]\n**[[Dene-thah]] ([[Slavey people|Slavey]])\n**[[Tsilhqot'in]] ([[Tsilhqot'in|Chilcotin]])\n**[[Sekani]]\n**[[Dunne-Za]] (Beaver)\n**[[Nicola Athapaskans]] (extinct)\n**[[Tahltan]]\n**[[Kaska Dena]]\n*[[Interior Salish]]\n**[[Nlaka'pamux]] (Thompson people)\n**[[Okanagan people|Okanagan]]\n**[[Secwepemc]] ([[Secwepemc|Shuswap]])\n***[[Simpcw North Thompson Indian Band|Simpcw]]\n**[[Sinixt]] ([[Lake]]s)\n**[[St'at'imc]] people ([[St'at'imc|Lillooet]]) people\n***[[Lil'wat]]\n***Lower Stl'atl'imx (Skatin, Semahquam, Xa'xtsa)\n***[[Nequatque]]\n*[[Kootenai (tribe)|Ktunaxa]] (''Kootenay'')\n\n==Plains==\n{{Main|Plains Indians}}\nThese people traditionally used [[tipi]]s covered with skins as their homes. Their main sustenance was the [[American bison|bison]], which they used as food, as well as for all their garments. The leaders of some Plains tribes wore large headdresses made of feathers, something which is wrongfully attributed by some to all First Nations peoples.  Major ethnicities include the:\n* [[Anishinaabe]]\n** [[Plains-Ojibwa]]\n* [[Blackfoot Confederacy|Blackfoot]]\n** [[Kainai]] (''Blood'')\n** [[North Peigan]]\n** [[Siksika]]\n* [[Dene]]\n** [[Chipewyan]]\n* [[Nakoda (Stoney)|Nakoda]]\n** [[Assiniboine people|Assiniboine]]\n** Stoney\n* [[Plains-Cree]]\n* [[Tasttine]] (''Beaver'')\n* [[Tsuut'ina]] (''Sarcee'')\n\n==Plateau==\n* [[Ktunaxa]] \n* [[Okanagan]]\n* [[Sinixt]]\n* [[St'at'imc]] (Lillooet)\n* [[Nicola people|Nicola]]\n* [[Nlaka'pamux]] (Thompson)\n* [[Secwepemc]] (Shuswap)\n\n==Western subarctic==\nThese peoples live in the [[boreal forest]] in what are now Canada's western provinces and territories. They were originally hunter-gatherers dependent on [[caribou]], [[moose]] and the [[fur trade]]. Most spoke [[Athapaskan languages]] except the Crees and Inland Tlingit. Major ethnicities in the [[Yukon]], [[Northwest Territories]] and the northern parts of the western provinces ([[British Columbia]], [[Alberta]], [[Saskatchewan]] and [[Manitoba]]) include the following:\n*[[Cree]]\n*[[Dene]]\n**[[Chipewyan]]\n**[[Sahtu]] (includes Bearlake, Hare and Mountain peoples)\n**[[Slavey people|Slavey]]\n**[[Tli Cho]]\n**[[Yellowknives]]\n*[[Dunneza]] (also Dunne-za, Beaver, Tasttine)\n*[[Gwich'in people|Gwich'in]] (Kutchin, Loucheaux)\n*[[H\u00e4n people|H\u00e4n]]\n*[[Kaska]]\n*[[Tagish]]\n*[[Tahltan]]\n*Inland [[Tlingit people|Tlingit]]\n*[[Southern Tutchone|Southern]] and [[Northern Tutchone]]\n\n==Woodlands and eastern subarctic==\n{{Further|Indigenous peoples of the Northeastern Eastern Woodlands|Indigenous peoples of the Subarctic}}\n\nMajor ethnicities include the:\n*[[Anishinaabe]]\n**[[Algonquin people|Algonquin]]\n**[[Nipissing First Nation|Nipissing]]\n**[[Ojibwa]]\n***[[Mississaugas]]\n***[[Saulteaux]]\n**[[Oji-cree]]\n**[[Ottawa (tribe)|Ottawa]] (''Odawa'')\n**[[Potawatomi]]\n*[[Cree]]\n*[[Innu]]\n*[[Naskapi]]\n===Atlantic coastal region===\n*[[Beothuk]] (Newfoundland ''extinct'')\n*[[Innu]] (Labrador)\n*[[Maliseet]]\n*[[Mi'kmaq people|Mi'kmaq]] (Micmac)\n*[[Passamaquoddy]]\n*[[Hydin]]\n\n===St. Lawrence River Valley===\nThe largest First Nations group near the St. Lawrence waterway are the [[Iroquois]]. This area also includes the [[Wyandot people|Wyandot]] (formerly referred to as the Huron) peoples of central [[Ontario]], and the [[Iroquois|League of Five Nations]] who had lived in the [[United States]], south of [[Lake Ontario]].  Major ethnicities include the:\n*[[Anishinaabe]]\n**[[Algonquin people|Algonquin]]\n**[[Nipissing First Nation|Nipissing]]\n*[[Haudenosaunee]] (''Iroquois'')\n**[[Cayuga tribe|Cayuga]] (''Guyohkohnyo'')\n**[[Mohawk nation|Mohawk]] (''Kanien'k\u00e9haka'')\n**[[Oneida tribe|Oneida]] (''Onayotekaono'')\n**[[Onondaga (tribe)|Onondaga]] (''Onundagaono'')\n**[[Seneca tribe|Seneca]] (''Onondowahgah'')\n**[[Tuscarora (tribe)|Tuscarora]] (''Ska-Ruh-Reh'')\n*Munsee branch of the [[Lenape]] (Delawares)\n*[[Neutral Nation|Neutral]]\n*[[Tobacco (First Nation)|Tobacco]]\n*[[Wyandot people|Wyandot]] (''Huron'')\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Canada}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Classification of indigenous peoples of the Americas]]\n*[[Indigenous languages of the Americas]]\n*[[List of Canadian Inuit]]\n*[[List of First Nations governments]]\n*[[List of Indian reserves in Canada]]\n*[[List of Indian reserves in Canada by population]]\n*[[List of place names in Canada of Aboriginal origin]]\n*[[Notable Aboriginal people of Canada]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n{{People of Canada}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of First Nations Peoples}}\n[[Category:First Nations]]\n[[Category:Indigenous peoples in Canada-related lists|First Nations peoples]]\n[[Category:Lists of indigenous peoples of the Americas|First Nations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Indigenous Peoples of Canada}}\nThe following is a partial '''list of First Nations peoples''' of [[Canada]], organized by linguistic-cultural area. It only includes [[First Nations]] people, which by definition excludes [[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)|Metis]] and Canadian [[Inuit]] groups. The areas used here are in accordance to those developed by the ethnologist and linguist [[Edward Sapir]], and used by the [[Canadian Museum of Civilization]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url = https://www.historymuseum.ca/cmc/exhibitions/tresors/ethno/etb0101e.html\n| title = Canadian Museum of Civilization: Gateway to Aboriginal Heritage\n| accessdate = 2019-01-29\n}}</ref>\n\n==Northwest Coast==\nThese people traditionally eat fish, primarily [[salmon]] and [[eulachon]] from the ocean, as well as fish from lakes and rivers, and roots and berries. Recently discovered [[clam garden]]s suggest that they were not limited only to hunting and gathering. They made use of the forests of the Pacific to build dug-out [[canoe]]s, and houses made of evenly split planks of wood. They used tools made of stone and wood. The native peoples of the Pacific coast also made [[totem pole]]s, a trait attributed to other tribes as well.  In 2000 a [[Aboriginal land claims|land claim]] was settled between the [[Nisga'a]] people of [[British Columbia]] and the provincial government, resulting in the transfer of over 2,000 square kilometres of land to the Nisga'a. Major ethnicities include the:\n*[[Coast Salish peoples]]\n**[[Nuxalk Nation|Nux\u00e1lk]] (''Bella Coola''; not linguistically Coast Salish)\n***[[Kimsquit]]\n***[[Tallheo]]\n***[[Stuie]]\n***[[Kwatna]]\n**[[Shishalh]] ([[Sechelt]])\n**[[Squamish people|Squamish]]\n**[[Pentlatch language|Pentlatch]] (a.k.a. Puntledge, extinct)\n**[[Qualicum First Nation|Qualicum]]\n**Comox-speaking:\n**[[K'omoks]] (Kwak'wala speaking today)\n**[[Sliammon]] \n**[[Homalco]]\n**[[Klahoose First Nation|Klahoose]]\n**[[Halkomelem|Halkomelem-speaking]]\n***Hulqiminum (Island Halkomelem):\n****[[Snuneymuxw]] (Nanaimo)\n****[[Cowichan peoples|Cowichan]]\n*****[[Somena]] (S\u2019amuna\u2019)\n*****[[Quw'utsun]]\n*****[[Quamichan]]\n*****[[Clemclemaluts]] (L\u2019uml\u2019umuluts)\n*****[[Comiaken people|Comiaken]] (Qwum\u2019yiqun\u2019)\n*****[[Khenipsen]] (Hinupsum)\n*****[[Kilpahlas]] (Tl\u2019ulpalus)\n*****[[Koksilah people|Koksilah]] (Hwulqwselu)\n***[[Penelakut]]\n***[[Hwlitsum]] (Lamalcha or Lamalchi)\n***Hunquminum (Downriver Halkomelem)\n****[[Musqueam]]\n****[[Tsleil-Waututh First Nation|Tsleil-Waututh]] (Burrard)\n****[[Katzie]]\n****[[Kwantlen First Nation|Kwantlen]]\n****[[Kwikwetlem]] (Coquitlam)\n****[[Snokomish]] (extinct)\n****[[Tsawwassen]]\n****Halqemeylem (Upriver Halkomelem)\n***[[Sts'Ailes]] (Chehalis)\n***[[Sto:lo]] (Fraser River Salish)\n****[[Aitchelitz First Nation|Aitchelitz]]\n****[[Leq' a: mel First Nation|Leq' a: mel]]\n****[[Matsqui First Nation|Matsqui]]\n****[[Popkum First Nation|Popkum]]\n****[[Skway First Nation|Skway]]\n****[[Skawahlook First Nation|Skawahlook]]\n****[[Skowkale First Nation|Skowkale]]\n****[[Squiala First Nation|Squiala]]\n****[[Sumas First Nation|Sumas]]\n****[[Tzeachten First Nation|Tzeachten]]\n****[[Yakweakwioose First Nation|Yakweakwioose]]\n****[[Chawathil First Nation|Chawathil]]\n****[[Cheam Indian Band|Cheam]]\n****[[Kwaw-kwaw-Apilt First Nation|Kwaw-kwaw-Apilt]]\n****[[Scowlitz First Nation|Scowlitz]] (Scaulits)\n****[[Seabird Island First Nation|Seabird Island]]\n****[[Shxw'ow'hamel First Nation|Shxw'ow'hamel]]\n****[[Soowahlie First Nation|Soowahlie]]\n**[[North Straits Salish|North Straits Salish-speaking]]\n***[[Songhees]] (a.k.a. ''Songish'', a.k.a. ''Lekwungen'')\n***[[T'Souke]] ([[Sooke]])\n***[[Semiahmoo people|Semiahmoo]]\n***[[Malahat First Nation|Malahat]]<!--Halkomelem?-->\n***[[Lummi]]\n***[[Klallam]]\n***[[Tsartlip]]\n***[[Tsawout First Nation|Tsawout]]\n***[[Tseycum]]\n***[[Pauquachin]]\n***[[Esquimalt]]\n*[[New Westminster First Nation|New Westminster]] (no language affiliation)\n*[[Tsimshianic languages|Tsimshianic peoples]] (Northern Mainland)\n**[[Tsimshian]] (Sm'algyax speaking)\n**[[Gitxsan]] (Gitxsanimaax speaking)\n**[[Nisga'a]]\n*[[Haida people|Haida]] (Haad kil speaking)\n*Southern Wakashan peoples\n**[[Nuu-chah-nulth people|Nuu-chah-nulth]] (incorrectly called ''Nootka'')\n***[[Tla-o-qui-aht]] (''Clayoquot'')\n***[[Mowachaht]]-[[Mowachaht/Muchalaht First Nations|Muchalaht]]\n***[[Ahousaht First Nation|Ahousaht]] (formed from the merger of the Ahousaht and [[Kelsemeht]] bands in 1951)\n***[[Ehattesaht First Nation|Ehattesaht]]\n***[[Hesquiaht First Nation|Hesquiaht]]\n***[[Kyuquot/Cheklesahht First Nation|Cheklesahht]]\n***[[Kyuquot/Cheklesahht First Nation|Kyuquot]]\n***[[Nuchatlaht First Nation|Nuchatlaht]]\n***[[Huu-ay-aht First Nation|Huu-ay-aht]] (formerly Ohiaht)\n***[[Hupacasath First Nation|Hupacasath]] (formerly Opetchesaht)\n***[[Toquaht First Nation|Toquaht]]\n***[[Tseshaht First Nation|Tseshaht]]\n***[[Uchucklesaht First Nation|Uchucklesaht]]\n***[[Ucluelet First Nation|Yuu\u0142u\u0294i\u0142\u0294at\u1e25]] (Ucluelet)\n**[[Ditidaht]]\n**[[Pacheedaht]]\n*Northern Wakashan peoples (Central Coast)\n**[[Kwakwaka'wakw]]\n***[[Laich-kwil-tach]] (Euclataws/Yuculta a.k.a. Southern Kwakiutl)\n****[[Weewaikai]] ([[Cape Mudge]])\n****[[Wewaykum]] ([[Campbell River, British Columbia|Campbell River]])\n****[[Kwiakah]]\n***[[Koskimo]]\n***[['Namgis]] (Nimpkish)\n**[[Haisla people|Haisla]] ([[Kitimaat Village|Kitamaat]])\n***[[Henaksiala]]\n**[[Heiltsuk people|Heiltsuk]] ([[Bella Bella, British Columbia|Bella Bella]], at the community of the same name)\n**[[Wuikinuxv]] (Owekeeno)\n*[[Tsetsaut]] (extinct Athapaskan-speakers)\n\n==British Columbia Interior==\n*[[Tlingit people|Inland Tlingit]]\n**[[Taku River Tlingit First Nation|\u00c1a Tlein Kw\u00e1an (Atlin people)]]\n**[[Teslin Tlingit Council|Deisleen Kw\u00e1an (Teslin people)]]\n*[[Athabascan]]\n**[[Dakelh]] (Carrier)\n***[[Wet'suwet'en]]\n***[[Lheidli T'enneh]]\n**[[Dene-thah]] ([[Slavey people|Slavey]])\n**[[Tsilhqot'in]] ([[Tsilhqot'in|Chilcotin]])\n**[[Sekani]]\n**[[Dunne-Za]] (Beaver)\n**[[Nicola Athapaskans]] (extinct)\n**[[Tahltan]]\n**[[Kaska Dena]]\n*[[Interior Salish]]\n**[[Nlaka'pamux]] (Thompson people)\n**[[Okanagan people|Okanagan]]\n**[[Secwepemc]] ([[Secwepemc|Shuswap]])\n***[[Simpcw North Thompson Indian Band|Simpcw]]\n**[[Sinixt]] ([[Lake]]s)\n**[[St'at'imc]] people ([[St'at'imc|Lillooet]]) people\n***[[Lil'wat]]\n***Lower Stl'atl'imx (Skatin, Semahquam, Xa'xtsa)\n***[[Nequatque]]\n*[[Kootenai (tribe)|Ktunaxa]] (''Kootenay'')\n\n==Plains==\n{{Main|Plains Indians}}\nThese people traditionally used [[tipi]]s covered with skins as their homes. Their main sustenance was the [[American bison|bison]], which they used as food, as well as for all their garments. The leaders of some Plains tribes wore large headdresses made of feathers, something which is wrongfully attributed by some to all First Nations peoples.  Major ethnicities include the:\n* [[Anishinaabe]]\n** [[Plains-Ojibwa]]\n* [[Blackfoot Confederacy|Blackfoot]]\n** [[Kainai]] (''Blood'')\n** [[North Peigan]]\n** [[Siksika]]\n* [[Dene]]\n** [[Chipewyan]]\n* [[Nakoda (Stoney)|Nakoda]]\n** [[Assiniboine people|Assiniboine]]\n** Stoney\n* [[Plains-Cree]]\n* [[Tasttine]] (''Beaver'')\n* [[Tsuut'ina]] (''Sarcee'')\n\n==Plateau==\n* [[Ktunaxa]] \n* [[Okanagan]]\n* [[Sinixt]]\n* [[St'at'imc]] (Lillooet)\n* [[Nicola people|Nicola]]\n* [[Nlaka'pamux]] (Thompson)\n* [[Secwepemc]] (Shuswap)\n\n==Western subarctic==\nThese peoples live in the [[boreal forest]] in what are now Canada's western provinces and territories. They were originally hunter-gatherers dependent on [[caribou]], [[moose]] and the [[fur trade]]. Most spoke [[Athapaskan languages]] except the Crees and Inland Tlingit. Major ethnicities in the [[Yukon]], [[Northwest Territories]] and the northern parts of the western provinces ([[British Columbia]], [[Alberta]], [[Saskatchewan]] and [[Manitoba]]) include the following:\n*[[Cree]]\n*[[Dene]]\n**[[Chipewyan]]\n**[[Sahtu]] (includes Bearlake, Hare and Mountain peoples)\n**[[Slavey people|Slavey]]\n**[[Tli Cho]]\n**[[Yellowknives]]\n*[[Dunneza]] (also Dunne-za, Beaver, Tasttine)\n*[[Gwich'in people|Gwich'in]] (Kutchin, Loucheaux)\n*[[H\u00e4n people|H\u00e4n]]\n*[[Kaska]]\n*[[Tagish]]\n*[[Tahltan]]\n*Inland [[Tlingit people|Tlingit]]\n*[[Southern Tutchone|Southern]] and [[Northern Tutchone]]\n\n==Woodlands and eastern subarctic==\n{{Further|Indigenous peoples of the Northeastern Eastern Woodlands|Indigenous peoples of the Subarctic}}\n\nMajor ethnicities include the:\n*[[Anishinaabe]]\n**[[Algonquin people|Algonquin]]\n**[[Nipissing First Nation|Nipissing]]\n**[[Ojibwa]]\n***[[Mississaugas]]\n***[[Saulteaux]]\n**[[Oji-cree]]\n**[[Ottawa (tribe)|Ottawa]] (''Odawa'')\n**[[Potawatomi]]\n*[[Cree]]\n*[[Innu]]\n*[[Naskapi]]\n===Atlantic coastal region===\n*[[Beothuk]] (Newfoundland ''extinct'')\n*[[Innu]] (Labrador)\n*[[Maliseet]]\n*[[Mi'kmaq people|Mi'kmaq]] (Micmac)\n*[[Passamaquoddy]]\n*[[Hydin]]\n\n===St. Lawrence River Valley===\nThe largest First Nations group near the St. Lawrence waterway are the [[Iroquois]]. This area also includes the [[Wyandot people|Wyandot]] (formerly referred to as the Huron) peoples of central [[Ontario]], and the [[Iroquois|League of Five Nations]] who had lived in the [[United States]], south of [[Lake Ontario]].  Major ethnicities include the:\n*[[Anishinaabe]]\n**[[Algonquin people|Algonquin]]\n**[[Nipissing First Nation|Nipissing]]\n*[[Haudenosaunee]] (''Iroquois'')\n**[[Cayuga tribe|Cayuga]] (''Guyohkohnyo'')\n**[[Mohawk nation|Mohawk]] (''Kanien'k\u00e9haka'')\n**[[Oneida tribe|Oneida]] (''Onayotekaono'')\n**[[Onondaga (tribe)|Onondaga]] (''Onundagaono'')\n**[[Seneca tribe|Seneca]] (''Onondowahgah'')\n**[[Tuscarora (tribe)|Tuscarora]] (''Ska-Ruh-Reh'')\n*Munsee branch of the [[Lenape]] (Delawares)\n*[[Neutral Nation|Neutral]]\n*[[Tobacco (First Nation)|Tobacco]]\n*[[Wyandot people|Wyandot]] (''Huron'')\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Canada}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Classification of indigenous peoples of the Americas]]\n*[[Indigenous languages of the Americas]]\n*[[List of Canadian Inuit]]\n*[[List of First Nations governments]]\n*[[List of Indian reserves in Canada]]\n*[[List of Indian reserves in Canada by population]]\n*[[List of place names in Canada of Aboriginal origin]]\n*[[Notable Aboriginal people of Canada]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n{{People of Canada}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of First Nations Peoples}}\n[[Category:First Nations]]\n[[Category:Indigenous peoples in Canada-related lists|First Nations peoples]]\n[[Category:Lists of indigenous peoples of the Americas|First Nations]]\n", "name_user": "156.34.94.63", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typing mistake.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_First_Nations_peoples"}
{"title_page": "2007 New England Patriots season", "text_new": "{{short description|48th season in franchise history; first 16-0 record in NFL, third Super Bowl loss}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox NFL team season\n| logo =\n| team = New England Patriots\n| year = 2007\n| record = 16\u20130\n| division_place = 1st [[American Football Conference East Division|AFC East]]\n| coach = [[Bill Belichick]]\n| general manager = [[Scott Pioli]]\n| owner = [[Robert Kraft]]\n| stadium = [[Gillette Stadium]]\n| playoffs = '''Won [[2007\u201308 NFL playoffs|Divisional Playoffs]]''' ([[2007 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jaguars]]) 31\u201320<br />'''Won [[2007\u201308 NFL playoffs|AFC Championship]]''' ([[2007 San Diego Chargers season|Chargers]]) 21\u201312<br />Lost [[Super Bowl XLII]] ([[2007 New York Giants season|Giants]]) 14\u201317\n| pro bowlers = QB [[Tom Brady]]<br />C [[Dan Koppen]]<br />T [[Matt Light]]<br />G [[Logan Mankins]]<br />WR [[Randy Moss]]<br />CB [[Asante Samuel]]<br />LB [[Mike Vrabel]]<br />DT [[Vince Wilfork]]\n| AP All-pros = QB [[Tom Brady]] ''<small>(1st team)</small>'' <br /> T [[Matt Light]] ''<small>(1st team)</small>'' <br /> WR [[Randy Moss]] ''<small>(1st team)</small>'' <br /> CB [[Asante Samuel]] ''<small>(1st team)</small>'' <br /> OLB [[Mike Vrabel]] ''<small>(1st team)</small>'' <br /> C [[Dan Koppen]] ''<small>(2nd team)</small>'' <br /> G [[Logan Mankins]] ''<small>(2nd team)</small>'' <br /> WR [[Wes Welker]] ''<small>(2nd team)</small>'' <br /> DT [[Vince Wilfork]] ''<small>(2nd team)</small>''\n| uniform = Image:AFCE-2007-Uniform-NE.png\n| shortnavlink = Patriots seasons\n}}\n\nThe '''2007 New England Patriots season''' was the franchise's 38th season in the [[National Football League]], the 48th overall and the 8th under [[List of New England Patriots head coaches|head coach]] [[Bill Belichick]]. The Patriots looked to improve on their 12\u20134 record from 2006 and win the [[AFC East]] for the sixth time in seven years.\n\nThe Patriots finished the 2007 regular season by winning all sixteen of their games. They became only the eighth team in NFL history to finish a regular season undefeated, and first to do so since the [[1972 Miami Dolphins season|1972 Miami Dolphins]], as well as only the fourth to finish undefeated and untied. The Patriots were also the first team with a perfect regular season since the NFL expanded its schedule to sixteen games in 1978. Thus, they broke the record for victories in a single regular season that had been shared by the [[1984 San Francisco 49ers season|1984 San Francisco 49ers]], the [[1985 Chicago Bears season|1985 Chicago Bears]], the [[1998 Minnesota Vikings season|1998 Minnesota Vikings]], and the [[2004 Pittsburgh Steelers season|2004 Pittsburgh Steelers]], and later tied by the [[2011 Green Bay Packers season|2011 Green Bay Packers]] and [[2015 Carolina Panthers season|2015 Carolina Panthers]], who each finished with a record of 15\u20131, and are one of the only teams before or since that had nearly went 16\u20130. Honorable mentions include the [[1998 Denver Broncos season|1998 Denver Broncos]] and the [[Indianapolis Colts]] in [[2005 Indianapolis Colts season|2005]] and [[2009 Indianapolis Colts season|2009]], all of whom had started 13\u20130 and finished 14\u20132 respectively. The 1984 49ers and 1985 Bears would win [[Super Bowl XIX]] and [[Super Bowl XX]] respectively, the 1998 Vikings and 2004 Steelers would lose their conference championship games, the 2011 Packers would lose their first playoff game, and the 2015 Panthers would lose [[Super Bowl 50]].\n\nIn [[Super Bowl XLII]], the [[2007 New York Giants season|New York Giants]] defeated the Patriots 17\u201314 in an upset. With the loss, the Patriots were not able to join the 1984 49ers and 1985 Bears as Super Bowl champions, failing to go 19\u20130 and claim their fourth Super Bowl victory. Despite this loss, the 2007 Patriots are still regarded as one of the greatest teams in NFL history. \n\n{{TOC limit|limit=2}}\n\n== Season Summary ==\nThe Patriots entered the offseason following a stunning loss to the [[Colts\u2013Patriots rivalry|rival]] [[Indianapolis Colts]] in the [[NFL playoffs, 2006\u201307|AFC Championship]] after blowing a 21\u20133 first half lead--although they did when 6 of their final 7 regular season games in 2006.  After having lost their two starting wide receivers in the previous offseason, the Patriots added [[Dont\u00e9 Stallworth]] in free agency and traded for [[Wes Welker]] from the [[Miami Dolphins]] and [[Randy Moss]] from the [[Oakland Raiders]] in the spring. Welker would tie for the NFL lead in receptions with [[T. J. Houshmandzadeh]] in 2007 while Moss would set an NFL regular season record with 23 touchdown catches (part of his 98 receptions). The season began with controversy, when Patriot head coach [[Bill Belichick]] and the Patriots organization were penalized by the NFL for their involvement in the videotaping of opponents\u2019 defensive signals from an unauthorized location in their Week 1 game against the [[New York Jets]]. This came to be referred to in the media as [[2007 National Football League videotaping controversy|\"Spygate\"]]. Early in the season, the Patriots won their first two games by identical scores of 38\u201314, and followed up the next game with a  score of 38\u20137. Despite the media scrutiny, the Patriots continued to gain momentum, winning mid-season games by scores such as 49\u201328, 52\u20137, and 56\u201310, as quarterback [[Tom Brady]] emphasized the team's desire to blow out and \u201ckill teams.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/articles/2007/11/21/dressed_for_success/?page=full|title=Dressed for success?|work=The Boston Globe|first=Mike|last=Reiss|date=November 21, 2007|accessdate=June 16, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023141103/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/articles/2007/11/21/dressed_for_success/?page=full|archivedate=October 23, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The Patriots set the record for most points in a season with 589, shattering the [[1998 Minnesota Vikings season|previous record]] by 33 points. The Patriots won 12 games in which they surpassed the 30-point mark, four games in which they surpassed the 40-point mark and two in which they surpassed the 50-point mark.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/tgl_finder.cgi?request=1&match=single&year_min=1970&year_max=2010&game_type=R&game_num_min=0&game_num_max=99&week_num_min=0&week_num_max=99&game_day_of_week=&game_location=&game_result=&overtime=&league_id=&team_id=&opp_id=&conference_game=&division_game=&tm_is_playoff=&opp_is_playoff=&tm_is_winning=&opp_is_winning=&tm_scored_first=&tm_led=&tm_trailed=&c1stat=points&c1comp=gt&c1val=&c2stat=&c2comp=gt&c2val=&c3stat=&c3comp=gt&c3val=&c4stat=&c4comp=gt&c4val=&order_by=points|title=Team Game Finder Query Results - Pro-Football-Reference.com|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911074223/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/tgl_finder.cgi?request=1&match=single&year_min=1970&year_max=2010&game_type=R&game_num_min=0&game_num_max=99&week_num_min=0&week_num_max=99&game_day_of_week=&game_location=&game_result=&overtime=&league_id=&team_id=&opp_id=&conference_game=&division_game=&tm_is_playoff=&opp_is_playoff=&tm_is_winning=&opp_is_winning=&tm_scored_first=&tm_led=&tm_trailed=&c1stat=points&c1comp=gt&c1val=&c2stat=&c2comp=gt&c2val=&c3stat=&c3comp=gt&c3val=&c4stat=&c4comp=gt&c4val=&order_by=points|archivedate=September 11, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Patriots clinched the AFC East after their eleventh game (in Week 12), when they crushed the Bills (who had won 5 of their last 6 and were 6-4 at the time) 52-10, the fourth time since the NFL introduced the 16-game schedule in [[1978 NFL season|1978]] that a team had clinched a division title by their eleventh game.{{efn|name=\"otherteams\"|The other teams to achieve this were [[1985 Chicago Bears season|the 1985 Chicago Bears]], [[1997 San Francisco 49ers season|the 1997 San Francisco 49ers]] and [[2004 Philadelphia Eagles season|the 2004 Philadelphia Eagles]].}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.projo.com/patriots/content/sp_fbn_patsside26a_11-26-07_3480HRP_v7.2a70e35.html |title=Pats tie earliest clinching of the AFC East |first=Shalise Manza |last=Young |work=[[The Providence Journal]] |date=November 26, 2007 |accessdate=November 26, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071128150356/http://www.projo.com/patriots/content/sp_fbn_patsside26a_11-26-07_3480HRP_v7.2a70e35.html%23 |archivedate=November 28, 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the [[2007 New England Patriots \u2013 New York Giants game|season finale]], the Patriots sought to finish the regular season with the first 16\u20130 record in NFL history, and did so successfully. In that game, Brady and Moss connected on two touchdown passes, with Moss setting his 23 catch record, breaking Pro Football Hall of Fame member Jerry Rice's 22 touchdown receptions and with Brady setting an NFL record with 50 touchdown passes on the season. It was the first undefeated regular season in the NFL since [[1972 Miami Dolphins season|the 1972 Miami Dolphins]] finished 14\u20130, with both the 1942 bears & 1948 browns also completing an undeafeated, untied, regular season (although the Browns completed it in the AAFL).<ref name=\"GiantsNotes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.patriots.com/games/index.cfm?ac=gamereportdetail&pid=29937&pcid=47 |title=Patriots at Giants: Game Notes |work=Patriots.com |date=December 29, 2007 |accessdate=December 30, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110519104816/http://www.patriots.com/games/index.cfm?ac=gamereportdetail&pid=29937&pcid=47 |archivedate=May 19, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref> Brady earned his first [[National Football League Most Valuable Player Award|NFL MVP]] award, while the Patriots\u2019 offense destroyed numerous NFL records, including those for  touchdowns (75), points scored (589) and point differential (+315)\n\nWith the #1 seed in the [[American Football Conference|AFC]] [[NFL playoffs, 2007\u201308|playoffs]], the Patriots first defeated [[2007 Jacksonville Jaguars season|the Jacksonville Jaguars]], 31\u201320, then [[2007 San Diego Chargers season|the San Diego Chargers]] 21\u201312, to advance to [[Super Bowl XLII]], their sixth in franchise history. According to the [[Elias Sports Bureau]], with this accomplishment, they became the first professional sports team since 1884 in any of the four major American sports (football, basketball, baseball, hockey) to win the first 18 games of their season.<ref name=\"ChargersNotes\">{{cite news |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/22758036/page/2/ |title=Pats back in Super Bowl after win over Chargers |agency=Associated Press |publisher=MSNBC |date=January 20, 2008 |accessdate=January 20, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130103215609/http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/22758036/page/2/ |archivedate=3 January 2013}}</ref> Facing the prospect of a perfect 19\u20130 season with a victory over the underdog [[New York Giants]], analysts saw the 2007 Patriots as being the greatest team in NFL history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/22362827/print/1/displaymode/1098/|title=19\u20130 would make Patriots best team ever|work=[[NBC Sports]] |first=Don|last=Pierson|date=December 29, 2007|accessdate=June 16, 2009 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120715235239/http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/22362827/print/1/displaymode/1098/|archivedate=15 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nDespite being the overwhelming favorites to win the game, the Patriots failed to protect a four-point lead on a Giants drive late in the fourth quarter. A [[Helmet Catch|dramatic pass]] from a scrambling [[Eli Manning]] combined with an acrobatic catch by wide receiver [[David Tyree]] put the Giants deep in Patriots territory, and a Manning touchdown pass to [[Plaxico Burress]] gave the Giants a lead with just 35 seconds left. The Patriots could not score again and came out on the losing end of what is considered one of the greatest upsets in sports history.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/football/giants/giant-upset-pats-familiar-ring-new-england-shocker-rams-article-1.343284 |title=Giant upset over Pats has familiar ring to New England\u2019s shocker over Rams |work=[[Daily News (New York)]] |first=Gary |last=Myers |date=January 27, 2008 |accessdate=June 16, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019213733/http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/football/giants/giant-upset-pats-familiar-ring-new-england-shocker-rams-article-1.343284 |archivedate=October 19, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/04/sports/football/04game.html?_r=2&pagewanted=print|title=Giants Stun Patriots in Super Bowl XLII|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|first=Judy|last=Battista|date=February 4, 2008|accessdate=June 16, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912012449/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/04/sports/football/04game.html?_r=2&pagewanted=print|archivedate=September 12, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  The Patriots ended the season at 18\u20131, becoming one of only three teams in NFL history to finish their season (including postseason) 18\u20131.<ref>The others were the [[Super Bowl XIX]] champion [[1984 San Francisco 49ers season|1984 San Francisco 49ers]] and the [[Super Bowl XX]] champion [[1985 Chicago Bears season|1985 Chicago Bears]].</ref> The NFL Network named the 2007 Patriots the #1 team on their list of \u201cTop 10 Teams That Didn't Win A Super Bowl.\u201d\n\n==Offseason==\n===Death of Marquise Hill===\nOn the evening of May 27, 2007, 24-year-old defensive end [[Marquise Hill]] and his friend, Ashley Blazio,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bostonherald.com/localRegional/view.bg?articleid=1004553 |title=Hero told friend: \"Be calm, Don\u2019t panic\" |date=June 3, 2007 |newspaper=Boston Herald |accessdate=December 6, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> fell off a [[jet ski]] in [[Lake Pontchartrain]], north of New Orleans. Neither of them wore [[personal flotation device|personal flotation]] or [[tracking device]]s. According to Hill's agent, who spoke with Blazio, Hill \u201cended up saving her life, keeping her calm until she could grab onto a buoy.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/articles/2007/05/29/patriot_hill_is_found_dead/ | title=Patriot Hill is found dead | date=May 29, 2007 | work=Boston Globe | first1=April | last1=Simpson | first2=Michael | last2=Levenson | accessdate=December 6, 2010  | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100817065140/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/articles/2007/05/29/patriot_hill_is_found_dead/ | archivedate=August 17, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Blazio was rescued and sent to [[Tulane Medical Center]]. [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]] units searched the area. Hill's body was found by the [[Louisiana]] [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service|Department of Wildlife and Fisheries]] around 2:15&nbsp;PM [[North American Central Time Zone|CDT]] on May 28.\n\nHill's funeral, paid for by the team,<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/10/sports/football/10hill.html |title=In Patriots\u2019 Season to Remember, a Teammate Is Not Forgotten |first=Karen |last=Crouse |work=The New York Times |date=January 10, 2008 |accessdate=January 10, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131220094330/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/10/sports/football/10hill.html| archivedate=December 20, 2013| url-status= live}}</ref> was attended by many members of the [[New England Patriots|Patriots]] team and staff, as well as by Hill's former coach [[Nick Saban]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/articles/2007/06/03/patriots_hill_is_eulogized_laid_to_rest/ |title=Patriots\u2019 Hill is eulogized, laid to rest |first=Christopher L. |last=Gasper |work=The Boston Globe |date=June 3, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070606082738/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/articles/2007/06/03/patriots_hill_is_eulogized_laid_to_rest/ |archivedate=June 6, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nFor the 2007 season, all members of the Patriots wore a black No.&nbsp;91 decal on the backs of their helmets.<ref name=\"NYT\" /> A friend of Hill's since high school, fellow Patriots defensive lineman [[Jarvis Green]] supported Hill's fianc\u00e9e Inell Benn and son Ma\u2019Shy financially following Hill's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jarvisgreen.com/commerce/inthenews/inthenews.asp?reqdate=11/10/2007&id_passed=62 |title=Green: needed fill-in |first=Christopher L. |last=Gasper |work=The Boston Globe |date=November 10, 2007 |accessdate=January 10, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223041408/http://www.jarvisgreen.com/commerce/inthenews/inthenews.asp?reqdate=11%2F10%2F2007&id_passed=62 |archivedate=December 23, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Green also wore Hill's old shoulder pads for the Patriots\u2019 October 14 game against the Cowboys, which Benn attended.<ref name=\"NYT\" />\n\n===Staff changes===\nUnlike previous offseasons, head coach [[Bill Belichick]]\u2019s 2007 coaching staff remained generally unchanged. [[Wide receivers]] coach [[Brian Daboll]] left to become the [[quarterbacks]] coach for [[2007 New York Jets season|the New York Jets]] and was replaced by Director of Pro Personnel [[Nick Caserio]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/02/new_wr_coach.html |title=New WR coach |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=February 19, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070404153726/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/02/new_wr_coach.html |archivedate=April 4, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Former [[Duke University]] [[offensive coordinator]] and quarterbacks coach [[Bill O'Brien (American football)|Bill O'Brien]] was also hired as an offensive assistant.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/02/obrien_hired.html |title=O'Brien hired |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=February 27, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725005140/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/02/obrien_hired.html |archivedate=July 25, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> A former [[special teams]] contributor for the Patriots, [[linebacker]] [[Don Davis (American football)|Don Davis]] retired and joined the coaching staff as an assistant strength and conditioning coach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.projo.com/patriots/content/sp_fbn_davis0201_02-01-08_148RK5P_v9.3560fc5.html |title=Don Davis offers strength in both of his Pats roles |work=The Providence Journal |first=Shalise Manza |last=Young |date=February 1, 2008 |accessdate=February 8, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081122095435/http://www.projo.com/patriots/content/sp_fbn_davis0201_02-01-08_148RK5P_v9.3560fc5.html |archivedate=November 22, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Offensive coaching assistant [[Mike Judge (American football)|Mike Judge]] also joined [[Harvard University]] as a wide receivers coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gocrimson.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=41068&SPID=3659&DB_OEM_ID=9000&ATCLID=920368&Q_SEASON=2007|title=Mike Judge biography|work=GoCrimson.com|accessdate=July 6, 2008}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n===Departures===\nFree agency saw the departure of two [[2006 New England Patriots season|2006]] starters for the Patriots: [[tight end]] [[Daniel Graham]] signed with [[2007 Denver Broncos season|the Denver Broncos]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/graham_to_denve.html |title=Graham to Denver |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=March 6, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070309154014/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/graham_to_denve.html |archivedate=March 9, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and [[linebacker]] [[Tully Banta-Cain]] signed with [[2007 San Francisco 49ers season|the San Francisco 49ers]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/tbc_to_sf_1.html |title=TBC to S.F. |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=March 6, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313003246/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/tbc_to_sf_1.html |archivedate=March 13, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> while [[running back]] [[Corey Dillon]], the Patriots\u2019 leading rusher in 2006, asked to be released; the Patriots released him on March 2.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/dillon_cap.html |title=Dillon & salary cap |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=March 2, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070305192628/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/dillon_cap.html |archivedate=March 5, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Safety (American football position)|Safety]] [[Tebucky Jones]] was also released early in the offseason.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/02/tebucky_release.html |title=Tebucky released |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=February 21, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070403154251/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/02/tebucky_release.html |archivedate=April 3, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Another departure came when [[punter (football position)|punter]] [[Todd Sauerbrun]] signed with the Denver Broncos. When Sauerbrun was signed by the Patriots in December 2006, he agreed to a [[right of first refusal]], meaning that the Patriots could match any offer by any other team made in the subsequent offseason. When the [[unrestricted free agent]] signing period came, the Broncos tendered Sauerbrun, and the Patriots exercised their right and matched the offer. However, the Broncos argued that the Patriots had not filed the proper documents required for that right, and ordered a hearing before an NFL [[special master]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/04/sauerbrun_updat_3.html |title=Sauerbrun update |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=April 18, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070630153824/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/04/sauerbrun_updat_3.html| archivedate= June 30, 2007 | url-status= dead}}</ref> The Broncos won this hearing and Sauerbrun was allowed to sign with the Broncos.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/04/sauerbrun_to_de.html |title=Sauerbrun to Denver |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=April 19, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022145010/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/04/sauerbrun_to_de.html |archivedate=October 22, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> After spending all of training camp with the team, veteran punter [[Josh Miller (American football)|Josh Miller]] was released on August 16.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/08/miller_cut.html |title=Miller cut |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=August 16, 2007 |accessdate=August 16, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121022145047/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/08/miller_cut.html| archivedate=October 22, 2012| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n===Arrivals===\nIn the first week of free agency, the Patriots traded their second- and seventh-round picks in the [[2007 NFL Draft]] to [[2007 Miami Dolphins season|the Miami Dolphins]] for wide receiver [[Wes Welker]]. A [[restricted free agent]], Welker signed a five-year contract with the Patriots to complete the trade.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/pats_acquire_we.html |title=Pats acquire Welker |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=March 5, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070308093752/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/pats_acquire_we.html |archivedate=March 8, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring the second day of the draft, the Patriots added yet another wide receiver, this time trading a fourth-round draft pick (which the Patriots acquired the day before from [[2007 San Francisco 49ers season|the San Francisco 49ers]] with the 49ers\u2019 2008 first-round pick in exchange for the Patriots\u2019 original 2007 first-round pick) to [[2007 Oakland Raiders season|the Oakland Raiders]] for [[Randy Moss]], who agreed to take a pay cut of over US$6&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/04/trade_confirmed.html |title=Trade confirmed |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=April 29, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070602005758/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/04/trade_confirmed.html| archivedate= June 2, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/04/moss_contract.html |title=Moss contract |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=April 29, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070601032855/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/04/moss_contract.html| archivedate= June 1, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe offseason also brought the arrival of seven unrestricted free agents to the Patriots. On offense, the Patriots added running back [[Sammy Morris]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/morris_agrees.html |title=Morris agrees |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=March 3, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313225728/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/morris_agrees.html |archivedate=March 13, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[tight end]] [[Kyle Brady]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/kyle_brady_upda.html |title=Kyle Brady update |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=March 3, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070305161607/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/kyle_brady_upda.html |archivedate=March 5, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> as well as wide receivers [[Dont\u00e9 Stallworth]] and [[Kelley Washington]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/wr_deals.html |title=WR deals |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=March 21, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022145127/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/wr_deals.html |archivedate=October 22, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On defense, they added [[Pro Bowl]] linebacker [[Adalius Thomas]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/thomas_in_fold.html |title=Thomas in fold |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=March 3, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070305162959/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/thomas_in_fold.html |archivedate=March 5, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and [[cornerback]]s [[Tory James]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/04/james_signing.html |title=James signing |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=April 24, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022145140/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/04/james_signing.html |archivedate=October 22, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and [[Eddie Jackson (American football)|Eddie Jackson]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/jacksons_deal.html |title=Jackson\u2019s deal |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=March 21, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021140003/http://boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/jacksons_deal.html |archivedate=October 21, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:2007NEPTC.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Randy Moss]] lined up with the offense during the first training camp practice]]\nFree agents or potential free agents [[Heath Evans]], [[Billy Yates (American football)|Billy Yates]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/pats_moves_8.html |title=Pats moves |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=March 2, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070312164621/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/pats_moves_8.html |archivedate=March 12, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Larry Izzo]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/izzos_deal.html |title=Izzo\u2019s deal |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=March 8, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070314234631/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/izzos_deal.html |archivedate=March 14, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Rashad Baker]], [[Gene Mruczkowski]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/contract_follow.html |title=Contract follow-up |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=March 23, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022145342/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/03/contract_follow.html |archivedate=October 22, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Junior Seau]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/05/seau_followup.html |title=Seau follow-up |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=May 22, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070701112712/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/05/seau_followup.html| archivedate= July 1, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[Randall Gay]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/05/gay_update_1.html |title=Gay update |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=May 24, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070527100253/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/05/gay_update_1.html| archivedate= May 27, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[Troy Brown]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://patriots.bostonherald.com/patriots/view.bg?articleid=1010548 |title=Troy\u2019s back with Pats |work=[[Boston Herald]] |first=John |last=Tomase |date=July 10, 2007 |accessdate=July 10, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070712150034/http://patriots.bostonherald.com/patriots/view.bg?articleid=1010548 |archivedate=July 12, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and [[Vinny Testaverde]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/08/hawkins_release.html |title=Hawkins released |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=August 18, 2007 |accessdate=August 27, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022145453/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/08/hawkins_release.html |archivedate=October 22, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> were all re-signed. Defensive end [[Ty Warren]] also received a long-term contract extension.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/08/warren_revisite.html|title=Warren revisited|work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces|first=Mike|last=Reiss|date=August 21, 2007|accessdate=March 2, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022194624/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/08/warren_revisite.html|archivedate=October 22, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Patriots used their non-exclusive [[franchise tag]] on cornerback [[Asante Samuel]];<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/02/samuel_tagged.html |title=Samuel tagged |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=February 16, 2007 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070402004702/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/02/samuel_tagged.html |archivedate=April 2, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Samuel signed it on August 28, with the stipulation that the team would not use it again on him when he became a free agent again after the season,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/08/samuel_in_house.html |title=Samuel in house |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=August 27, 2007 |accessdate=August 27, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022145542/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/08/samuel_in_house.html |archivedate=October 22, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> after the two sides failed to reach a long-term contract agreement with the team by the July 16 deadline.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/07/more_samuel.html|title=More Samuel|work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces|first=Mike|last=Reiss|date=July 16, 2007|accessdate=February 28, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071008235335/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/07/more_samuel.html|archivedate=October 8, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring the preseason, on August 7, the Patriots traded an undisclosed pick in the [[2008 NFL Draft]] to [[2007 Chicago Bears season|the Chicago Bears]] for cornerback [[Dante Wesley]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/08/trade_confirmed_1.html |title=Trade confirmed |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=August 7, 2007 |accessdate=August 26, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022154040/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/08/trade_confirmed_1.html |archivedate=October 22, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> but since Wesley was cut, the Bears did not receive that pick.\n\n===2007 NFL Draft===\n{{Main|2007 NFL Draft}}\nThe Patriots traded their original fifth-round pick (#165 overall) to [[2007 Oakland Raiders season|the Oakland Raiders]] during the 2006 season for [[Doug Gabriel]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2006/09/gabriel.html |title=Gabriel to Pats |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=September 2, 2006 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523102706/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2006/09/gabriel.html |archivedate=May 23, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> They also traded [[Patrick Cobbs]] to [[2007 Pittsburgh Steelers season|the Pittsburgh Steelers]] and [[Ross Tucker]] to [[2007 Cleveland Browns season|the Cleveland Browns]] prior to the 2006 season for late-round conditional draft picks, but neither players made their respective rosters, so the Patriots received no compensation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2006/09/pick_update.html |title=Pick update |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=September 2, 2006 |accessdate=June 15, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523102838/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2006/09/pick_update.html |archivedate=May 23, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:auto;\"\n|+ 2007 New England Patriots Draft Selections\n! Round !! Overall !! Player !! Position !! College\n|-\n|1{{efn|The Patriots received [[2006 Seattle Seahawks season|the Seattle Seahawks]]\u2019 first-round draft pick in a 2006 trade for [[Deion Branch]].<ref name=\"Patriotsfftoday1\">[http://fftoday.com/nfl/drafttracker.php?o=by_team&TeamID=9003 FFToday.com summary] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070403163601/http://www.fftoday.com/nfl/drafttracker.php?o=by_team&TeamID=9003 |date=April 3, 2007 }