|Dan Connolly]] C/G''\n* <span style=\"font-family: Courier New;\">''19''</span> ''[[C. J. Jones]] WR''\n* <span style=\"font-family: Courier New;\">''25''</span> ''[[Tim Mixon]] CB'' <sup>UR</sup>\n* <span style=\"font-family: Courier New;\">''85''</span> ''[[Jason Rader]] TE''\n* <span style=\"font-family: Courier New;\">''42''</span> ''[[Gemara Williams]] CB''\n\n<small>'''Notations'''</small>\n* <small>R: [[2007 NFL Draft|2007 Rookie]]</small>\n* <small>UR: 2007 [[Undrafted sportsperson|Undrafted Rookie]]</small>\n* <small>''Italicized players are not on the 53-man roster.''</small>\n|}\n\n==Awards and honors==\nBill Belichick, and numerous players, were the recipients of awards for their performances in the 2007 regular season:<ref name=\"Awards\">{{cite web |url=http://library.kraftsportsgroup.com/sbxlii_mediaguide.pdf |title=New England Patriots pre-Super Bowl press release |work=Patriots.com |accessdate=January 25, 2008 |format=PDF |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713170905/http://library.kraftsportsgroup.com/sbxlii_mediaguide.pdf |archivedate=July 13, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Recipient\n! Award(s)\n|-\n| [[Bill Belichick]]\n| Week 6: [[Motorola]] NFL Coach of the Week<br />Week 17: Motorola NFL Coach of the Week<br />2007 [[Associated Press]] [[NFL Coach of the Year Award|NFL Coach of the Year]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3179438 |title=Belichick voted coach of year for second time in four years |agency=Associated Press |publisher=ESPN |date=January 3, 2008 |accessdate=February 8, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080219194004/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3179438| archivedate= February 19, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Tom Brady]]\n| Week 3: AFC Offensive Player of the Week<br />September: AFC Offensive Player of the Month<br />Week 6: AFC Offensive Player of the Week<br />Week 6: [[FedEx Express]] NFL Player of the Week<br />Week 7: AFC Offensive Player of the Week<br />Week 7: FedEx Express NFL Player of the Week<br />October: AFC Offensive Player of the Month<br />Week 11: FedEx Express NFL Player of the Week<br />Week 14: AFC Offensive Player of the Week<br />Week 17: AFC Offensive Player of the Week<br />2007 ''[[The Sporting News|Sporting News]]'' Sportsman of the Year<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wbztv.com/local/Tom.Brady.Patriots.2.613570.html |title=Brady Named 'Sportsman Of Year' By Sporting News |work=[[WBZ-TV]] |date=December 18, 2007 |accessdate=December 21, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080114003713/http://wbztv.com/local/Tom.Brady.Patriots.2.613570.html |archivedate = January 14, 2008}}</ref><br />2007 Associated Press [[Associated Press Athlete of the Year|Male Athlete of the Year]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3164993 |title=Brady, steering Pats toward perfection, is AP male athlete of year |agency=Associated Press |publisher=ESPN |date=December 21, 2007 |accessdate=December 21, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071230020228/http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=3164993| archivedate= December 30, 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref><br />2007 Associated Press [[National Football League Most Valuable Player Award|NFL MVP]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/articles/2008/01/05/record_setting_brady_wins_mvp/ |title=Patriots QB Tom Brady rides records to MVP award |agency=Associated Press |work=The Boston Globe |first=Barry |last=Wilner |date=January 5, 2008 |accessdate=January 5, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724002649/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/articles/2008/01/05/record_setting_brady_wins_mvp/ |archivedate=July 24, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>{{ref label|offensive|a|a}}<br />2007 Associated Press [[National Football League Offensive Player of the Year Award|NFL Offensive Player of the Year]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=nfl&id=3186647 |title=Tom Brady adds AP Offensive Player of Year to MVP |agency=Associated Press |publisher=ESPN |date=January 8, 2008 |accessdate=January 8, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203090449/http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=nfl&id=3186647 |archivedate=December 3, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>{{ref label|offensive|b|b}}\n|-\n| [[Ellis Hobbs]]\n| Week 1: AFC Special Teams Player of the Week\n|-\n| [[Randy Moss]]\n| Week 9: AFC Offensive Player of the Week<br />Week 11: AFC Offensive Player of the Week<br />November: AFC Offensive Player of the Month\n|-\n| [[Stephen Neal]]\n| 2007 New England Patriots [[Ed Block Courage Award]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2008/01/neal_earns_cour.html |title=Neal earns Courage award |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=January 11, 2008 |accessdate=January 11, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022154254/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2008/01/neal_earns_cour.html |archivedate=October 22, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Asante Samuel]]\n| Week 12: AFC Defensive Player of the Week\n|-\n| [[Mike Vrabel]]\n| Week 8: AFC Defensive Player of the Week<br />Week 8: [[General Motors Corporation|GMC]] NFL Defensive Player of the Week\n|-\n| [[Ty Warren]]\n| 2007 New England Patriots [[Ron Burton]] Community Service Award<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/08/festive_gala.html |title=Festive gala |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=August 27, 2007 |accessdate=November 9, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022154302/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/08/festive_gala.html |archivedate=October 22, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Wes Welker]]\n| 2007 New England Patriots 12th Player Award<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/12/welker_12th_pla.html |title=Welker: 12th player award |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=December 19, 2007 |accessdate=December 19, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090925182448/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/12/welker_12th_pla.html |archivedate=September 25, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n|}\n\n'''Notes'''\n*{{note label|offensive|a|a}} Brady received 49 of 50 votes; [[Brett Favre]] received the other vote.\n*{{note label|offensive|b|b}} Patriots players received 49 of 50 votes: Brady earned 35.5, Randy Moss 12.5, and Wes Welker 1 (the remaining vote went to Brett Favre).\n\n===Pro Bowl and All-Pro selections===\nEight Patriots were elected to the [[2008 Pro Bowl]], the most since [[1985 New England Patriots season|1985]].<ref name=\"ProBowl\">{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/12/pro_bowl_announ.html |title=Pro Bowl announcement |work=Boston.com Reiss\u2019 Pieces |first=Mike |last=Reiss |date=December 18, 2007 |accessdate=December 18, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726170538/http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/reiss_pieces/2007/12/pro_bowl_announ.html |archivedate=July 26, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Quarterback [[Tom Brady]], offensive tackle [[Matt Light]], guard [[Logan Mankins]], wide receiver [[Randy Moss]], cornerback [[Asante Samuel]], linebacker [[Mike Vrabel]], and defensive tackle [[Vince Wilfork]] were all named as starters, while center [[Dan Koppen]] was named as a reserve.<ref name=\"ProBowl\" />\n\nOf those eight, five\u2014Brady, Light, Moss, Samuel, and Vrabel\u2014were selected to the NFL's [[All-Pro]] first team<ref name=\"All-Pro\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d805db597&template=with-video&confirm=true |title=2007 NFL All-Pro roster |agency=Associated Press |publisher=NFL  |date=January 9, 2008 |accessdate=January 10, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080111000639/http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d805db597&template=with-video&confirm=true| archivedate= January 11, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> with Moss being a unanimous selection, and Brady receiving all but one-half vote (the other half was given to Brett Favre). Wilfork, Mankins, Koppen, and wide receiver [[Wes Welker]] were named to the second team.\n\n==NFL and Franchise records set==\nThe 2007 New England Patriots tied or broke many NFL and franchise records.\n\n===Team===\n====NFL Records====\n* '''Most games won, Regular Season:''' 16\n* '''Fewest games lost, Regular Season:''' 0 ''(tied with the [[1972 Miami Dolphins season|1972 Miami Dolphins]])''\n* '''Most games won, Regular and Post Season:''' 18 ''(tied with the [[1985 Chicago Bears season|1985 Chicago Bears]])'' and 1984 San Francisco 49ers\n* '''Longest winning streak, Season:''' 16\n* '''Longest winning streak, Regular and Post Season:''' 18\n* Most Points, Season: 589 ''(surpassed by the [[2013 Denver Broncos season|2013 Denver Broncos]])''\n* '''Most Points on the Road, Season:''' 314\n* Most Games Scoring 30+ Points, Season: 12 ''(surpassed by the 2013 Denver Broncos)''\n* '''Highest Point Differential, Season:''' +315\n* Most First Downs, Season: 391 ''(surpassed by the [[2012 New England Patriots]])''\n* Touchdowns Scored, Season: 75 ''(surpassed by the 2013 Denver Broncos)''\n* '''Most consecutive games with a 20-point margin of victory, to start season:''' 4\n* '''Most Consecutive Games Won, Start of Season:''' 16\n* '''Most Consecutive Games Won, End of Season:''' 16\n* Most Consecutive Regular Season Games Won: 19 ''(surpassed by the [[2008 New England Patriots season|2008 New England Patriots]] and [[2009 Indianapolis Colts season|2009 Indianapolis Colts]])''\n\n====Franchise Records====\n* Most points scored, Game: 56 ''(tied with the [[1979 New England Patriots season|1979 New England Patriots]], surpassed by the [[2009 New England Patriots season|2009 New England Patriots]])''\n\n===Tom Brady===\n* '''Most passing touchdowns, Season:''' 50 ''(surpassed by [[Peyton Manning]] in 2013)''\n\n===Randy Moss===\n* '''Most receiving touchdowns, Season:''' 23\n\n===Wes Welker===\n* '''Most receptions in a Super Bowl:''' 11 ''(surpassed by [[James White (running back)|James White]] in [[Super Bowl LI]])''\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2007.htm Season page on Pro Football Reference]\n\n{{New England Patriots}}\n{{New England Patriots seasons}}\n{{NFL on Fox}}\n{{2007 NFL season by team}}\n\n[[Category:2007 National Football League season by team|New England]]\n[[Category:AFC East championship seasons]]\n[[Category:American Football Conference championship seasons]]\n[[Category:New England Patriots seasons]]\n[[Category:2007 in sports in Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Sub2Pewds16463", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSeason Summary", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007_New_England_Patriots_season"}
{"title_page": "Renaissance humanism", "text_new": "{{short description|Revival in the study of classical antiquity}}\n[[File:Da Vinci Vitruve Luc Viatour.jpg|thumb|upright=1|[[Leonardo da Vinci]]'s ''[[Vitruvian Man]]'' (c. 1490)\nshows the correlations of ideal human [[body proportions]] with [[geometry]] described by the ancient [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] [[architect]] [[Vitruvius]] in his ''[[De Architectura]]''. Vitruvius described the human figure as being like the principal source of proportion among the [[Classical orders]] of architecture. ]]\n\n'''Renaissance humanism''' was a revival in the study of [[classical antiquity]], at first [[Italian Renaissance|in Italy]] and then spreading across [[Western Europe]] in the 14th, 15th, and 16th centuries. Contemporary use of the term ''humanism'' is consistent with the historical use prominent in that period, while ''Renaissance humanism'' is a [[retronym]] used to distinguish it from later humanist developments.<ref>The term ''la rinascita'' (rebirth) first appeared, however, in its broad sense in [[Giorgio Vasari]]'s ''[[Vite de' pi\u00f9 eccellenti architetti, pittori, et scultori Italiani]]'' (The Lives of the Artists, 1550, revised 1568) [[Erwin Panofsky|Panofsky, Erwin]]. ''Renaissance and Renascences in Western Art'', New York: Harper and Row, 1960.\n\"The term ''umanista'' was used in fifteenth-century Italian academic slang to describe a teacher or student of classical literature and the arts associated with it, including that of rhetoric. The English equivalent 'humanist' makes its appearance in the late sixteenth century with similar meaning. Only in the nineteenth century, however, and probably for the first time in [[Humanism in Germany|Germany]] in 1809, is the attribute transformed into a substantive: ''humanism'', standing for devotion to the literature of ancient Greece and Rome, and the humane values that may be derived from them\" Nicholas Mann \"The Origins of Humanism,\" ''Cambridge Companion to Humanism'', Jill Kraye, editor [Cambridge University Press, 1996], p. 1\u20132).  The term \"[[Middle Ages]]\" for the preceding period separating classical antiquity from its \"rebirth\" first appears in Latin in 1469 as ''media tempestas''.</ref>\n\nRenaissance humanism was a response to what came to be depicted by later [[whig historians]] as the \"narrow pedantry\" associated with medieval [[scholasticism]].<ref>, Craig W. Kallendorf, introduction to ''Humanist Educational Treatises'', edited and translated by Craig W. Kallendorf (Cambridge, Massachusetts, and London England: The I Tatti Renaissance Library, 2002) p. vii.</ref> Humanists sought to create a [[citizenship|citizenry]] able to speak and write with eloquence and clarity and thus capable of engaging in the [[Civic engagement|civic life]] of their communities and persuading others to [[virtue|virtuous]] and [[prudence|prudent]] actions. This was to be accomplished through the study of the ''[[humanitas|studia humanitatis]]'', today known as the [[humanities]]: [[grammar]], [[rhetoric]], [[history]], [[poetry]], and [[ethics|moral philosophy]].\n\nHumanism was a pervasive cultural mode and not the program of a small elite, a program to revive the cultural legacy, literary legacy, and moral philosophy of classical antiquity. There were important centres of humanism in [[Florence]], [[Naples]], [[Rome]], [[Venice]], [[Genoa]], [[Mantua]], [[Ferrara]], and [[Urbino]].\n\nThe Renaissance humanism also awoke in man a love of learning and \"a true love for books...[where] humanists built book collections and university libraries developed.\" Humanists believed that the individual encompassed \"body, mind, and soul,\" and learning was very much a part of educating all aspects of the human. This love of and for learning would lead to a demand in the printed word, which in turn drove the invention of Gutenberg's printing press.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Murray, Stuart|title=Library, the : an illustrated history|date=2009|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing, Inc|isbn=978-1-62873-322-8|location=|pages=58, 68|oclc=855503629}}</ref> \n\n==Definition==\nAccording to one scholar of the movement,\n<blockquote>Early Italian humanism, which in many respects continued the grammatical and rhetorical traditions of the Middle Ages, not merely provided the old [[Trivium]] with a new and more ambitious name (''Studia humanitatis''), but also increased its actual scope, content, and significance in the curriculum of the schools and universities and its extensive literary production. The ''studia humanitatis'' excluded logic, but they added to the traditional grammar and rhetoric not only history, [[Greek language|Greek]], and moral philosophy, but also made poetry, once a sequel of grammar and rhetoric, the most important member of the whole group.<ref>Paul Oskar Kristeller, ''Renaissance Thought II: Papers on Humanism and the Arts'' (New York: Harper Torchbooks, 1965), p. 178. See also Kristeller's ''Renaissance Thought I'', \"Humanism and Scholasticism In the Italian Renaissance,\" ''Byzantion 17'' (1944\u201345), pp. 346\u201374. Reprinted in ''Renaissance Thought'' (New York: Harper Torchbooks), 1961.</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Origin==\n{{Renaissance}}\nSome of the first humanists were great collectors of antique [[manuscript]]s, including [[Petrarch]], [[Giovanni Boccaccio]], [[Coluccio Salutati]], and [[Poggio Bracciolini]]. Of the four, Petrarch was dubbed the \"Father of Humanism\" because of his devotion or loyalty to Greek and Roman scrolls. Many worked for the [[Catholic Church]] and were in [[Holy orders in the Catholic Church|holy orders]], like Petrarch. In contrast, others were [[lawyer]]s and [[chancellor]]s of Italian cities, and thus had access to book copying workshops, such as Petrarch's disciple [[Salutati]], the [[Chancellor of Florence]].\n\nIn Italy, the humanist educational program won rapid acceptance, and, by the mid-15th century, many of the [[upper class]]es had received humanist educations, possibly in addition to traditional [[Scholasticism|scholastic]] ones. Some of the highest officials of the Catholic Church were humanists with the resources to amass important libraries. Such was [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Basilios Bessarion]], a [[Religious conversion|convert]] to the Catholic Church from [[Greek Orthodoxy]], who was considered for the [[papacy]], and was one of the most learned scholars of his time. There were several 15th-century and early 16th-century humanist Popes<ref>They include [[Innocent VII]], [[Nicholas V]], [[Pius II]], [[Sixtus IV]], [[Alexander VI]], [[Julius II]] and [[Leo X]]. Innocent VII, a patron of Leonardo Bruni, is considered the first humanist Pope. See [https://books.google.com/books?id=BLgfAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA49&dq=renaissance+Humanist+popes&hl=en&ei=lPjAS6DqFYO8lQeqj-ndBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CFoQ6AEwCDge#v=onepage&q=renaissance%20Humanist%20popes&f=false  James Hankins, ''Plato in the Italian Renaissance'' (New York: Columbia Studies in the Classical Tradition, 1990), p. 49]; for the others, see their respective entries in Sir John Hale's ''Concise Encyclopaedia of the Italian Renaissance'' (Oxford University Press, 1981).</ref> one of whom, [[Aeneas Silvius Piccolomini]] (Pope Pius II), was a prolific author and wrote a treatise on ''The Education of Boys''.<ref>See ''Humanist Educational Treatises'', (2001) pp. 126\u2013259. This volume (pp. 92\u2013125) contains an essay by [[Leonardo Bruni]], entitled \"The Study of Literature,\" on the education of girls.</ref> These subjects came to be known as the humanities, and the movement which they inspired is shown as humanism.\n\nThe migration waves of [[Greek scholars in the Renaissance|Byzantine Greek scholars]] and \u00e9migr\u00e9s in the period following the [[Fourth Crusade|Crusader]] [[Sack of Constantinople (1204)|sacking of Constantinople]] and the [[fall of Constantinople|end of the Byzantine Empire]] in 1453 greatly assisted the revival of [[ancient Greece|Greek]] and [[ancient Rome|Roman]] literature and science via their greater familiarity with ancient languages and works.<ref>[http://www.the-orb.net/encyclop/late/laterbyz/harris-ren.html Byzantines in Renaissance Italy]</ref><ref>[http://how-to-learn-any-language.com/e/polyglots/greeks-in-italy.html Greeks in Italy]</ref> They included [[Gemistus Pletho]], [[George of Trebizond]], [[Theodorus Gaza]], and [[John Argyropoulos]].\n\nItalian humanism spread northward to [[Humanism in France|France]], [[Germany]], the [[Low Countries]], Poland-Lithuania, Hungary and [[England]] with the adoption of large-scale printing after 1500, and it became associated with the [[Reformation]]. In France, pre-eminent humanist [[Guillaume Bud\u00e9]] (1467\u20131540) applied the [[philology|philological]] methods of Italian humanism to the study of antique [[coin]]age and to [[legal history]], composing a detailed commentary on [[Corpus Juris Civilis|Justinian's Code]]. Bud\u00e9 was a [[Absolute monarchy|royal absolutist]] (and not a [[republicanism|republican]] like the early Italian ''umanisti'') who was active in civic life, serving as a [[diplomat]] for [[Fran\u00e7ois I]] and helping to found the [[Coll\u00e8ge de France|Coll\u00e8ge des Lecteurs Royaux]] (later the Coll\u00e8ge de France). Meanwhile, [[Marguerite de Navarre]], the sister of Fran\u00e7ois I, was a [[poet]], [[novelist]], and [[religious mystic]]<ref>She was the author of ''Miroir de l'ame pecheresse'' (''The Mirror of a Sinful Soul''), published after her death, among other devotional poetry. See also \"Marguerite de Navarre: Religious Reformist\" in Jonathan A. Reid, [http://www.brill.nl/print.aspx?partid=210&pid=18212   ''King's sister--queen of dissent: Marguerite of Navarre (1492-1549) and her evangelical network''] {{dead link|date=June 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} (''Studies in medieval and Reformation traditions, 1573-4188''; v. 139). Leiden; Boston: Brill, 2009. (2 v.: (xxii, 795 p.) {{ISBN|978-90-04-17760-4}} (v. 1), 9789004177611 (v. 2)</ref> who gathered around her and protected a circle of vernacular poets and writers, including [[Cl\u00e9ment Marot]], [[Pierre de Ronsard]], and [[Fran\u00e7ois Rabelais]].\n\n==Paganism and Christianity in the Renaissance==\n\nMany humanists were churchmen, most notably Pope Pius II, [[Pope Sixtus IV|Sixtus IV]], and [[Pope Leo X|Leo X]],<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|first=Klemens|last=L\u00f6ffler|title=Humanism|encyclopedia=The Catholic Encyclopedia|volume=VII|pages=538\u2013542|publisher=Robert Appleton Company|location=New York|year=1910}}</ref><ref>See note two, above.</ref> and there was often patronage of humanists by senior church figures.<ref>Davies, 477</ref>  Much humanist effort went into improving the understanding and translations of Biblical and early Christian texts, both before and after the Reformation, which was greatly influenced by the work of non-Italian, Northern European figures such as [[Erasmus]], [[Jacques Lef\u00e8vre d'\u00c9taples]], [[William Grocyn]], and Swedish Catholic Archbishop in exile [[Olaus Magnus]].\n\n===Description===\n''The Cambridge Dictionary of Philosophy'' describes the [[rationalism]] of ancient writings as having a tremendous impact on [[Renaissance]] scholars:\n\n{{quote|Here, one felt no weight of the supernatural pressing on the human mind, demanding homage and allegiance. Humanity\u2014with all its distinct capabilities, talents, worries, problems, possibilities\u2014was the center of interest. It has been said that medieval thinkers philosophized on their knees, but, bolstered by the new studies, they dared to stand up and to rise to full stature.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Humanism|encyclopedia=[[The Cambridge Dictionary of Philosophy]], Second Edition|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1999}} p.397 quotation: {{quotation|The unashamedly humanistic flavor of classical writings had a tremendous impact on Renaissance scholar.}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1417, for example, [[Poggio Bracciolini]] discovered the manuscript of [[Lucretius]], ''[[De rerum natura]]'', which had been lost for centuries and which contained an explanation of [[Epicureanism|Epicurean doctrine]]. However, at the time this was not commented on much by Renaissance scholars, who confined themselves to remarks about Lucretius's grammar and [[syntax]].\n\nOnly in 1564 did French commentator Denys Lambin (1519\u201372) announce in the preface to the work that \"he regarded Lucretius's Epicurean ideas as 'fanciful, absurd, and opposed to Christianity.'\" Lambin's introduction remained standard until the nineteenth century.<ref>See Jill Kraye's essay, \"Philologists and Philosophers\" in the ''Cambridge Companion to Renaissance Humanism'' [1996], p. 153.)</ref> Epicurus's unacceptable doctrine that pleasure was the highest good \"ensured the unpopularity of his philosophy.\" <ref>(Kraye [1996] p. 154.)</ref> [[Lorenzo Valla]], however, puts a defense of Epicureanism in the mouth of one of the interlocutors of one of his dialogues.\n\n===Epicureanism===\nCharles Trinkhaus regards Valla's \"epicureanism\" as a ploy, not seriously meant by Valla, but designed to refute Stoicism, which he regarded together with Epicureanism as equally inferior to Christianity.<ref>See Trinkaus, ''In Our Image and Likeness'' Vol. 1 (University of Chicago Press, 1970), pp. 103\u2013170</ref> Valla's defense, or adaptation, of Epicureanism was later taken up  in ''The Epicurean'' by [[Erasmus]], the \"Prince of humanists:\"\n\n{{quote|If people who live agreeably are [[Epicureans]], none are more truly [[Epicurean]] than the righteous and godly.  And if it is names that bother us, no one better deserves the name of Epicurean than the revered founder and head of the [[Christianity|Christian]] philosophy [[Christ]], for in Greek ''epikouros'' means \"helper.\"  He alone, when the [[law of Nature]] was all but blotted out by sins, when the [[law of Moses]] incited to lists rather than cured them, when [[Satan]] ruled in the world unchallenged, brought timely aid to perishing humanity.  Completely mistaken, therefore, are those who talk in their foolish fashion about Christ's having been sad and gloomy in character and calling upon us to follow a dark mode of life.  On the contrary, he alone shows the most enjoyable life of all and the one most full of true pleasure.<ref name=\"Lepage2012\">{{cite book|author=John L. Lepage|title=The Revival of Antique Philosophy in the Renaissance|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xb2uw2LQjPQC&pg=PA111|date=5 December 2012|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-137-28181-4|page=111}}</ref>}}\n\nThis passage exemplifies how the humanists saw [[pagan]] [[Ancient Greek literature|classical works]], such as the philosophy of [[Epicurus]], as being in harmony with their interpretation of [[Christianity]].\n\n===Neo-Platonism===\n[[Platonism in the Renaissance|Renaissance Neo-Platonists]] such as [[Marsilio Ficino]] (whose translations of Plato's works into Latin were still used into the 19th century) attempted to reconcile [[Platonism]] with Christianity, according to the suggestions of early [[Church Fathers]] [[Lactantius]] and [[Augustine of Hippo|Saint Augustine]]. In this spirit, [[Giovanni Pico della Mirandola|Pico della Mirandola]] attempted to construct a [[syncretism]] of religions and philosophies with Christianity, but his work did not win favor with the church authorities, who rejected it because of his views on magic.<ref name=\"O'Callaghan2012\">{{cite book|author=Daniel O'Callaghan|title=The Preservation of Jewish Religious Books in Sixteenth-Century Germany: Johannes Reuchlin's Augenspiegel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xt6b2Wi8kCQC&pg=PA43|date=9 November 2012|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-24185-X|pages=43\u2013}}</ref>\n\n===Widespread view===\nHistorian Steven Kreis expresses a widespread view (derived from the 19th-century Swiss historian [[Jacob Burckhardt]]), when he writes that: <blockquote>The period from the fourteenth century to the seventeenth worked in favor of the general emancipation of the individual. The city-states of northern Italy had come into contact with the diverse customs of the East, and gradually permitted expression in matters of taste and dress. The writings of Dante, and particularly the doctrines of Petrarch and humanists like Machiavelli, emphasized the virtues of intellectual freedom and individual expression. In the essays of Montaigne the individualistic view of life received perhaps the most persuasive and eloquent statement in the history of literature and philosophy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kreis|first=Steven|title=Renaissance Humanism|year=2008|url=http://www.historyguide.org/intellect/humanism.html|accessdate=2009-03-03}}</ref></blockquote>\nTwo noteworthy trends in Renaissance humanism were Renaissance Neo-Platonism and [[Hermeticism]], which through the works of figures like [[Nicholas of Kues]], [[Giordano Bruno]], [[Cornelius Agrippa]], [[Tommaso Campanella|Campanella]] and Pico della Mirandola sometimes came close to constituting a new religion itself. Of these two, Hermeticism has had great continuing influence in Western thought, while the former mostly dissipated as an intellectual trend, leading to movements in [[Western esotericism]] such as [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|Theosophy]] and [[New Age]] thinking.<ref>Plumb, 95</ref>  The \"Yates thesis\" of [[Frances Yates]] holds that before falling out of favor, esoteric Renaissance thought introduced several concepts that were useful for the development of the scientific method. However, this remains a matter of controversy.\n\n===Sixteenth century and beyond===\n{{Reformationliterature |expanded=overview}}\nThough humanists continued to use their scholarship in the service of the church into the middle of the sixteenth century and beyond, the sharply confrontational religious atmosphere following the Reformation resulted in the [[Counter-Reformation]] that sought to silence challenges to [[Catholic theology]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Rome Reborn: The Vatican Library & Renaissance Culture: Humanism|publisher=The Library of Congress|url=https://www.loc.gov/exhibits/vatican/humanism.html|date=2002-07-01|accessdate=2009-03-03}}</ref> with similar efforts among the [[Protestant denominations]]. However, a number of humanists joined the Reformation movement and took over leadership functions, for example, [[Philipp Melanchthon]], [[Ulrich Zwingli]], [[Martin Luther]], [[Henry VIII]], [[John Calvin]], and [[William Tyndale]].\n\nWith the Counter-Reformation initiated by the [[Council of Trent]] (1545-1563), positions hardened and a strict Catholic orthodoxy based on Scholastic philosophy was imposed. Some humanists, even moderate Catholics such as Erasmus, risked being declared heretics for their perceived criticism of the church. In 1514 he left for [[Basel]] and worked at the [[University of Basel]] for several years.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Humanism|encyclopedia=Encyclopedic Dictionary of Religion|volume=F-N|pages=[https://archive.org/details/encyclopedicdict0000meag/page/1733 1733]|publisher=Corpus Publications|year=1979|isbn=978-0-9602572-1-8|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopedicdict0000meag/page/1733}}</ref>\n\nThe historian of the Renaissance [[John Rigby Hale|Sir John Hale]] cautions against too direct a linkage between Renaissance humanism and modern uses of the term humanism: \"Renaissance humanism must be kept free from any hint of either 'humanitarianism' or 'humanism' in its modern sense of rational, non-religious approach to life ... the word 'humanism' will mislead ... if it is seen in opposition to a Christianity its students in the main wished to supplement, not contradict, through their patient excavation of the sources of ancient God-inspired wisdom.\"<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=dJc3cOUVIYMC&q=contradict#search_anchor Hale, 171.] See also Davies, 479-480 for similar caution.</ref>\n\n==Humanists==\n{{main|List of Renaissance humanists}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Humanism}}\n* [[Renaissance humanism in Northern Europe]]\n* [[Christian humanism]]\n* [[Greek scholars in the Renaissance]]\n* [[Renaissance Latin]]\n* [[Legal humanists]]\n* [[New Learning]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bolgar, R. R. ''The Classical Heritage and Its Beneficiaries: from the Carolingian Age to the End of the Renaissance''. Cambridge, 1954.\n* [[Ernst Cassirer|Cassirer, Ernst]]. ''Individual and Cosmos in Renaissance Philosophy''. Harper and Row, 1963.\n* Cassirer, Ernst (Editor), Paul Oskar Kristeller (Editor), John Herman Randall (Editor). ''The Renaissance Philosophy of Man''. University of Chicago Press, 1969.\n* Cassirer, Ernst. ''Platonic Renaissance in England''. Gordian, 1970.\n* Celenza, Christopher S. ''The Lost Italian Renaissance: Humanism, Historians, and Latin's Legacy''. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press. 2004 {{ISBN|978-0-8018-8384-2}}\n* Celenza, Christopher S. ''Petrarch: Everywhere a Wanderer''. London: Reaktion. 2017\n* Celenza, Christopher S. ''The Intellectual World of the Italian Renaissance: Language, Philosophy, and the Search for Meaning''. New York and Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. 2018\n* [[Desiderius Erasmus|Erasmus, Desiderius]]. \"The Epicurean.\" In ''Colloquies''.\n* [[Eugenio Garin|Garin, Eugenio]]. ''Science and Civic Life in the Italian Renaissance''. New York: Doubleday, 1969.\n* Garin, Eugenio. ''Italian Humanism: Philosophy and Civic Life in the Renaissance.'' Basil Blackwell, 1965.\n* Garin, Eugenio. ''History of Italian Philosophy.'' (2 vols.) Amsterdam/New York: Rodopi, 2008. {{ISBN|978-90-420-2321-5}}\n* [[Anthony Grafton|Grafton, Anthony]]. ''Bring Out Your Dead: The Past as Revelation''. Harvard University Press, 2004 {{ISBN|0-674-01597-5}}\n* Grafton, Anthony. ''Worlds Made By Words: Scholarship and Community in the Modern West''. Harvard University Press, 2009 {{ISBN|0-674-03257-8}}\n* [[John Rigby Hale|Hale, John]]. ''A Concise Encyclopaedia of the Italian Renaissance''. Oxford University Press, 1981, {{ISBN|0-500-23333-0}}.\n* Kallendorf, Craig W, editor. ''Humanist Educational Treatises''. Cambridge, Massachusetts: The I Tatti Renaissance Library, 2002.\n* Kraye, Jill (Editor). ''The Cambridge Companion to Renaissance Humanism''. Cambridge University Press, 1996.\n* [[Paul Oskar Kristeller|Kristeller, Paul Oskar]]. ''Renaissance Thought and Its Sources''. Columbia University Press, 1979 {{ISBN|978-0-231-04513-1}}\n* [[Giovanni Pico della Mirandola|Pico della Mirandola, Giovanni]]. ''Oration on the Dignity of Man''. In Cassirer, Kristeller, and Randall, eds. ''Renaissance Philosophy of Man''. University of Chicago Press, 1969.\n* [[Quentin Skinner|Skinner, Quentin]]. ''Renaissance Virtues: Visions of Politics: Volume II''. Cambridge University Press, [2002] 2007.\n* McManus, Stuart M. \"Byzantines in the Florentine Polis: Ideology, Statecraft, and Ritual during the Council of Florence.\" ''[[Journal of the Oxford University History Society]]'', 6 (Michaelmas 2008/Hilary 2009).\n* {{cite book | author=Melchert, Norman | title=The Great Conversation: A Historical Introduction to Philosophy | url=https://archive.org/details/greatconversatio00norm | url-access=registration | publisher=McGraw Hill | year=2002 | isbn=978-0-19-517510-3}}\n* Nauert, Charles Garfield. ''Humanism and the Culture of Renaissance Europe (New Approaches to European History).'' Cambridge University Press, 2006.\n* [[John H. Plumb|Plumb, J. H.]] ed.: ''The Italian Renaissance'' 1961, American Heritage, New York, {{ISBN|0-618-12738-0}} (page refs from 1978 UK Penguin edn).\n* [[Roberto Rossellini|Rossellini, Roberto]]. ''The Age of the Medici'': Part 1, ''Cosimo de' Medici''; Part 2, ''Alberti'' 1973.  (Film Series). Criterion Collection.\n* [[John Addington Symonds|Symonds, John Addington]].''The Renaissance in Italy''. Seven Volumes. 1875\u20131886.\n* {{cite book|url=http://xtf.lib.virginia.edu/xtf/view?docId=DicHist/uvaGenText/tei/DicHist4.xml;chunk.id=dv4-20 | contribution = Renaissance Idea of the Dignity of Man | title = Dictionary of the History of Ideas | accessdate=2009-12-02 | last = Trinkaus | first = Charles | editor-last = Wiener | editor-first = Philip P | year = 1973 | ISBN = 978-0-684-13293-8}}\n* Trinkaus, Charles. ''The Scope of Renaissance Humanism''. Ann Arbor: University of Michigan Press, 1983.\n* [[Edgar Wind|Wind, Edgar]]. ''Pagan Mysteries in the Renaissance''. New York: W.W. Norton, 1969.\n* Witt, Ronald. \"In the footsteps of the ancients: the origins of humanism from Lovato to Bruni.\" Leiden: Brill Publishers, 2000\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101102042052/http://globaled.org/nyworld/materials/humanism/H1.html Humanism 1: An Outline by Albert Rabil, Jr.]\n* [https://www.loc.gov/exhibits/vatican/humanism.html \"Rome Reborn: The Vatican Library & Renaissance Culture: Humanism.\" The Library of Congress. 2002-07-01]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p003k9ct Paganism in the Renaissance], BBC Radio 4 discussion with Tom Healy, Charles Hope & Evelyn Welch (''In Our Time'', June 16, 2005)\n\n{{Philosophy topics}}\n{{Middle Ages}}\n\n[[Category:Renaissance humanism| ]]\n[[Category:Medieval philosophy]]\n[[Category:Philosophical movements]]\n[[Category:Renaissance|Humanism]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Revival in the study of classical antiquity}}\n[[File:Da Vinci Vitruve Luc Viatour.jpg|thumb|upright=1|[[Leonardo da Vinci]]'s ''[[Vitruvian Man]]'' (c. 1490)\nshows the correlations of ideal human [[body proportions]] with [[geometry]] described by the ancient [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] [[architect]] [[Vitruvius]] in his ''[[De Architectura]]''. Vitruvius described the human figure as being like the principal source of proportion among the [[Classical orders]] of architecture. ]]\n\n'''Renaissance humanism''' was a revival in the study of [[classical antiquity]], at first [[Italian Renaissance|in Italy]] and then spreading across [[Western Europe]] in the 14th, 15th, and 16th centuries. Contemporary use of the term ''humanism'' is consistent with the historical use prominent in that period, while ''Renaissance humanism'' is a [[retronym]] used to distinguish it from later humanist developments.<ref>The term ''la rinascita'' (rebirth) first appeared, however, in its broad sense in [[Giorgio Vasari]]'s ''[[Vite de' pi\u00f9 eccellenti architetti, pittori, et scultori Italiani]]'' (The Lives of the Artists, 1550, revised 1568) [[Erwin Panofsky|Panofsky, Erwin]]. ''Renaissance and Renascences in Western Art'', New York: Harper and Row, 1960.\n\"The term ''umanista'' was used in fifteenth-century Italian academic slang to describe a teacher or student of classical literature and the arts associated with it, including that of rhetoric. The English equivalent 'humanist' makes its appearance in the late sixteenth century with similar meaning. Only in the nineteenth century, however, and probably for the first time in [[Humanism in Germany|Germany]] in 1809, is the attribute transformed into a substantive: ''humanism'', standing for devotion to the literature of ancient Greece and Rome, and the humane values that may be derived from them\" Nicholas Mann \"The Origins of Humanism,\" ''Cambridge Companion to Humanism'', Jill Kraye, editor [Cambridge University Press, 1996], p. 1\u20132).  The term \"[[Middle Ages]]\" for the preceding period separating classical antiquity from its \"rebirth\" first appears in Latin in 1469 as ''media tempestas''.</ref>\n\nRenaissance humanism was a response to what came to be depicted by later [[whig historians]] as the \"narrow pedantry\" associated with medieval [[scholasticism]].<ref>, Craig W. Kallendorf, introduction to ''Humanist Educational Treatises'', edited and translated by Craig W. Kallendorf (Cambridge, Massachusetts, and London England: The I Tatti Renaissance Library, 2002) p. vii.</ref> Humanists sought to create a [[citizenship|citizenry]] able to speak and write with eloquence and clarity and thus capable of engaging in the [[Civic engagement|civic life]] of their communities and persuading others to [[virtue|virtuous]] and [[prudence|prudent]] actions. This was to be accomplished through the study of the ''[[humanitas|studia humanitatis]]'', today known as the [[humanities]]: [[grammar]], [[rhetoric]], [[history]], [[poetry]], and [[ethics|moral philosophy]].\n\nHumanism was a pervasive cultural mode and not the program of a small elite, a program to revive the cultural legacy, literary legacy, and moral philosophy of classical antiquity. There were important centres of humanism in [[Florence]], [[Naples]], [[Rome]], [[Venice]], [[Genoa]], [[Mantua]], [[Ferrara]], and [[Urbino]].\n\nThe Renaissance humanism also awoke in man a love of learning and \"a true love for books...[where] humanists built book collections and university libraries developed.\" Humanists believed that the individual encompassed \"body, mind, and soul,\" and learning was very much a part of educating all aspects of the human. This love of and for learning would lead to a demand in the printed word, which in turn drove the invention of Gutenberg's printing press.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Murray, Stuart, 1948-|title=Library, the : an illustrated history|date=2009|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing, Inc|isbn=978-1-62873-322-8|location=|pages=58, 68|oclc=855503629}}</ref> \n\n==Definition==\nAccording to one scholar of the movement,\n<blockquote>Early Italian humanism, which in many respects continued the grammatical and rhetorical traditions of the Middle Ages, not merely provided the old [[Trivium]] with a new and more ambitious name (''Studia humanitatis''), but also increased its actual scope, content, and significance in the curriculum of the schools and universities and its extensive literary production. The ''studia humanitatis'' excluded logic, but they added to the traditional grammar and rhetoric not only history, [[Greek language|Greek]], and moral philosophy, but also made poetry, once a sequel of grammar and rhetoric, the most important member of the whole group.<ref>Paul Oskar Kristeller, ''Renaissance Thought II: Papers on Humanism and the Arts'' (New York: Harper Torchbooks, 1965), p. 178. See also Kristeller's ''Renaissance Thought I'', \"Humanism and Scholasticism In the Italian Renaissance,\" ''Byzantion 17'' (1944\u201345), pp. 346\u201374. Reprinted in ''Renaissance Thought'' (New York: Harper Torchbooks), 1961.</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Origin==\n{{Renaissance}}\nSome of the first humanists were great collectors of antique [[manuscript]]s, including [[Petrarch]], [[Giovanni Boccaccio]], [[Coluccio Salutati]], and [[Poggio Bracciolini]]. Of the four, Petrarch was dubbed the \"Father of Humanism\" because of his devotion or loyalty to Greek and Roman scrolls. Many worked for the [[Catholic Church]] and were in [[Holy orders in the Catholic Church|holy orders]], like Petrarch. In contrast, others were [[lawyer]]s and [[chancellor]]s of Italian cities, and thus had access to book copying workshops, such as Petrarch's disciple [[Salutati]], the [[Chancellor of Florence]].\n\nIn Italy, the humanist educational program won rapid acceptance, and, by the mid-15th century, many of the [[upper class]]es had received humanist educations, possibly in addition to traditional [[Scholasticism|scholastic]] ones. Some of the highest officials of the Catholic Church were humanists with the resources to amass important libraries. Such was [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Basilios Bessarion]], a [[Religious conversion|convert]] to the Catholic Church from [[Greek Orthodoxy]], who was considered for the [[papacy]], and was one of the most learned scholars of his time. There were several 15th-century and early 16th-century humanist Popes<ref>They include [[Innocent VII]], [[Nicholas V]], [[Pius II]], [[Sixtus IV]], [[Alexander VI]], [[Julius II]] and [[Leo X]]. Innocent VII, a patron of Leonardo Bruni, is considered the first humanist Pope. See [https://books.google.com/books?id=BLgfAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA49&dq=renaissance+Humanist+popes&hl=en&ei=lPjAS6DqFYO8lQeqj-ndBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CFoQ6AEwCDge#v=onepage&q=renaissance%20Humanist%20popes&f=false  James Hankins, ''Plato in the Italian Renaissance'' (New York: Columbia Studies in the Classical Tradition, 1990), p. 49]; for the others, see their respective entries in Sir John Hale's ''Concise Encyclopaedia of the Italian Renaissance'' (Oxford University Press, 1981).</ref> one of whom, [[Aeneas Silvius Piccolomini]] (Pope Pius II), was a prolific author and wrote a treatise on ''The Education of Boys''.<ref>See ''Humanist Educational Treatises'', (2001) pp. 126\u2013259. This volume (pp. 92\u2013125) contains an essay by [[Leonardo Bruni]], entitled \"The Study of Literature,\" on the education of girls.</ref> These subjects came to be known as the humanities, and the movement which they inspired is shown as humanism.\n\nThe migration waves of [[Greek scholars in the Renaissance|Byzantine Greek scholars]] and \u00e9migr\u00e9s in the period following the [[Fourth Crusade|Crusader]] [[Sack of Constantinople (1204)|sacking of Constantinople]] and the [[fall of Constantinople|end of the Byzantine Empire]] in 1453 greatly assisted the revival of [[ancient Greece|Greek]] and [[ancient Rome|Roman]] literature and science via their greater familiarity with ancient languages and works.<ref>[http://www.the-orb.net/encyclop/late/laterbyz/harris-ren.html Byzantines in Renaissance Italy]</ref><ref>[http://how-to-learn-any-language.com/e/polyglots/greeks-in-italy.html Greeks in Italy]</ref> They included [[Gemistus Pletho]], [[George of Trebizond]], [[Theodorus Gaza]], and [[John Argyropoulos]].\n\nItalian humanism spread northward to [[Humanism in France|France]], [[Germany]], the [[Low Countries]], Poland-Lithuania, Hungary and [[England]] with the adoption of large-scale printing after 1500, and it became associated with the [[Reformation]]. In France, pre-eminent humanist [[Guillaume Bud\u00e9]] (1467\u20131540) applied the [[philology|philological]] methods of Italian humanism to the study of antique [[coin]]age and to [[legal history]], composing a detailed commentary on [[Corpus Juris Civilis|Justinian's Code]]. Bud\u00e9 was a [[Absolute monarchy|royal absolutist]] (and not a [[republicanism|republican]] like the early Italian ''umanisti'') who was active in civic life, serving as a [[diplomat]] for [[Fran\u00e7ois I]] and helping to found the [[Coll\u00e8ge de France|Coll\u00e8ge des Lecteurs Royaux]] (later the Coll\u00e8ge de France). Meanwhile, [[Marguerite de Navarre]], the sister of Fran\u00e7ois I, was a [[poet]], [[novelist]], and [[religious mystic]]<ref>She was the author of ''Miroir de l'ame pecheresse'' (''The Mirror of a Sinful Soul''), published after her death, among other devotional poetry. See also \"Marguerite de Navarre: Religious Reformist\" in Jonathan A. Reid, [http://www.brill.nl/print.aspx?partid=210&pid=18212   ''King's sister--queen of dissent: Marguerite of Navarre (1492-1549) and her evangelical network''] {{dead link|date=June 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} (''Studies in medieval and Reformation traditions, 1573-4188''; v. 139). Leiden; Boston: Brill, 2009. (2 v.: (xxii, 795 p.) {{ISBN|978-90-04-17760-4}} (v. 1), 9789004177611 (v. 2)</ref> who gathered around her and protected a circle of vernacular poets and writers, including [[Cl\u00e9ment Marot]], [[Pierre de Ronsard]], and [[Fran\u00e7ois Rabelais]].\n\n==Paganism and Christianity in the Renaissance==\n\nMany humanists were churchmen, most notably Pope Pius II, [[Pope Sixtus IV|Sixtus IV]], and [[Pope Leo X|Leo X]],<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|first=Klemens|last=L\u00f6ffler|title=Humanism|encyclopedia=The Catholic Encyclopedia|volume=VII|pages=538\u2013542|publisher=Robert Appleton Company|location=New York|year=1910}}</ref><ref>See note two, above.</ref> and there was often patronage of humanists by senior church figures.<ref>Davies, 477</ref>  Much humanist effort went into improving the understanding and translations of Biblical and early Christian texts, both before and after the Reformation, which was greatly influenced by the work of non-Italian, Northern European figures such as [[Erasmus]], [[Jacques Lef\u00e8vre d'\u00c9taples]], [[William Grocyn]], and Swedish Catholic Archbishop in exile [[Olaus Magnus]].\n\n===Description===\n''The Cambridge Dictionary of Philosophy'' describes the [[rationalism]] of ancient writings as having a tremendous impact on [[Renaissance]] scholars:\n\n{{quote|Here, one felt no weight of the supernatural pressing on the human mind, demanding homage and allegiance. Humanity\u2014with all its distinct capabilities, talents, worries, problems, possibilities\u2014was the center of interest. It has been said that medieval thinkers philosophized on their knees, but, bolstered by the new studies, they dared to stand up and to rise to full stature.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Humanism|encyclopedia=[[The Cambridge Dictionary of Philosophy]], Second Edition|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1999}} p.397 quotation: {{quotation|The unashamedly humanistic flavor of classical writings had a tremendous impact on Renaissance scholar.}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1417, for example, [[Poggio Bracciolini]] discovered the manuscript of [[Lucretius]], ''[[De rerum natura]]'', which had been lost for centuries and which contained an explanation of [[Epicureanism|Epicurean doctrine]]. However, at the time this was not commented on much by Renaissance scholars, who confined themselves to remarks about Lucretius's grammar and [[syntax]].\n\nOnly in 1564 did French commentator Denys Lambin (1519\u201372) announce in the preface to the work that \"he regarded Lucretius's Epicurean ideas as 'fanciful, absurd, and opposed to Christianity.'\" Lambin's introduction remained standard until the nineteenth century.<ref>See Jill Kraye's essay, \"Philologists and Philosophers\" in the ''Cambridge Companion to Renaissance Humanism'' [1996], p. 153.)</ref> Epicurus's unacceptable doctrine that pleasure was the highest good \"ensured the unpopularity of his philosophy.\" <ref>(Kraye [1996] p. 154.)</ref> [[Lorenzo Valla]], however, puts a defense of Epicureanism in the mouth of one of the interlocutors of one of his dialogues.\n\n===Epicureanism===\nCharles Trinkhaus regards Valla's \"epicureanism\" as a ploy, not seriously meant by Valla, but designed to refute Stoicism, which he regarded together with Epicureanism as equally inferior to Christianity.<ref>See Trinkaus, ''In Our Image and Likeness'' Vol. 1 (University of Chicago Press, 1970), pp. 103\u2013170</ref> Valla's defense, or adaptation, of Epicureanism was later taken up  in ''The Epicurean'' by [[Erasmus]], the \"Prince of humanists:\"\n\n{{quote|If people who live agreeably are [[Epicureans]], none are more truly [[Epicurean]] than the righteous and godly.  And if it is names that bother us, no one better deserves the name of Epicurean than the revered founder and head of the [[Christianity|Christian]] philosophy [[Christ]], for in Greek ''epikouros'' means \"helper.\"  He alone, when the [[law of Nature]] was all but blotted out by sins, when the [[law of Moses]] incited to lists rather than cured them, when [[Satan]] ruled in the world unchallenged, brought timely aid to perishing humanity.  Completely mistaken, therefore, are those who talk in their foolish fashion about Christ's having been sad and gloomy in character and calling upon us to follow a dark mode of life.  On the contrary, he alone shows the most enjoyable life of all and the one most full of true pleasure.<ref name=\"Lepage2012\">{{cite book|author=John L. Lepage|title=The Revival of Antique Philosophy in the Renaissance|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xb2uw2LQjPQC&pg=PA111|date=5 December 2012|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-137-28181-4|page=111}}</ref>}}\n\nThis passage exemplifies how the humanists saw [[pagan]] [[Ancient Greek literature|classical works]], such as the philosophy of [[Epicurus]], as being in harmony with their interpretation of [[Christianity]].\n\n===Neo-Platonism===\n[[Platonism in the Renaissance|Renaissance Neo-Platonists]] such as [[Marsilio Ficino]] (whose translations of Plato's works into Latin were still used into the 19th century) attempted to reconcile [[Platonism]] with Christianity, according to the suggestions of early [[Church Fathers]] [[Lactantius]] and [[Augustine of Hippo|Saint Augustine]]. In this spirit, [[Giovanni Pico della Mirandola|Pico della Mirandola]] attempted to construct a [[syncretism]] of religions and philosophies with Christianity, but his work did not win favor with the church authorities, who rejected it because of his views on magic.<ref name=\"O'Callaghan2012\">{{cite book|author=Daniel O'Callaghan|title=The Preservation of Jewish Religious Books in Sixteenth-Century Germany: Johannes Reuchlin's Augenspiegel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xt6b2Wi8kCQC&pg=PA43|date=9 November 2012|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-24185-X|pages=43\u2013}}</ref>\n\n===Widespread view===\nHistorian Steven Kreis expresses a widespread view (derived from the 19th-century Swiss historian [[Jacob Burckhardt]]), when he writes that: <blockquote>The period from the fourteenth century to the seventeenth worked in favor of the general emancipation of the individual. The city-states of northern Italy had come into contact with the diverse customs of the East, and gradually permitted expression in matters of taste and dress. The writings of Dante, and particularly the doctrines of Petrarch and humanists like Machiavelli, emphasized the virtues of intellectual freedom and individual expression. In the essays of Montaigne the individualistic view of life received perhaps the most persuasive and eloquent statement in the history of literature and philosophy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kreis|first=Steven|title=Renaissance Humanism|year=2008|url=http://www.historyguide.org/intellect/humanism.html|accessdate=2009-03-03}}</ref></blockquote>\nTwo noteworthy trends in Renaissance humanism were Renaissance Neo-Platonism and [[Hermeticism]], which through the works of figures like [[Nicholas of Kues]], [[Giordano Bruno]], [[Cornelius Agrippa]], [[Tommaso Campanella|Campanella]] and Pico della Mirandola sometimes came close to constituting a new religion itself. Of these two, Hermeticism has had great continuing influence in Western thought, while the former mostly dissipated as an intellectual trend, leading to movements in [[Western esotericism]] such as [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|Theosophy]] and [[New Age]] thinking.<ref>Plumb, 95</ref>  The \"Yates thesis\" of [[Frances Yates]] holds that before falling out of favor, esoteric Renaissance thought introduced several concepts that were useful for the development of the scientific method. However, this remains a matter of controversy.\n\n===Sixteenth century and beyond===\n{{Reformationliterature |expanded=overview}}\nThough humanists continued to use their scholarship in the service of the church into the middle of the sixteenth century and beyond, the sharply confrontational religious atmosphere following the Reformation resulted in the [[Counter-Reformation]] that sought to silence challenges to [[Catholic theology]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Rome Reborn: The Vatican Library & Renaissance Culture: Humanism|publisher=The Library of Congress|url=https://www.loc.gov/exhibits/vatican/humanism.html|date=2002-07-01|accessdate=2009-03-03}}</ref> with similar efforts among the [[Protestant denominations]]. However, a number of humanists joined the Reformation movement and took over leadership functions, for example, [[Philipp Melanchthon]], [[Ulrich Zwingli]], [[Martin Luther]], [[Henry VIII]], [[John Calvin]], and [[William Tyndale]].\n\nWith the Counter-Reformation initiated by the [[Council of Trent]] (1545-1563), positions hardened and a strict Catholic orthodoxy based on Scholastic philosophy was imposed. Some humanists, even moderate Catholics such as Erasmus, risked being declared heretics for their perceived criticism of the church. In 1514 he left for [[Basel]] and worked at the [[University of Basel]] for several years.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Humanism|encyclopedia=Encyclopedic Dictionary of Religion|volume=F-N|pages=[https://archive.org/details/encyclopedicdict0000meag/page/1733 1733]|publisher=Corpus Publications|year=1979|isbn=978-0-9602572-1-8|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopedicdict0000meag/page/1733}}</ref>\n\nThe historian of the Renaissance [[John Rigby Hale|Sir John Hale]] cautions against too direct a linkage between Renaissance humanism and modern uses of the term humanism: \"Renaissance humanism must be kept free from any hint of either 'humanitarianism' or 'humanism' in its modern sense of rational, non-religious approach to life ... the word 'humanism' will mislead ... if it is seen in opposition to a Christianity its students in the main wished to supplement, not contradict, through their patient excavation of the sources of ancient God-inspired wisdom.\"<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=dJc3cOUVIYMC&q=contradict#search_anchor Hale, 171.] See also Davies, 479-480 for similar caution.</ref>\n\n==Humanists==\n{{main|List of Renaissance humanists}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Humanism}}\n* [[Renaissance humanism in Northern Europe]]\n* [[Christian humanism]]\n* [[Greek scholars in the Renaissance]]\n* [[Renaissance Latin]]\n* [[Legal humanists]]\n* [[New Learning]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bolgar, R. R. ''The Classical Heritage and Its Beneficiaries: from the Carolingian Age to the End of the Renaissance''. Cambridge, 1954.\n* [[Ernst Cassirer|Cassirer, Ernst]]. ''Individual and Cosmos in Renaissance Philosophy''. Harper and Row, 1963.\n* Cassirer, Ernst (Editor), Paul Oskar Kristeller (Editor), John Herman Randall (Editor). ''The Renaissance Philosophy of Man''. University of Chicago Press, 1969.\n* Cassirer, Ernst. ''Platonic Renaissance in England''. Gordian, 1970.\n* Celenza, Christopher S. ''The Lost Italian Renaissance: Humanism, Historians, and Latin's Legacy''. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press. 2004 {{ISBN|978-0-8018-8384-2}}\n* Celenza, Christopher S. ''Petrarch: Everywhere a Wanderer''. London: Reaktion. 2017\n* Celenza, Christopher S. ''The Intellectual World of the Italian Renaissance: Language, Philosophy, and the Search for Meaning''. New York and Cambridge: Cambridge University Press. 2018\n* [[Desiderius Erasmus|Erasmus, Desiderius]]. \"The Epicurean.\" In ''Colloquies''.\n* [[Eugenio Garin|Garin, Eugenio]]. ''Science and Civic Life in the Italian Renaissance''. New York: Doubleday, 1969.\n* Garin, Eugenio. ''Italian Humanism: Philosophy and Civic Life in the Renaissance.'' Basil Blackwell, 1965.\n* Garin, Eugenio. ''History of Italian Philosophy.'' (2 vols.) Amsterdam/New York: Rodopi, 2008. {{ISBN|978-90-420-2321-5}}\n* [[Anthony Grafton|Grafton, Anthony]]. ''Bring Out Your Dead: The Past as Revelation''. Harvard University Press, 2004 {{ISBN|0-674-01597-5}}\n* Grafton, Anthony. ''Worlds Made By Words: Scholarship and Community in the Modern West''. Harvard University Press, 2009 {{ISBN|0-674-03257-8}}\n* [[John Rigby Hale|Hale, John]]. ''A Concise Encyclopaedia of the Italian Renaissance''. Oxford University Press, 1981, {{ISBN|0-500-23333-0}}.\n* Kallendorf, Craig W, editor. ''Humanist Educational Treatises''. Cambridge, Massachusetts: The I Tatti Renaissance Library, 2002.\n* Kraye, Jill (Editor). ''The Cambridge Companion to Renaissance Humanism''. Cambridge University Press, 1996.\n* [[Paul Oskar Kristeller|Kristeller, Paul Oskar]]. ''Renaissance Thought and Its Sources''. Columbia University Press, 1979 {{ISBN|978-0-231-04513-1}}\n* [[Giovanni Pico della Mirandola|Pico della Mirandola, Giovanni]]. ''Oration on the Dignity of Man''. In Cassirer, Kristeller, and Randall, eds. ''Renaissance Philosophy of Man''. University of Chicago Press, 1969.\n* [[Quentin Skinner|Skinner, Quentin]]. ''Renaissance Virtues: Visions of Politics: Volume II''. Cambridge University Press, [2002] 2007.\n* McManus, Stuart M. \"Byzantines in the Florentine Polis: Ideology, Statecraft, and Ritual during the Council of Florence.\" ''[[Journal of the Oxford University History Society]]'', 6 (Michaelmas 2008/Hilary 2009).\n* {{cite book | author=Melchert, Norman | title=The Great Conversation: A Historical Introduction to Philosophy | url=https://archive.org/details/greatconversatio00norm | url-access=registration | publisher=McGraw Hill | year=2002 | isbn=978-0-19-517510-3}}\n* Nauert, Charles Garfield. ''Humanism and the Culture of Renaissance Europe (New Approaches to European History).'' Cambridge University Press, 2006.\n* [[John H. Plumb|Plumb, J. H.]] ed.: ''The Italian Renaissance'' 1961, American Heritage, New York, {{ISBN|0-618-12738-0}} (page refs from 1978 UK Penguin edn).\n* [[Roberto Rossellini|Rossellini, Roberto]]. ''The Age of the Medici'': Part 1, ''Cosimo de' Medici''; Part 2, ''Alberti'' 1973.  (Film Series). Criterion Collection.\n* [[John Addington Symonds|Symonds, John Addington]].''The Renaissance in Italy''. Seven Volumes. 1875\u20131886.\n* {{cite book|url=http://xtf.lib.virginia.edu/xtf/view?docId=DicHist/uvaGenText/tei/DicHist4.xml;chunk.id=dv4-20 | contribution = Renaissance Idea of the Dignity of Man | title = Dictionary of the History of Ideas | accessdate=2009-12-02 | last = Trinkaus | first = Charles | editor-last = Wiener | editor-first = Philip P | year = 1973 | ISBN = 978-0-684-13293-8}}\n* Trinkaus, Charles. ''The Scope of Renaissance Humanism''. Ann Arbor: University of Michigan Press, 1983.\n* [[Edgar Wind|Wind, Edgar]]. ''Pagan Mysteries in the Renaissance''. New York: W.W. Norton, 1969.\n* Witt, Ronald. \"In the footsteps of the ancients: the origins of humanism from Lovato to Bruni.\" Leiden: Brill Publishers, 2000\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101102042052/http://globaled.org/nyworld/materials/humanism/H1.html Humanism 1: An Outline by Albert Rabil, Jr.]\n* [https://www.loc.gov/exhibits/vatican/humanism.html \"Rome Reborn: The Vatican Library & Renaissance Culture: Humanism.\" The Library of Congress. 2002-07-01]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p003k9ct Paganism in the Renaissance], BBC Radio 4 discussion with Tom Healy, Charles Hope & Evelyn Welch (''In Our Time'', June 16, 2005)\n\n{{Philosophy topics}}\n{{Middle Ages}}\n\n[[Category:Renaissance humanism| ]]\n[[Category:Medieval philosophy]]\n[[Category:Philosophical movements]]\n[[Category:Renaissance|Humanism]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed cite error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Renaissance_humanism"}
{"title_page": "Ehsan Elahi Zaheer", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious biography|religion=[[Islam]]\n|  region          = \n|  main_interests  = Salafism\n|  era             = Modern era\n|  caption   = \n|  name             = Ehsan Elahi Zaheer  \n|  other_names=Allama, Ihsan Ilahi Zahir; Ehsaan.\n|  image            = \n|  birth_date       =31 May 1945  \n|  birth_place      =Ahmedpura, [[Sialkot]], [[British Raj]], now [[Punjab]], [[Pakistan]] \n|  death_date       =30 March 1987  (aged 41)  \n|  death_place      = [[Riyadh]], [[Saudi Arabia]]\n|  ethnicity        = \n|  school_tradition =  [[Ahl-e-Hadith]]\n|  influences = \n}}\n\n'''Ehsan Elahi Zaheer''' ({{lang-ur|''' \u0627\u062d\u0633\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u06c1\u06cc \u0638\u06c1\u06cc\u0631'''}}) (31 May 1945 \u2013 30 March 1987) was a [[Pakistan]]i [[Islamic theologian]] and leader of the [[Ahl-e-Hadith]] movement.<ref>Ravinder Kaur, Religion, Violence and Political Mobilisation in South Asia, p 153. {{ISBN|0761934308}}</ref><ref name=\"Roy\">Roy, Olivier, ''The Failure of Political Islam'', by Olivier Roy, translated by Carol Volk, Harvard University Press, 1994, p.118-9</ref> He died from an assassin's bomb blast in 1987.\n\n==Early life and education==\nHe was born in 1945 in [[Sialkot]] into a deeply religious trading [[Punjabi people|Punjabi]] family of the [[Sethi]] clan, and he was educated in [[Salafi]] seminaries from [[Gujranwala]] and [[Faisalabad]] before earning [[Masters]] in Arabic, Islamic studies, Urdu and Persian at the [[University of the Punjab]] and further continuing his studies at the [[University of Madinah]] under many scholars, most importantly [[Ibn Baz]].<ref>Mariam Abou Zahab, ''Pakistan: A Kaleidoscope of Islam'', Oxford University Press, 2020, note 19 of chapter 6.</ref> Zaheer will eventually become Ibn Baz's \"star student\", and Saudis would translate his books (written directly in Arabic instead of his native Urdu) and distribute them all over the world at cheap prices.<ref>[[Kim Ghattas]], ''Black Wave: Saudi Arabia, Iran, and the Forty-Year Rivalry That Unraveled Culture, Religion, and Collective Memory in the Middle East'', Henry Holt and Company, 2020, chapter 6.</ref>\n\n==Views==\nZaheer believed that [[Shia Islam|Shi'ites]] were [[State of Israel|Israeli]] agents<ref>{{Cite book|title = Islam in Saudi Arabia|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=GQPhBwAAQBAJ|publisher = I.B.Tauris|date = 2015-03-30|isbn = 9781848858015|language = en|first = David|last = Commins|page = 170}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=January 2020|reason=False information, the citation did not contain the claim made in the previous sentence.}} and infidels.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Militancy and Political Violence in Shiism: Trends and Patterns|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=hiipAgAAQBAJ|publisher = Routledge|date = 2011-07-21|isbn = 9781136663536|language = en|first = Assaf|last = Moghadam|page = 166}}</ref>\n\n==Assassination==\nWhile Zaheer was giving a speech, a bomb which had been planted on the stage exploded, killing him.<ref>Derrick M. Nault, ''Development in Asia: Interdisciplinary, Post-neoliberal, and Transnational Perspectives'', p 184. {{ISBN|1599424886}}</ref>\n\nDue to hi influence, his funerals were held in Saudi Arabia, attended by millions including the country's main Islamic scholars, and he was buried next to [[Imam Malik]].<ref>Imtiaz Alam, ''Religious revivalism in South Asia'', South Asian Policy Analysis Network, 2006, p. 85</ref>\n\n==Family==\nMany of his relatives are involved in the Islamic sciences, including his son Ibtisam Elahi Zaheer, a famous scholar who also leads the [[Jamiat Ahle Hadith]] party he founded,<ref>Kalbe Ali (30 April 2014), [https://www.dawn.com/news/1103234 \"Another side of the story in the missing persons\u2019 saga\"], ''Dawn''. Retrieved 3 April 2020.</ref> while another son, Hisham Elahi Zaheer, is a well-known Islamic scholar as well.\n\n==Works==\n*Al-Qadiyaniyyah, a refutation of Ahmadiyyah (1376 AH)\n*Al-Barelvia,      a refutation of [[Barelvi]]  \n*Al-Babia                                            \n*Alshia wa Tashee a refutation of Shia\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Islamism in South Asia |state=expanded}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zaheer, Ehsan Elahi}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:University of the Punjab alumni]]\n[[Category:Islamic University of Madinah alumni]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Sunni Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:People from Sialkot]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Salafis]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Critics of Shia Islam]]\n[[Category:Ahl-i Hadith]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox religious biography|religion=[[Islam]]\n|  region          = \n|  main_interests  = Salafism\n|  era             = Modern era\n|  caption   = \n|  name             = Ehsan Elahi Zaheer  \n|  other_names=Allama, Ihsan Ilahi Zahir; Ehsaan.\n|  image            = \n|  birth_date       =31 May 1945  \n|  birth_place      =Ahmedpura, [[Sialkot]], [[British Raj]], now [[Punjab]], [[Pakistan]] \n|  death_date       =30 March 1987  (aged 41)  \n|  death_place      = [[Riyadh]], [[Saudi Arabia]]\n|  ethnicity        = \n|  school_tradition =  [[Ahl-e-Hadith]]\n|  influences = \n}}\n\n'''Ehsan Elahi Zaheer''' ({{lang-ur|''' \u0627\u062d\u0633\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u06c1\u06cc \u0638\u06c1\u06cc\u0631'''}}) (31 May 1945 \u2013 30 March 1987) was a [[Pakistan]]i [[Islamic theologian]] and leader of the [[Ahl-e-Hadith]] movement.<ref>Ravinder Kaur, Religion, Violence and Political Mobilisation in South Asia, p 153. {{ISBN|0761934308}}</ref><ref name=\"Roy\">Roy, Olivier, ''The Failure of Political Islam'', by Olivier Roy, translated by Carol Volk, Harvard University Press, 1994, p.118-9</ref> He died from an assassin's bomb blast in 1987.\n\n==Early life and education==\nHe was born in 1945 in [[Sialkot]] into a deeply religious family belonging to a trading [[Punjabi people|Punjabi]] family of the [[Sethi]] clan, and he was educated in [[Salafi]] seminaries from [[Gujranwala]] and [[Faisalabad]] before earning [[Masters]] in Arabic, Islamic studies, Urdu and Persian at the [[University of the Punjab]] and further continuing his studies at the [[University of Madinah]] under many scholars, most importantly [[Ibn Baz]].<ref>Mariam Abou Zahab, ''Pakistan: A Kaleidoscope of Islam'', Oxford University Press, 2020, note 19 of chapter 6.</ref> Zaheer will eventually become Ibn Baz's \"star student\", and Saudis would translate his books (written directly in Arabic instead of his native Urdu) and distribute them all over the world at cheap prices.<ref>[[Kim Ghattas]], ''Black Wave: Saudi Arabia, Iran, and the Forty-Year Rivalry That Unraveled Culture, Religion, and Collective Memory in the Middle East'', Henry Holt and Company, 2020, chapter 6.</ref> \n\n==Views==\nZaheer believed that [[Shia Islam|Shi'ites]] were [[State of Israel|Israeli]] agents<ref>{{Cite book|title = Islam in Saudi Arabia|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=GQPhBwAAQBAJ|publisher = I.B.Tauris|date = 2015-03-30|isbn = 9781848858015|language = en|first = David|last = Commins|page = 170}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=January 2020|reason=False information, the citation did not contain the claim made in the previous sentence.}} and infidels.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Militancy and Political Violence in Shiism: Trends and Patterns|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=hiipAgAAQBAJ|publisher = Routledge|date = 2011-07-21|isbn = 9781136663536|language = en|first = Assaf|last = Moghadam|page = 166}}</ref>\n\n==Assassination==\nWhile Zaheer was giving a speech, a bomb which had been planted on the stage exploded, killing him.<ref>Derrick M. Nault, ''Development in Asia: Interdisciplinary, Post-neoliberal, and Transnational Perspectives'', p 184. {{ISBN|1599424886}}</ref>\n\nDue to hi influence, his funerals were held in Saudi Arabia, attended by millions including the country's main Islamic scholars, and he was buried next to [[Imam Malik]].<ref>Imtiaz Alam, ''Religious revivalism in South Asia'', South Asian Policy Analysis Network, 2006, p. 85</ref>\n\n==Family==\nMany of his relatives are involved in the Islamic sciences, including his son Ibtisam Elahi Zaheer, a famous scholar who also leads the [[Jamiat Ahle Hadith]] party he founded,<ref>Kalbe Ali (30 April 2014), [https://www.dawn.com/news/1103234 \"Another side of the story in the missing persons\u2019 saga\"], ''Dawn''. Retrieved 3 April 2020.</ref> while another son, Hisham Elahi Zaheer, is a well-known Islamic scholar as well.\n\n==Works==\n*Al-Qadiyaniyyah, a refutation of Ahmadiyyah (1376 AH)\n*Al-Barelvia,      a refutation of [[Barelvi]]  \n*Al-Babia                                            \n*Alshia wa Tashee a refutation of Shia\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Islamism in South Asia |state=expanded}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zaheer, Ehsan Elahi}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:University of the Punjab alumni]]\n[[Category:Islamic University of Madinah alumni]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Sunni Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:People from Sialkot]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Salafis]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Critics of Shia Islam]]\n[[Category:Ahl-i Hadith]]\n", "name_user": "Arslan-San", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and education", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ehsan_Elahi_Zaheer"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Macau", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Macau}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{expand Chinese|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Macau\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Macau.svg\n| legend1         = {{center|Map of parishes with confirmed (red) or suspected (blue) coronavirus cases (as of 28 January)}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Macau]]\n| first_case      = \n| arrival_date    = 22 January 2020 \u2013 present <br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=22|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 10\n| deaths          = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 39\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [https://www.ssm.gov.mo/apps1/PreventWuhanInfection/en.aspx Macao Government Special webpage against Epidemics]\n}}\nThe [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] had its first case in [[Macau]] confirmed on 22 January 2020.\n__TOC__\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Macau medical cases chart}}\nOn 22 January 2020, Macau confirmed two COVID-19 cases, that of a 52-year-old woman and of a 66-year-old man, both from [[Wuhan]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/news/20200123/mobile/bkn-20200123095348297-0123_00822_001.html |script-title=zh:\u6fb3\u9580\u78ba\u8a3a\u7b2c2\u5b97\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u3000\u60a3\u8005\u70ba66\u6b72\u7537\u904a\u5ba2 |website= HK |language=zh-hk |date=23 January 2020 |access-date=23 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124014056/https://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/news/20200123/mobile/bkn-20200123095348297-0123_00822_001.html |archive-date=24 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn the morning of 26 January, the [[Macau Health Bureau]] confirmed three additional cases: that of a 58-year-old woman arriving from [[Hong Kong]] on 23 January after travelling to Wuhan, and of two women, aged 21 and 39, both arriving in Macau on 22 January via the [[Lotus Bridge]]; all three were residents of Wuhan. The Macau government has since temporarily closed all schools and universities, and has imposed border controls with temperature checks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://macaunews.mo/government-confirms-5-cases-of-coronavirus-so-far-in-macau/|title=Government confirms 5 cases of coronavirus so far in Macau|date=26 January 2020|website=Macau News|access-date=2020-01-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126102217/https://macaunews.mo/government-confirms-5-cases-of-coronavirus-so-far-in-macau/|archive-date=26 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The government also declared the closing of several venues to limit the possible spread of the virus, including several entertainment venues and planned Lunar New Year performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.asgam.com/index.php/2020/01/28/macau-irs-close-facilities-as-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-reach-seven/|title=Macau IRs close facilities as confirmed Coronavirus cases reach seven|last=|first=|date=28 January 2020|website=Inside Asian Gaming|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129140552/https://www.asgam.com/index.php/2020/01/28/macau-irs-close-facilities-as-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-reach-seven/|archive-date=29 January 2020|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 January, a 15-year-old boy, the son of one of the previously confirmed patients, was declared the sixth case of the virus in Macau.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://macaunews.mo/15-year-old-wuhan-boy-confirmed-as-the-sixth-coronavirus-case-in-macau/|title=15-year-old Wuhan boy confirmed as the sixth coronavirus case in Macau|last=|first=|date=27 January 2020|website=Macau News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129141126/https://macaunews.mo/15-year-old-wuhan-boy-confirmed-as-the-sixth-coronavirus-case-in-macau/|archive-date=29 January 2020|access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref> The next day, the seventh case was announced, that of a 67-year-old woman, a resident of Wuhan who travelled to [[Guangzhou]] before entering Macau through the Barrier Gate checkpoint.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://macaunews.mo/macau-confirms-7th-wuhan-virus-case-in-a-deserted-city/|title=Macau confirms 7th Wuhan virus case in a deserted city|last=|first=|date=28 January 2020|website=Macau News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129150822/https://macaunews.mo/macau-confirms-7th-wuhan-virus-case-in-a-deserted-city/|archive-date=29 January 2020|access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, all 10 confirmed patients with the virus had recovered. According to authorities, however, there are still 224 people in isolation, 6 in quarantine, and 58 Macau residents who have been to South Korea and Italy also isolated.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://macaunews.mo/no-more-covid-19-cases-in-macau/ |title=No more COVID-19 cases in Macau |work=Macau News |date=6 March 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 March, the Philippines announced that an airlift operation will be launched to bring home 167 Filipinos working in Macau.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/7/macau-evacuees-go-home-march-7.html |title = 163 stranded Filipinos from Macau arrive home |work=CNN Philippines}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, the city registered a new COVID-19 case imported from Portugal, the first new case in over a month. The patient is a Korean migrant worker who visited her boyfriend's family in the city of [[Porto]].\nThe woman departed Macau on January 30. She flew back to Hong Kong from Dubai on March 13 on flight number EK380, taking seat 31J.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://macaunews.mo/macau-recorded-the-11th-case-of-covid-19/ |title=Macau records its 11th case of COVID-19 &#124; Macau News |publisher=Macaunews.mo |date=2020-03-16 |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref> She returned to Macau on the same day via the [[Hong Kong-Zhuhai-Macau Bridge]]. Later in the day she started experiencing coughing and went to the hospital on Sunday afternoon, March 15, with fever.\n\nOn 17 March, two new cases were reported. The first patient, a 47-year-old male, is a Spanish national doing business in Macau; he took the SU2501 flight from Madrid to Moscow on March 15, and then the SU204 flight from Moscow to Beijing. On 16 March, he took the NX001 flight from Beijing to Macau, arriving at Macau Airport at 8:00 pm of the same day. The second patient is a 20-year-old woman, a Macau resident who was studying in the United Kingdom. The patient left London and arrived at the [[Hong Kong International Airport]] via Kuala Lumpur on the night of March 16. Upon arrival at the [[Hong Kong-Zhuhai-Macau Bridge]], she was detected to have a fever and was immediately taken to the hospital. Further testing revealed she was infected with the novel coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tdm.com.mo/c_news/radio_news.php?id=460383 |title=\u96fb\u53f0\u65b0\u805e>\u672c\u6fb3\u4eca\u65e5\u78ba\u8a3a2\u5b97\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e(2020.03.17 19:47) |publisher=Tdm.com.mo |date=2020-03-17 |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the [[Education and Youth Affairs Bureau (Macau)|Education and Youth Affairs Bureau]] announced the re-postponement of its plans to resume primary and secondary education as a response to the second wave of COVID-19 cases beginning with the 11th case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/en/N20CS1PR97?keyword=%E9%9D%9E%E9%AB%98%E7%AD%89%E6%95%99%E8%82%B2|title=NEWS.GOV.MO: Class resumption for non-tertiary education schools will be postponed until further notice|website=news.gov.mo}}</ref> This is after the bureau's class resumption plans starting on 30 March, announced on 11 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/en/N20CJOAuRT|title=NEWS.GOV.MO: DSEJ formulates a plan for class resumption of non-tertiary education schools|website=news.gov.mo}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, the government of neighbouring [[Zhuhai]] announced that anyone returning or travelling from outside Mainland China (including Macau and Hong Kong) would undergo mandatory 14-day quarantine with a few exceptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20CaKhyeq|title=NEWS.GOV.MO: \u3010\u5716\u6587\u5305\u3011\u51fa\u5165\u5883\u8c41\u514d\u60c5\u6cc1\u548c\u51fa\u5165\u5883\u7279\u5225\u624b\u7e8c|website=news.gov.mo}}</ref> This caused large crowds and chaos at the [[L\u00f3tus Bridge|Lotus Checkpoint]] in [[Cotai]], which was the only border checkpoint open at the time.\n\n==Response and impact==\n\n===December 2019===\n\nOn 31 December 2019, the Health Bureau was notified by the [[National Health Commission]] of an outbreak of pneumonia of unknown cause in [[Wuhan]]. Residents were asked to avoid excessive panic but to be conscious of personal hygiene and the hygiene of their environment. Those traveling to Wuhan were advised to avoid visiting local hospitals or having contact with sick people.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u885b\u751f\u5c40\u63a5\u570b\u5bb6\u885b\u5065\u59d4\u901a\u5831\u6b66\u6f22\u4e0d\u660e\u539f\u56e0\u80ba\u708e \u5df2\u6709\u6a5f\u5236\u76e3\u6e2c\u53ca\u61c9\u5c0d\u5e02\u6c11\u6bcb\u9808\u904e\u5206\u6050\u614c |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/312595/ |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u885b\u751f\u5c40 |language=zh-tw |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207071843/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AAECxlQ;jsessionid=9665DE00A598BF844DDF6A08E7161D73.app02?0 |archivedate=2019-12-31 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===January 2020===\n\nOn 1 January 2020, the Macao Health Bureau asked [[Macau International Airport]] to implement body temperature screening for all passengers on flights coming from Wuhan.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u4eca\u5929\u8d77\u5c0d\u4f86\u81ea\u6b66\u6f22\u822a\u73ed\u4e58\u5ba2\u9032\u884c\u9ad4\u6e29\u7be9\u67e5 \u885b\u751f\u5c40\u8207\u570b\u5bb6\u885b\u751f\u5065\u5eb7\u59d4\u54e1\u4fdd\u6301\u5bc6\u5207\u806f\u7e6b |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AAECxlQ |accessdate=2020-01-02 |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u885b\u751f\u5c40 |language=zh-tw |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207071843/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AAECxlQ;jsessionid=9665DE00A598BF844DDF6A08E7161D73.app02?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref> Starting 5 January, the Health Bureau raised the pneumonia warning level to 3, medium risk, and on the same day established the \"Interdepartmental Working Group Against Pneumonia of Unknown Cause\" (\u61c9\u5c0d\u4e0d\u660e\u539f\u56e0\u80ba\u708e\u8de8\u90e8\u9580\u5de5\u4f5c\u5c0f\u7d44).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AEUUwwZ |title=\u7279\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u63d0\u6607\u5c0d\"\u6b66\u6f22\u4e0d\u660e\u539f\u56e0\u80ba\u708e\"\u7684\u9810\u8b66\u7d1a\u5225\u81f3\u7b2cIII\u7d1a(\u8f03\u91cd) \u885b\u751f\u5c40\u547c\u7c72\u5e02\u6c11\u63d0\u9ad8\u9632\u7bc4\u610f\u8b58 |date=2020-01-05 |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u885b\u751f\u5c40 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207072051/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AEUUwwZ;jsessionid=2C12CEB2F0CA4908E13CF5B20217344E.app01?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live |access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n\nStarting January 10, people bought large quantities of masks, leading to shortages in some pharmacies. ''[[Macao Daily News]]'' reported that, according to the Health Bureau, the city's supply of masks was sufficient.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.macaodaily.com/html/2020-01/10/content_1408320.htm |title=\u53e3\u7f69\u5145\u8db3\u6bcb\u6050\u614c \u61c9\u5c0d\u80ba\u708e\u53ca\u65e9\u9632 |date=2020-01-10 |newspaper=\u6fb3\u95e8\u65e5\u62a5 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207072757/http://www.macaodaily.com/html/2020-01/10/content_1408320.htm |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live |language=zh}}</ref> On the day that the first case in Macau was confirmed, the Health Bureau announced at a press conference that starting in the evening of January 23, Macau residents and foreign workers could use [[Macau Resident Identity Card]]s and foreign worker identity cards respectively to purchase up to 10 masks per person every 10 days. Director of the Health Bureau Li Zhanrun (\u674e\u5c55\u6f64) said that out of 294 pharmacies in Macau, 160 did not have masks and that out of eight mask suppliers, one had 150,000 masks remaining in stock whereas the others were out of stock.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AVJspef |title=\u885b\u751f\u5c40\u5c07\u63a8\u51fa\u4fdd\u969c\u53e3\u7f69\u4f9b\u61c9\u6fb3\u9580\u5c45\u6c11\u8a08\u5283 \u78ba\u4fdd\u5c45\u6c11\u53ef\u8cfc\u8cb7\u5230\u6240\u9700\u53e3\u7f69 |date=2020-01-22 |newspaper=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207073025/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AVJspef;jsessionid=4EE7B5BEBF6A13FA624B6707AA84E3F1.app01?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live |language=zh}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 January, [[Chief Executive of Macau|Chief Executive]] [[Ho Iat Seng]] ordered the establishment of a 24-hour \"Novel Coronavirus Emergency Coordination Center\", replacing the \"Interdepartmental Working Group Against Pneumonia of Unknown Cause\", to operate directly under the chief executive, with Secretary for Social Affairs and Culture as vice chair.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AUAWxeo |title=\u7279\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u63d0\u6607\u5c0d\"\u6b66\u6f22\u4e0d\u660e\u539f\u56e0\u80ba\u708e\"\u7684\u9810\u8b66\u7d1a\u5225\u81f3\u7b2cIII\u7d1a(\u8f03\u91cd) \u885b\u751f\u5c40\u547c\u7c72\u5e02\u6c11\u63d0\u9ad8\u9632\u7bc4\u610f\u8b58 |date=2020-01-21 |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u885b\u751f\u5c40 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207072247/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AUAWxeo;jsessionid=90528C1EE65EC09E19A413B749F04296.app01?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live |access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u5370\u52d9\u5c40 - \u884c\u653f\u9577\u5b98\u6279\u793a |url=https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/03/despce_cn.asp |accessdate=2020-02-01 |work=bo.io.gov.mo |publisher=\u5370\u52d9\u5c40 |language=zh-Hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201091940/https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/03/despce_cn.asp |archivedate=2020-02-01 |url-status=live}}</ref> In response to the city's first imported case, steps were taken, including: border control points implemented health declarations,<ref>{{cite web |title=\u3010\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u3011\u6fb3\u9580\u6240\u6709\u53e3\u5cb8\u5be6\u65bd\u5065\u5eb7\u7533\u5831 \u4e58\u91d1\u5df4\u5165\u5883\u9808\u586b\u8868 |url=https://std.stheadline.com/instant/articles/detail/1186708/ |accessdate=2020-01-23 |date=2020-01-22 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207072444/https://std.stheadline.com/instant/articles/detail/1186708/%E5%8D%B3%E6%99%82-%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF-%E6%AD%A6%E6%BC%A2%E8%82%BA%E7%82%8E-%E6%BE%B3%E9%96%80%E6%89%80%E6%9C%89%E5%8F%A3%E5%B2%B8%E5%AF%A6%E6%96%BD%E5%81%A5%E5%BA%B7%E7%94%B3%E5%A0%B1-%E4%B9%98%E9%87%91%E5%B7%B4%E5%85%A5%E5%A2%83%E9%A0%88%E5%A1%AB%E8%A1%A8 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live |website=\u661f\u5cf6\u65e5\u5831}}</ref> resort workers had to wear masks, Macau residents were not encouraged to travel to Wuhan, and tour groups between Wuhan and Macau were suspended.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u653f\u5e9c\u5168\u529b\u61c9\u5c0d\u52a0\u5f37\u9632\u63a7\u75ab\u60c5 |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/314827/ |accessdate=2020-01-23 |date=2020-01-22 |language=zh-hant |url-status=live |author1=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3 |website=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124152435/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/314827/ |archive-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u6fb3\u958011\u65e5\u7121\u78ba\u8a3a \u4f55\u6822\u826f\uff1a\u63a7\u75ab\u52dd\u6e2f \u7a31\u627e\u51fa\u6e56\u5317\u5ba2\u95dc\u9375 \u65e9\u5207\u65b7\u96b1\u5f62\u50b3\u64ad\u93c8|url=https://m.mingpao.com/pns/%E8%A6%81%E8%81%9E/article/20200216/s00001/1581789946951/%E6%BE%B3%E9%96%8011%E6%97%A5%E7%84%A1%E7%A2%BA%E8%A8%BA-%E4%BD%95%E6%A0%A2%E8%89%AF-%E6%8E%A7%E7%96%AB%E5%8B%9D%E6%B8%AF-%E7%A8%B1%E6%89%BE%E5%87%BA%E6%B9%96%E5%8C%97%E5%AE%A2%E9%97%9C%E9%8D%B5-%E6%97%A9%E5%88%87%E6%96%B7%E9%9A%B1%E5%BD%A2%E5%82%B3%E6%92%AD%E9%8F%88|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217151832/https://m.mingpao.com/pns/%E8%A6%81%E8%81%9E/article/20200216/s00001/1581789946951/%E6%BE%B3%E9%96%8011%E6%97%A5%E7%84%A1%E7%A2%BA%E8%A8%BA-%E4%BD%95%E6%A0%A2%E8%89%AF-%E6%8E%A7%E7%96%AB%E5%8B%9D%E6%B8%AF-%E7%A8%B1%E6%89%BE%E5%87%BA%E6%B9%96%E5%8C%97%E5%AE%A2%E9%97%9C%E9%8D%B5-%E6%97%A9%E5%88%87%E6%96%B7%E9%9A%B1%E5%BD%A2%E5%82%B3%E6%92%AD%E9%8F%88|archivedate=2020-02-17|accessdate=2020-02-17|date=2020-02-17|work=\u660e\u5831}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January, Macau confirmed its second imported case, leading the Government Tourism Office to cancel all Chinese New Year celebrations, including the Macau Chinese New Year Parade.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AW8tgPg |title=\u653f\u5e9c\u53d6\u6d88\u65b0\u6625\u5927\u578b\u516c\u773e\u6d3b\u52d5\u3000\u964d\u4f4e\u50b3\u67d3\u75c5\u50b3\u64ad\u98a8\u96aa |date=2020-01-23 |publisher=\u6fb3\u9580\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207073332/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AW8tgPg;jsessionid=66F89CB747B12058FF7648786127368F.app02?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day, Ho Iat Seng announced that anyone with fever symptoms should not leave Macau. On January 23, Ho Iat Seng announced that Macau had ordered 20 million masks to sell to Macau residents and foreign workers at cost.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AWOxBz2 |title=\u884c\u653f\u9577\u5b98\uff1a\u52a0\u5f37\u9632\u63a7 \u5b89\u5ea6\u6625\u7bc0 |date=2020-01-23 |publisher=\u6fb3\u9580\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207073530/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AWOxBz2;jsessionid=DAA9C5B9204BB1D2539118C50E12066B.app03?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref> The Correctional Services Authority announced precautions against the virus.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u61f2\u6559\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40\u5be6\u65bd\u9810\u9632\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u7684\u63aa\u65bd|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/314975/|accessdate=2020-03-28|author=\u61f2\u6559\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40|date=2020-01-23|authorlink=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u61f2\u6559\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328051859/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/314975/|archivedate=2020-03-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January, the [[Education and Youth Affairs Bureau (Macau)|Education and Youth Affairs Bureau]] announced that all non-tertiary schools would extend their Chinese New Year holiday, not resuming classes until February 10 or later. The bureau also asked other private tutoring and continuing education centers to delay the resumption of classes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/20200124/K3HGL5C4TWLPPTKT6JEXUYQM5M/ |title=\u3010\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u3011\u6fb3\u9580\u5ba3\u4f48\u4e2d\u5c0f\u5b78\u65b0\u5e74\u5047\u5f8c\u5ef6\u671f\u4e0a\u8ab2 \u7c72\u6821\u5b89\u6392\u5b78\u751f\u7559\u5bb6\u5b78\u7fd2 |date=2020-01-24 |work=\u860b\u679c\u65e5\u5831 |url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day, the Tertiary Education Bureau also announced that ten tertiary institutions would delay classes until February 11.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u6fb3\u9580\u5341\u9ad8\u6821\u5ef6\u5f8c\u81f32\u670811\u65e5\u958b\u5b78-\u9ad8\u7b49\u6559\u80b2\u5c40|url=https://www.dses.gov.mo/news/5162-2020-01-24|accessdate=2020-01-26|author=dses.gov.mo|date=2020-01-24|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126024001/https://www.dses.gov.mo/news/5162-2020-01-24|archive-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> The Sports Bureau later announced that sporting facilities would be closed from that afternoon (24 January) at 4PM.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u9ad4\u80b2\u5c40\u8f44\u4e0b\u9ad4\u80b2\u8a2d\u65bd\u4eca\u5348\u56db\u6642\u8d77\u66ab\u505c\u958b\u653e|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/315058/|accessdate=2020-03-10|author=\u9ad4\u80b2\u5c40|date=2020-01-24|authorlink=\u9ad4\u80b2\u5c40 (\u6fb3\u9580)|format=|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310135821/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/315058/|archivedate=2020-03-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 January, the government of Macau announced that the opening hours at the [[Posto Fronteiri\u00e7o das Portas do Cerco|Portas do Cerco border crossing]] with [[Zhuhai]] would be reduced by three hours, to 6AM\u201310PM, until further notice. Opening hours at other border crossings with Zhuhai and Hong Kong would not be affected for the time being.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/ch/component/k2/1504833-20200125.htm?archive_date=2020-01-25 |title=\u6fb3\u9580\u5ba3\u5e03\u95dc\u9598\u62f1\u5317\u53e3\u5cb8\u4eba\u8eca\u901a\u95dc\u6642\u9593\u7e2e\u77ed3\u5c0f\u6642 |date=2020-01-25 |work=\u9999\u6e2f\u96fb\u53f0 |url-status=live |access-date=2020-01-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125145402/https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/ch/component/k2/1504833-20200125.htm%3Farchive_date%3D2020-01-25 |archive-date=2020-01-25 |language=zh}}</ref> On the same day, the Macau government announced that they would donate 50,000 urgently needed medical masks to the city of Zhuhai, to be used for the prevention and treatment of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u62f1\u5317\u6d77\u5173\u5feb\u901f\u9a8c\u653e\u6fb3\u95e8\u6350\u8d60\u73e0\u6d775\u4e07\u4e2a\u533b\u7528\u53e3\u7f69 |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/2020-01/25/c_1125501932.htm |url-status=live |agency=\u65b0\u534e\u7f51 |access-date=2020-01-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126113849/http://www.xinhuanet.com/2020-01/25/c_1125501932.htm |archive-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 January, the government announced that starting on the 27th, all non-residents who were from or had been to Hubei in the past 14 days were required to have a doctor's note certifying that they did not have the virus in order to be allowed into Macau. In addition, anyone who had been to Hubei in the past 14 days was prohibited from entering casinos.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AaeveUQ |title=\u9650\u5236\u5165\u5883\u6fb3\u9580\u524d14\u65e5\u5167\u66fe\u5230\u6e56\u5317\u7701\u4eba\u58eb\u9032\u5165\u5a1b\u6a02\u5834 |date=2020-01-27 |publisher=\u535a\u5f69\u76e3\u5bdf\u5354\u8abf\u5c40 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207073832/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AaeveUQ;jsessionid=6586AFC3DEF51B5F887875E59B51BAC7.app02?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref> That evening the government of Macau announced that starting at 9AM on the 27th, the 1,113 travelers from Hubei who had entered Macau between December 1 and January 26 and remained in the territory would be quarantined.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20Aa8HHeL |title=\u6cbb\u5b89\u8b66\u7a4d\u6975\u914d\u5408\u7279\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u9632\u75ab\u5de5\u4f5c |date=2020-01-27 |publisher=\u6cbb\u5b89\u8b66\u5bdf\u5c40 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207074009/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20Aa8HHeL;jsessionid=ACBA16C393CFB50B3763BD3BD8A14BAD.app01?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 January, [[Secretariat for Administration and Justice (Macau)|Secretary for Administration and Justice]] Zhang Yongchun (\u5f35\u6c38\u6625) said that in accordance with the decision of the central government, endorsements for mainland Chinese visitors to Macau would be suspended.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nia.gov.cn/n741440/n741542/c1214127/content.html |title=\u56fd\u5bb6\u79fb\u6c11\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40\u6682\u505c\u529e\u7406\u5185\u5730\u5c45\u6c11\u5f80\u6765\u6e2f\u6fb3\u5730\u533a\u65c5\u6e38\u7b7e\u6ce8 |work=\u56fd\u5bb6\u79fb\u6c11\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40 |language=zh-hk |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207074151/https://www.nia.gov.cn/n741440/n741542/c1214127/content.html |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 January, the Tertiary Education Bureau accounced that the resumption of classes would be delayed further, and that a schedule for resuming classes would be released one week before classes were to resume.<ref name=\":18\">{{cite web |title=\u672c\u6fb3\u6240\u6709\u5927\u5c08\u3001\u975e\u9ad8\u7b49\u6559\u80b2\u6a5f\u69cb\u53ca\u79c1\u7acb\u88dc\u5145\u6559\u5b78\u8f14\u52a9\u4e2d\u5fc3\u5ef6\u9072\u958b\u8ab2\u81f3\u53e6\u884c\u516c\u4f48 |url=https://www.dses.gov.mo/news/5179-2020-01-30 |accessdate=2020-01-31 |author=dses.gov.mo |date=2020-01-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207074315/https://www.dses.gov.mo/news/5179-2020-01-30 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===February 2020===\nOn 3 February, the government of Macau announced that starting at noon, all bus and taxi passengers were required to wear wear masks; otherwise the driver would have the right to refuse boarding.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u4e58\u5ba2\u9808\u4f69\u6234\u53e3\u7f69\u65b9\u53ef\u4e58\u642d\u5df4\u58eb |url=https://www.dsat.gov.mo/dsat/news_detail.aspx?a_id=5FE497B2F8060898A9BBA44F10244BA6 |accessdate=2020-02-03 |date=2020-02-03 |language=zh-mo |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207074557/https://www.dsat.gov.mo/dsat/news_detail.aspx?a_id=5FE497B2F8060898A9BBA44F10244BA6 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live |author1=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u4ea4\u901a\u4e8b\u52d9\u5c40}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u4e58\u5ba2\u9808\u4f69\u6234\u53e3\u7f69\u65b9\u53ef\u4e58\u642d\u7684\u58eb |url=https://www.dsat.gov.mo/dsat/news_detail.aspx?a_id=074A4495F12B6EFE7C84E7B30431AF15 |accessdate=2020-02-03 |date=2020-02-03 |language=zh-mo |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207074655/https://www.dsat.gov.mo/dsat/news_detail.aspx?a_id=074A4495F12B6EFE7C84E7B30431AF15 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live |author1=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u4ea4\u901a\u4e8b\u52d9\u5c40}}</ref> Starting at 13:00, all light rail passengers were required to wear a mask; otherwise the driver would have the right to refuse boarding.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |title=NEWS.GOV.MO: \uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u9632\u75ab\u63aa\u65bd\uff09\uff0d |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20BCzi7H3 |accessdate=2020-02-09 |author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |date=2020-02-03 |work=news.gov.mo |publisher=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |language=zh-Hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209075337/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20BCzi7H3;jsessionid=EA578917F150E31435A7327F15BF9B8B.app01?0 |archivedate=2020-02-09 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 February 2020, all [[casino]]s in Macau were ordered to shut down for 15 days.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stevenson |first=Alexandra |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/04/business/coronavirus-macau-gambling.html |title=Coronavirus Shuts Macau, the World's Gambling Capital |date=4 February 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204121004/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/04/business/coronavirus-macau-gambling.html |archive-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Yang |first=Joyu Wang and Jing |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/deadly-coronavirus-forces-chinas-gambling-hub-to-shut-its-casinos-11580816447 |title=Coronavirus: Bad Luck Hits Macau Casinos With 15-Day Shutdown |date=4 February 2020 |work=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=4 February 2020 |issn=0099-9660 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206113014/https://www.wsj.com/articles/deadly-coronavirus-forces-chinas-gambling-hub-to-shut-its-casinos-11580816447 |archive-date=6 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The following facilities were also required to close: cinemas, theatres, indoor amusement parks, arcades, internet cafes, pool halls, bowling alleys, steam baths, massage parlours, beauty salons, gyms, health clubs, bars, karaoke bars, nightclubs, discos, and dance clubs.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u5370\u52d9\u5c40 - \u884c\u653f\u9577\u5b98\u6279\u793a |url=https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/05/despce_cn.asp |accessdate=2020-02-08 |author=\u884c\u653f\u9577\u5b98 \u8cc0\u4e00\u8aa0 |date=2020-02-04 |work=bo.io.gov.mo |publisher=\u5370\u52d9\u5c40 |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204112701/https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/05/despce_cn.asp |archivedate=2020-02-04 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 7, the government of Macau announced that government workers were to stay home from the 8th to the 16th, except for emergency services.<ref>{{cite web |title=NEWS.GOV.MO: \u516c\u52d9\u4eba\u54e1\u56e0\u9632\u75ab\u9700\u89818\u81f316\u865f\u514d\u9664\u4e0a\u73ed |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20BGROZbm |accessdate=2020-02-07 |author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |date=2020-02-07 |work=news.gov.mo |publisher=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207115559/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20BGROZbm;jsessionid=2ABAEBA2B2217366ECACFAFBEE4717F1.app01?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 February, at the daily press conference, the government announced the third face mask safeguarding plan and provided masks for children for the first time, but due to limited quantities, each child was only permitted to buy five.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite web |title=\u660e\u5929\u8d77\u6709\u5152\u7ae5\u53e3\u7f69\u4f9b\u61c9 |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/317960/ |accessdate=2020-02-11 |author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |date=2020-02-11 |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211135351/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/317960/ |archivedate=2020-02-11 |url-status=live}}</ref> The government also announced that testing would begin for groups at high risk of infection, and that the highest-risk group was tour bus drivers, of which 103 were to be tested that day.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web |title=\uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u64f4\u5927\u6aa2\u6e2c\u7bc4\u570d \u5b89\u6392\u65c5\u904a\u5df4\u53f8\u6a5f\u6aa2\u6e2c\uff09\uff0d |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/317900/ |accessdate=2020-02-11 |author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |date=2020-02-11 |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211135342/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/317900/ |archivedate=2020-02-11 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 February the government announced economic relief measures, including: (1) reduction of taxes and fees to relieve the burden on businesses and residents; (2) assistance to small and medium enterprises and interest subsidies, to support the continued existence of enterprises; (3) measures to enhance people's livelihoods and support vulnerable families; (4) technical training, providing work, and protecting wages; (5) putting out electronic coupons to accelerate economic recovery.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |title=\u7d13\u89e3\u6c11\u56f0\u3001\u5171\u6e21\u6642\u8271 |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/318146/ |accessdate=2020-02-14 |author=\u7d93\u6fdf\u8ca1\u653f\u53f8\u53f8\u9577\u8fa6\u516c\u5ba4 |date=2020-02-13 |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214125602/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/318146/ |archivedate=2020-02-14 |url-status=live}}</ref> The government also announced that it would cooperate with a local research team in Macau to establish production lines in the mainland and safeguard the supply of face masks.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |title=\u7279\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u63a8\u591a\u9805\u7d93\u6fdf\u63f4\u52a9\u63aa\u65bd \u6297\u75ab\u5de5\u4f5c\u521d\u898b\u6210\u6548 \u547c\u7c72\u5e02\u6c11\u5805\u6301\u9632\u75ab\u52ff\u9b06\u61c8 |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/318253/ |accessdate=2020-02-15 |author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3 |date=2020-02-13 |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215114456/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/318253/ |archivedate=2020-02-15 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, the government announced that, after balancing epidemic prevention with citizens' need for public services, starting 17 February, basic public services would be restored.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u516c\u5171\u90e8\u9580\u4e0b\u5468\u4e00\u8d77\u50c5\u7dad\u6301\u57fa\u672c\u670d\u52d9 \u2013 \u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/318287/ |accessdate=2020-02-14 |author=\u884c\u653f\u6cd5\u52d9\u53f8\u53f8\u9577\u8fa6\u516c\u5ba4 |date=2020-02-14 |work=web.archive.org |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214105827/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/318287/ |archivedate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 February, the government announced that effective 20 February, casinos could reopen but other entertainment facilities such as cinemas and bars were to remain closed. The government also announced that migrant workers entering Macau who had been to mainland China in the past 14 days would need to undergo 14 days of medical observation at a designated location in [[Zhuhai]].<ref name=\":16\">{{cite web|title=\u5370\u52d9\u5c40 - \u884c\u653f\u9577\u5b98\u6279\u793a|url=https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/07/despce_cn.asp|accessdate=2020-02-17|author=|date=|format=|work=bo.io.gov.mo|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217090424/https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/07/despce_cn.asp|archivedate=2020-02-17|url-status=live|quote=}}</ref> At a press conference, the [[Secretariat for Economy and Finance (Macau)|Secretary for Economy and Finance]] Lei Wai Nong (\u674e\u5049\u8fb2) mentioned that when casinos reopened, they would have to follow government measures in order to protect employee and guest safety. If casinos were unable to prepare adequately for reopening, they could apply to delay reopening for up to 30 days.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u674e\u5049\u8fb2\uff1a\u614e\u91cd\u8655\u7406\u5a1b\u6a02\u5834\u91cd\u958b\u7684\u5f8c\u7e8c\u5de5\u4f5c|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319128/|accessdate=2020-02-17|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-17|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217130429/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319128/|archivedate=2020-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 February, due to the global face mask shortage, the government began providing masks with ties instead of ear straps.<ref name=\":17\">{{cite web|title=\uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u7d81\u5e36\u5f0f\u6216\u639b\u8033\u5f0f\u53e3\u7f69\u7684\u9632\u8b77\u6548\u80fd\u76f8\u540c\uff09\uff0d|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319228/|accessdate=2020-02-18|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-18|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218112834/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319228/|archivedate=2020-02-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 February, the government announced that effective 20 February, passengers coming from COVID-19 hotspots would need to undergo medical checks upon entering Macau. Medical checks might also be conducted on Macau residents who made multiple trips back and forth to Zhuhai every day. It was also announced that some parks would reopen and government broadcasts would be adjusted.<ref name=\":21\">{{cite web|title=\uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u653f\u5e9c\u8abf\u6574\u9632\u75ab\u63aa\u65bd\uff09\uff0d|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319322/|accessdate=2020-02-19|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-19|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219102214/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319322/|archivedate=2020-02-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAll casinos reopened on 20 February 2020,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/3051571/macau-casinos-reopen-after-coronavirus-shutdown-gamblers-keep-their|title=Gamblers hedge their bets as Macau casinos reopen to small crowds|date=2020-02-20|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> but visitor numbers remained low due to the pandemic, with hotels at less than 12% occupancy at the end of February.<ref name=\"88 percent\">{{cite news |last1=Sullivan |first1=Lewis |title=Macau\u2019s gaming revenue fell 88 percent in February |url=https://www.casino-review.co/macau-gaming-revenue/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=Casino Review}}</ref> Macau's casinos suffered a year-on-year revenue drop of 88% during February 2020, the worst ever recorded.<ref name=\"88 percent\"/>\n\nStarting on February 20, the government of Macau restricted entry from mainland China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Macau considering easing of entry restrictions from mainland China |url=https://www.asgam.com/index.php/2020/03/12/macau-considering-easing-of-entry-restrictions-from-mainland-china/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=IAG |date=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 February, the government announced that the following week, 24\u201328 February, the public sector would still provide basic services.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u516c\u5171\u90e8\u9580\u4e0b\u5468\u7e7c\u7e8c\u7dad\u6301\u57fa\u672c\u670d\u52d9|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319529/|accessdate=2020-02-21|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-21|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221114529/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319529/|archivedate=2020-02-21|url-status=live}}</ref> The fourth face mask safeguarding plan would begin the following day, 22 February.<ref>{{cite web|title=\uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u7b2c\u56db\u8f2a\u4fdd\u969c\u53e3\u7f69\u4f9b\u61c9\u8a08\u5283\u660e\u5c55\u958b\uff09\uff0d|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319573/|accessdate=2020-02-21|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-21|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221115412/http://web.archive.org/screenshot/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319573/|archivedate=2020-02-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 February, the Health Bureau announced that people entering Macau who had been to South Korea in the past 14 days would be required to undergo 14 days of medical observation.<ref name=\":22\">{{cite web|title=NEWS.GOV.MO: \u81ea\u660e\uff0826\uff09\u65e5\u4e2d\u5348\u8d77\u66fe\u5230\u97d3\u570b\u7684\u4eba\u58eb \u9700\u63a5\u53d714\u5929\u7684\u9694\u96e2\u91ab\u5b78\u89c0\u5bdf|url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20BYhxp2c|accessdate=2020-02-25|author=\u885b\u751f\u5c40|date=2020-02-25|work=news.gov.mo|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225154838/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20BYhxp2c;jsessionid=32474981D8F273844A20ADDCC779360E.app03?0|archivedate=2020-02-25|url-status=live}}</ref> The Maritime and Water Bureau announced that the opening hours of the [[Outer Harbour Ferry Terminal]] and [[Taipa Ferry Terminal]] would be changed to 07:00\u201320:00 until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|title=NEWS.GOV.MO: \u5916\u6e2f\u8207\u6c39\u4ed4\u5ba2\u904b\u78bc\u982d\u8abf\u6574\u958b\u653e\u6642\u9593|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320394/|accessdate=2020-02-25|author=\u6d77\u4e8b\u53ca\u6c34\u52d9\u5c40|date=2020-02-25|work=news.gov.mo|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225154838/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320394/;jsessionid=32474981D8F273844A20ADDCC779360E.app03?0|archivedate=2020-02-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February,<ref>{{cite web|title=\u5370\u52d9\u5c40 - \u884c\u653f\u9577\u5b98\u6279\u793a|url=https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/08/despce_cn.asp#50|accessdate=2020-02-27|author=|date=2020-02-27|work=bo.io.gov.mo|publisher=|language=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227083042/https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/08/despce_cn.asp#50|archivedate=2020-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref> the other venues that had been closed on 5 February along with the casinos were permitted to reopen. However, the government of Macau recommended that they implement epidemic control measures; if an outbreak occurred in such a place, they would require site control measures in accordance with Article 19 of the Infectious Disease Prevention Law.<ref>{{cite web|title=\uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u5c07\u89e3\u9664\u7f8e\u5bb9\u9662\u7b49\u5834\u6240\u7684\u95dc\u9589\u4ee4\uff09\uff0d|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320478/|accessdate=2020-02-27|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-27|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227104957/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320478/|archivedate=2020-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref> The government of Macau announced that effective 2 March, public services would return to normal.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u516c\u5171\u90e8\u9580\u4e0b\u5468\u4e00\u8d77\u6062\u5fa9\u6b63\u5e38\u8fa6\u516c|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320518/|accessdate=2020-02-27|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-27|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227110408/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320518/|archivedate=2020-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref> Private tutoring and continuing education institutions that meet health guidelines could also resume operations.<ref>{{cite web|title=\uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u88dc\u7fd2\u793e\u7b49\u65bc3\u67082\u65e5\u8d77\u5206\u6279\u5206\u968e\u6bb5\u6062\u5fa9\u904b\u4f5c\uff09\uff0d|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320488/|accessdate=2020-02-27|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-27|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227110903/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320488/|archivedate=2020-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref> The Education Bureau announced that, subject to the conditions that Macau and [[Guangdong Province]] had no new confirmed cases for 14 consecutive days and Macau schools did not resume classes before Zhuhai and [[Zhongshan]], it would be possible to announce the resumption of classes at non-tertiary schools.<ref name=\":27\">{{cite web|title=\uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u8a02\u5b9a\u975e\u9ad8\u7b49\u6559\u80b2\u5fa9\u8ab2\u65e5\u7684\u539f\u5247\uff09\uff0d|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320473/|accessdate=2020-02-27|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-27|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227111610/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320473/|archivedate=2020-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref> The Correctional Services Authority announced that visiting services would partially resume on 4 March.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u61f2\u6559\u7ba1\u7406\u5c403\u67084\u65e5\u8d77\u5c40\u90e8\u6062\u5fa9\u63a2\u8a2a\u670d\u52d9|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320757/|accessdate=2020-03-28|author=\u61f2\u6559\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40|date=2020-02-28|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328052149/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320757/|archivedate=2020-03-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 February, it was announced that passengers who had been to Italy or Iran in the past 14 days would need to undergo 14 days of medical observation in isolation. Macau residents would be permitted to undergo medical observation at a home location deemed appropriate by authorities.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u81ea\u4eca\uff0829\uff09\u65e5\u4e2d\u5348\u8d77\u66fe\u5230\u610f\u5927\u5229\u6216\u4f0a\u6717\u7684\u5165\u5883\u4eba\u58eb\u9808\u63a5\u53d714\u5929\u7684\u9694\u96e2\u91ab\u5b78\u89c0\u5bdf|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320881/|accessdate=2020-02-29|author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=2020-02-29|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229112717/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320881/|archivedate=2020-02-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\n\nOn 8 March it was announced that starting at noon the same day, people entering Macau who had been to Germany, France, Spain, or Japan in the past 14 days would need to undergo a health check. In addition, starting 10 March at noon, passengers coming from those locations would need to undergo 14 days of isolation and medical observation at a designated location. Macau residents would be permitted to undergo medical observation at an approved home location.<ref name=\":29\">{{Cite web|title=\u672c\u6fb3\u5206\u5225\u81ea\u4eca\u65e5\u53ca\u4e0b\u5468\u4e8c\u4e2d\u5348\u8d77\u5c0d\u66fe\u5230\u5fb7\u570b\u3001\u6cd5\u570b\u3001\u897f\u73ed\u7259\u6216\u65e5\u672c\u7684\u5165\u5883\u4eba\u58eb\u63a1\u53d6\u91ab\u5b78\u6aa2\u67e5\u53ca14\u5929\u9694\u96e2\u91ab\u5b78\u89c0\u5bdf|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322218/|accessdate=2020-03-08|author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=2020-03-08|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305125732/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322218/|archivedate=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref> The Tertiary Education Bureau announced measures to help students from Macau studying abroad to purchase face masks.<ref name=\":34\">{{Cite web|title=\u5728\u5916\u5730\u5c31\u8b80\u7684\u6fb3\u9580\u5927\u5b78\u751f\u53ef\u900f\u904e\u53e3\u7f69\u4fdd\u969c\u8a08\u5283\u8cfc\u8cb7\u53e3\u7f69|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322289/|accessdate=2020-03-14|author=\u9ad8\u7b49\u6559\u80b2\u5c40|date=2020-03-08 |format=HTML |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314081930/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322289/|archivedate=2020-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, the Sports Bureau announced that sports facilities under its authority had gradually resumed opening starting March 2, and that other facilities would be able to gradually resume opening starting 11 March. These facilities had been closed since 24 January.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u9ad4\u80b2\u5c40\u201c\u516c\u5171\u9ad4\u80b2\u8a2d\u65bd\u7db2\u7d61\u201d\u5167\u5404\u9ad4\u80b2\u8a2d\u65bd3\u670811\u65e5\u91cd\u65b0\u5c0d\u5916\u958b\u653e\u5b89\u6392|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322409/|accessdate=2020-03-10|author=\u9ad4\u80b2\u5c40|date=2020-03-09|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310140130/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322409/|archivedate=2020-03-10|url-status=live}}</ref> The Blood Donation Center announced the suspension of blood donation by at-risk individuals for 28 days.<ref name=\":33\">{{Cite web|title=\u6350\u8840\u4e2d\u5fc3\u61c9\u5c0d\u201c\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u80ba\u708e\u201d\u7684\u6700\u65b0\u63aa\u65bd|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322374/|accessdate=2020-03-14|author=\u885b\u751f\u5c40|date=2020-03-09|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314074638/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322374/|archivedate=2020-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, the Education and Youth Affairs Bureau announced a contingency plan for resuming classes in stages, with different grades gradually going back to school on different dates from 30 March and 4 May.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u7279\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u547c\u7c72\u5e02\u6c11\u5982\u975e\u5fc5\u8981\u52ff\u5916\u904a \u516c\u4f48\u975e\u9ad8\u7b49\u6559\u80b2\u7684\u5206\u968e\u6bb5\u5fa9\u8ab2\u9810\u6848|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323058/|accessdate=2020-03-13|author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=2020-03-13|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312140624/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323058/|archivedate=2020-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, it was announced that people entering Macau who had been to the COVID-19 hotspots of the [[Schengen Area]], the United Kingdom, the United States, Canada, Russia, Brazil, Egypt, Australia, or New Zealand in the past 14 days would be required to undergo medical observation at a designated location.<ref name=\"qu0314\">{{Cite web|title=\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u591a\u500b\u570b\u5bb6\u6216\u5730\u5340\u88ab\u65b0\u589e\u5217\u5165\u9ad8\u767c\u5730\u5340\uff09 |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20CNpLrh0;jsessionid=5F167B7154B9B8F0C2F27F46A70F7A01.app03?0|accessdate=2020-03-14|author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=2020-03-14|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330144608/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20CNpLrh0;jsessionid=E426A6DAB90AA280A2027822FEB77FC1.app02?0 |archivedate=2020-03-30|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=30\u9ad8\u5371\u570b\u5bb6\u8fd4\u6fb3\u9580\u4eba\u58eb\u9808\u9694\u96e214\u5929\u3000\u9ad8\u7b49\u9662\u6821\u4e0b\u67081\u65e5\u5fa9\u8ab2|url=https://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/news/20200314/bkn-20200314173508703-0314_00822_001.html?eventsection=hk_cnnews&eventid=71549E518A5CCA45E050007F010049A4 |accessdate=2020-03-14 |author= |date=2020-03-14 |format=|work=on.cc\u4e1c\u7f51|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=|archivedate=|url-status=live}}</ref>The Tertiary Education Bureau announced that some classes meeting certain conditions would be allowed to resume on 1 April.<ref name=\":35\">{{Cite web|title=\u6d77\u5916\u8fd4\u6fb3\u5b78\u751f\u9808\u63a5\u53d7\u5bb6\u5c45\u91ab\u5b78\u89c0\u5bdf \u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3\u547c\u7c72\u56b4\u683c\u9075\u5b88\u885b\u751f\u6307\u5f15|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323152/|accessdate=2020-03-14|author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=2020-03-14 |format=HTML |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314144405/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323152/ |archivedate=2020-03-14 |url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, it was announced that students returning to Macau from abroad would have to undergo 14 days of medical observation at home and a nucleic acid test.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u6d77\u5916\u56de\u6fb3\u5b78\u751f\u9808\u63a5\u53d714\u5929\u5bb6\u5c45\u91ab\u5b78\u89c0\u5bdf\uff09|url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20CN3jwSS?3|accessdate=2020-03-14|author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=2020-03-14 |format=HTML |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315021910/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20CN3jwSS;jsessionid=F2A8C45AD59381824CF5E86248697F54.app01?0 |archivedate=2020-03-15 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, it was announced that New Zealand is not considered a COVID-19 hotspot.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a (,\u65b0\u897f\u862d\u4e0d\u88ab\u5217\u5165\u9ad8\u767c\u5730\u5340)|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323210/|accessdate=2020-03-15|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-03-15|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315021412/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323210/ |archivedate=2020-03-15|url-status=live}}</ref> The Tourism Bureau announced that from 17 March to 22 March the government would arrange transportation from [[Hong Kong International Airport]] for Macau residents and students coming from European countries to bring them to a designated location for 14 days of medical observation.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u63a5\u8f09\u5f9e\u6b50\u6d32\u795e\u6839\u5730\u5340\u8fd4\u9999\u6e2f\u7684\u672c\u6fb3\u6b50\u6d32\u7559\u5b78\u751f\u53ca\u5916\u904a\u6b50\u6d32\u7684\u6fb3\u9580\u5c45\u6c11\u5b89\u6392\uff09|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323219/|accessdate=2020-03-15|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-03-15|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315021412/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323219/|archivedate=2020-03-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, it was announced that starting 17 March at midnight (00:00), people arriving in Macau from any countries outside China (meaning mainland China, Hong Kong, Macau, and Taiwan) would have to undergo 14 days of medical observation at a designated location. The Tourism Bureau announced that transportation from Hong Kong International Airport to a designated location would be arranged for Macau residents and students coming from the United States as well as European countries.<ref name=\":37\">{{Cite web|title=\u660e\u65e5\u96f6\u6642\u8d77\u672c\u6fb3\u5c0d\u4e2d\u570b\u4ee5\u5916\u570b\u5bb6\u6216\u5730\u5340\u5165\u5883\u4eba\u58eb\u5be6\u65bd\u91ab\u5b78\u89c0\u5bdf\u63aa\u65bd \u547c\u7c72\u5165\u5883\u4eba\u58eb\u5165\u5883\u5982\u5be6\u7533\u5831 \u5c45\u6c11\u5982\u975e\u5fc5\u8981\u52ff\u5916\u904a|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323430/ |accessdate=2020-03-16 |author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=2020-03-16 |format=HTML |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |publisher= |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316154242/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323430/ |archivedate=2020-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nEffective March 18, the government banned entry of all non-residents, with exceptions for mainland China, Hong Kong, and Taiwan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://macaunews.mo/macau-prohibits-non-residents-from-entering-macau-with-the-exception-of-those-from-mainland-china-hong-kong-and-taiwan/|title=Macau Prohibits Non-Residents from Entering Macau with the exception of those from Mainland China, Hong Kong and Taiwan|website=Macau News |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the Tourism Bureau announced that from 19 March to 31 March, transportation from Hong Kong International Airport would take Macau residents and students coming from all countries to designated locations for medical observation.\n\nOn 19 March, the plan for resuming classes in stages was cancelled.<ref name=\":46\">{{Cite web|title=\u975e\u9ad8\u7b49\u6559\u80b2\u5b78\u6821\u5ef6\u671f\u5fa9\u8ab2\u81f3\u53e6\u884c\u518d\u516c\u5e03 |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323922/|accessdate=2020-03-19|author=\u6559\u80b2\u66a8\u9752\u5e74\u5c40|date=2020-03-19|format=|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319114318/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323922/ |archivedate=2020-03-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, the chief executive announced that starting 25 March, connecting flights would no longer be permitted at [[Macau International Airport]]; any residents of Hong Kong, Taiwan, or mainland China who had been to other countries in the previous 14 days were prohibited from entering Macau; and Macau residents who had been to Hong Kong, Taiwan, or other countries in the past 14 days would be required to undergo 14 days of medical observation at a designated location.<ref name=\":56\">{{Cite web|title=\uff0d\u884c\u653f\u9577\u5b98\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u660e\u8d77\u7981\u6b62\u5165\u5883\u524d14\u5929\u5167\u66fe\u5230\u5916\u570b\u7684\u975e\u6fb3\u9580\u5c45\u6c11\u5165\u5883\uff09\uff0d|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/324556/|accessdate=2020-03-24|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |date=2020-03-24 |format=HTML |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200324031513/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/324556/|archivedate=2020-03-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the Health Bureau expanded restrictions on blood donations.<ref name=\":63\">{{Cite web|title=\u6350\u8840\u4e2d\u5fc3\u61c9\u5c0d\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u80ba\u708e\u7684\u6700\u65b0\u63aa\u65bd\u548c\u547c\u7c72\u6350\u8840|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/325006/|accessdate=2020-03-25|author=2020-03-25|date=2020-03-25|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325131008/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/325006/|archivedate=2020-03-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\n\nOn 4 April, the government of Macau followed the Chinese central government in holding a day of mourning throughout Macau. [[Chinese flag]]s and [[Macau flag]]s were to be flown at [[half mast]], and public entertainment and celebrations or festive events were to stop. Starting at 10AM that day, Macau would observe a three-minute moment of silence.<ref>[https://hd.stheadline.com/news/realtime/hk/1739427/%E5%8D%B3%E6%99%82-%E6%B8%AF%E8%81%9E-%E7%96%AB%E6%83%85%E4%B8%8B%E5%85%A7%E5%9C%B0%E6%98%8E%E6%97%A5%E5%85%A8%E5%9C%8B%E5%93%80%E6%82%BC-%E6%BE%B3%E9%96%80%E5%B0%87%E4%B8%8B%E5%8D%8A%E6%97%97%E8%87%B4%E5%93%80 \u75ab\u60c5\u4e0b\u5167\u5730\u660e\u65e5\u5168\u570b\u54c0\u60bc \u6fb3\u9580\u5c07\u4e0b\u534a\u65d7\u81f4\u54c0]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by dependent territory|Macau]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in China by city|Macau]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Macau]]\n[[Category:2020 in Macau]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Macau]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Macau}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{expand Chinese|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Macau\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Macau.svg\n| legend1         = {{center|Map of parishes with confirmed (red) or suspected (blue) coronavirus cases (as of 28 January)}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Macau]]\n| first_case      = \n| arrival_date    = 22 January 2020 \u2013 present <br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=22|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 10\n| deaths          = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 39\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [https://www.ssm.gov.mo/apps1/PreventWuhanInfection/en.aspx Macao Government Special webpage against Epidemics]\n}}\nThe [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] had its first case in [[Macau]] confirmed on 22 January 2020.\n__TOC__\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Macau medical cases chart}}\nOn 22 January 2020, Macau confirmed two COVID-19 cases, that of a 52-year-old woman and of a 66-year-old man, both from [[Wuhan]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/news/20200123/mobile/bkn-20200123095348297-0123_00822_001.html |script-title=zh:\u6fb3\u9580\u78ba\u8a3a\u7b2c2\u5b97\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u3000\u60a3\u8005\u70ba66\u6b72\u7537\u904a\u5ba2 |website= HK |language=zh-hk |date=23 January 2020 |access-date=23 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124014056/https://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/news/20200123/mobile/bkn-20200123095348297-0123_00822_001.html |archive-date=24 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn the morning of 26 January, the [[Macau Health Bureau]] confirmed three additional cases: that of a 58-year-old woman arriving from [[Hong Kong]] on 23 January after travelling to Wuhan, and of two women, aged 21 and 39, both arriving in Macau on 22 January via the [[Lotus Bridge]]; all three were residents of Wuhan. The Macau government has since temporarily closed all schools and universities, and has imposed border controls with temperature checks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://macaunews.mo/government-confirms-5-cases-of-coronavirus-so-far-in-macau/|title=Government confirms 5 cases of coronavirus so far in Macau|date=26 January 2020|website=Macau News|access-date=2020-01-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126102217/https://macaunews.mo/government-confirms-5-cases-of-coronavirus-so-far-in-macau/|archive-date=26 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The government also declared the closing of several venues to limit the possible spread of the virus, including several entertainment venues and planned Lunar New Year performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.asgam.com/index.php/2020/01/28/macau-irs-close-facilities-as-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-reach-seven/|title=Macau IRs close facilities as confirmed Coronavirus cases reach seven|last=|first=|date=28 January 2020|website=Inside Asian Gaming|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129140552/https://www.asgam.com/index.php/2020/01/28/macau-irs-close-facilities-as-confirmed-coronavirus-cases-reach-seven/|archive-date=29 January 2020|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 January, a 15-year-old boy, the son of one of the previously confirmed patients, was declared the sixth case of the virus in Macau.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://macaunews.mo/15-year-old-wuhan-boy-confirmed-as-the-sixth-coronavirus-case-in-macau/|title=15-year-old Wuhan boy confirmed as the sixth coronavirus case in Macau|last=|first=|date=27 January 2020|website=Macau News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129141126/https://macaunews.mo/15-year-old-wuhan-boy-confirmed-as-the-sixth-coronavirus-case-in-macau/|archive-date=29 January 2020|access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref> The next day, the seventh case was announced, that of a 67-year-old woman, a resident of Wuhan who travelled to [[Guangzhou]] before entering Macau through the Barrier Gate checkpoint.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://macaunews.mo/macau-confirms-7th-wuhan-virus-case-in-a-deserted-city/|title=Macau confirms 7th Wuhan virus case in a deserted city|last=|first=|date=28 January 2020|website=Macau News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129150822/https://macaunews.mo/macau-confirms-7th-wuhan-virus-case-in-a-deserted-city/|archive-date=29 January 2020|access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, all 10 confirmed patients with the virus had recovered. According to authorities, however, there are still 224 people in isolation, 6 in quarantine, and 58 Macau residents who have been to South Korea and Italy also isolated.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://macaunews.mo/no-more-covid-19-cases-in-macau/ |title=No more COVID-19 cases in Macau |work=Macau News |date=6 March 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 March, the Philippines announced that an airlift operation will be launched to bring home 167 Filipinos working in Macau.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/7/macau-evacuees-go-home-march-7.html |title = 163 stranded Filipinos from Macau arrive home |work=CNN Philippines}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, the city registered a new COVID-19 case imported from Portugal, the first new case in over a month. The patient is a Korean migrant worker who visited her boyfriend's family in the city of [[Porto]].\nThe woman departed Macau on January 30. She flew back to Hong Kong from Dubai on March 13 on flight number EK380, taking seat 31J.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://macaunews.mo/macau-recorded-the-11th-case-of-covid-19/ |title=Macau records its 11th case of COVID-19 &#124; Macau News |publisher=Macaunews.mo |date=2020-03-16 |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref> She returned to Macau on the same day via the [[Hong Kong-Zhuhai-Macau Bridge]]. Later in the day she started experiencing coughing and went to the hospital on Sunday afternoon, March 15, with fever.\n\nOn 17 March, two new cases were reported. The first patient, a 47-year-old male, is a Spanish national doing business in Macau; he took the SU2501 flight from Madrid to Moscow on March 15, and then the SU204 flight from Moscow to Beijing. On 16 March, he took the NX001 flight from Beijing to Macau, arriving at Macau Airport at 8:00 pm of the same day. The second patient is a 20-year-old woman, a Macau resident who was studying in the United Kingdom. The patient left London and arrived at the [[Hong Kong International Airport]] via Kuala Lumpur on the night of March 16. Upon arrival at the [[Hong Kong-Zhuhai-Macau Bridge]], she was detected to have a fever and was immediately taken to the hospital. Further testing revealed she was infected with the novel coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tdm.com.mo/c_news/radio_news.php?id=460383 |title=\u96fb\u53f0\u65b0\u805e>\u672c\u6fb3\u4eca\u65e5\u78ba\u8a3a2\u5b97\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e(2020.03.17 19:47) |publisher=Tdm.com.mo |date=2020-03-17 |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the [[Education and Youth Affairs Bureau (Macau)|Education and Youth Affairs Bureau]] announced the re-postponement of its plans to resume primary and secondary education as a response to the second wave of COVID-19 cases beginning with the 11th case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/en/N20CS1PR97?keyword=%E9%9D%9E%E9%AB%98%E7%AD%89%E6%95%99%E8%82%B2|title=NEWS.GOV.MO: Class resumption for non-tertiary education schools will be postponed until further notice|website=news.gov.mo}}</ref> This is after the bureau's class resumption plans starting on 30 March, announced on 11 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/en/N20CJOAuRT|title=NEWS.GOV.MO: DSEJ formulates a plan for class resumption of non-tertiary education schools|website=news.gov.mo}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, the government of neighbouring [[Zhuhai]] announced that anyone returning or travelling from outside Mainland China (including Macau and Hong Kong) would undergo mandatory 14-day quarantine with a few exceptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20CaKhyeq|title=NEWS.GOV.MO: \u3010\u5716\u6587\u5305\u3011\u51fa\u5165\u5883\u8c41\u514d\u60c5\u6cc1\u548c\u51fa\u5165\u5883\u7279\u5225\u624b\u7e8c|website=news.gov.mo}}</ref> This caused large crowds and chaos at the [[L\u00f3tus Bridge|Lotus Checkpoint]] in [[Cotai]], which was the only border checkpoint open at the time.\n\n==Response and impact==\n\n===December 2019===\n\nOn 31 December 2019, the Health Bureau was notified by the [[National Health Commission]] of an outbreak of pneumonia of unknown cause in [[Wuhan]]. Residents were asked to avoid excessive panic but to be conscious of personal hygiene and the hygiene of their environment. Those traveling to Wuhan were advised to avoid visiting local hospitals or having contact with sick people.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u885b\u751f\u5c40\u63a5\u570b\u5bb6\u885b\u5065\u59d4\u901a\u5831\u6b66\u6f22\u4e0d\u660e\u539f\u56e0\u80ba\u708e \u5df2\u6709\u6a5f\u5236\u76e3\u6e2c\u53ca\u61c9\u5c0d\u5e02\u6c11\u6bcb\u9808\u904e\u5206\u6050\u614c |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/312595/ |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u885b\u751f\u5c40 |language=zh-tw |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207071843/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AAECxlQ;jsessionid=9665DE00A598BF844DDF6A08E7161D73.app02?0 |archivedate=2019-12-31 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===January 2020===\n\nOn 1 January 2020, the Macao Health Bureau asked [[Macau International Airport]] to implement body temperature screening for all passengers on flights coming from Wuhan.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u4eca\u5929\u8d77\u5c0d\u4f86\u81ea\u6b66\u6f22\u822a\u73ed\u4e58\u5ba2\u9032\u884c\u9ad4\u6e29\u7be9\u67e5 \u885b\u751f\u5c40\u8207\u570b\u5bb6\u885b\u751f\u5065\u5eb7\u59d4\u54e1\u4fdd\u6301\u5bc6\u5207\u806f\u7e6b |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AAECxlQ |accessdate=2020-01-02 |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u885b\u751f\u5c40 |language=zh-tw |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207071843/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AAECxlQ;jsessionid=9665DE00A598BF844DDF6A08E7161D73.app02?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref> Starting 5 January, the Health Bureau raised the pneumonia warning level to 3, medium risk, and on the same day established the \"Interdepartmental Working Group Against Pneumonia of Unknown Cause\" (\u61c9\u5c0d\u4e0d\u660e\u539f\u56e0\u80ba\u708e\u8de8\u90e8\u9580\u5de5\u4f5c\u5c0f\u7d44).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AEUUwwZ |title=\u7279\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u63d0\u6607\u5c0d\"\u6b66\u6f22\u4e0d\u660e\u539f\u56e0\u80ba\u708e\"\u7684\u9810\u8b66\u7d1a\u5225\u81f3\u7b2cIII\u7d1a(\u8f03\u91cd) \u885b\u751f\u5c40\u547c\u7c72\u5e02\u6c11\u63d0\u9ad8\u9632\u7bc4\u610f\u8b58 |date=2020-01-05 |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u885b\u751f\u5c40 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207072051/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AEUUwwZ;jsessionid=2C12CEB2F0CA4908E13CF5B20217344E.app01?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live |access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref>\n\nStarting January 10, people bought large quantities of masks, leading to shortages in some pharmacies. ''[[Macao Daily News]]'' reported that, according to the Health Bureau, the city's supply of masks was sufficient.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.macaodaily.com/html/2020-01/10/content_1408320.htm |title=\u53e3\u7f69\u5145\u8db3\u6bcb\u6050\u614c \u61c9\u5c0d\u80ba\u708e\u53ca\u65e9\u9632 |date=2020-01-10 |newspaper=\u6fb3\u95e8\u65e5\u62a5 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207072757/http://www.macaodaily.com/html/2020-01/10/content_1408320.htm |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live |language=zh}}</ref> On the day that the first case in Macau was confirmed, the Health Bureau announced at a press conference that starting in the evening of January 23, Macau residents and foreign workers could use [[Macau Resident Identity Card]]s and foreign worker identity cards respectively to purchase up to 10 masks per person every 10 days. Director of the Health Bureau Li Zhanrun (\u674e\u5c55\u6f64) said that out of 294 pharmacies in Macau, 160 did not have masks and that out of eight mask suppliers, one had 150,000 masks remaining in stock whereas the others were out of stock.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AVJspef |title=\u885b\u751f\u5c40\u5c07\u63a8\u51fa\u4fdd\u969c\u53e3\u7f69\u4f9b\u61c9\u6fb3\u9580\u5c45\u6c11\u8a08\u5283 \u78ba\u4fdd\u5c45\u6c11\u53ef\u8cfc\u8cb7\u5230\u6240\u9700\u53e3\u7f69 |date=2020-01-22 |newspaper=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207073025/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AVJspef;jsessionid=4EE7B5BEBF6A13FA624B6707AA84E3F1.app01?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live |language=zh}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 January, [[Chief Executive of Macau|Chief Executive]] [[Ho Iat Seng]] ordered the establishment of a 24-hour \"Novel Coronavirus Emergency Coordination Center\", replacing the \"Interdepartmental Working Group Against Pneumonia of Unknown Cause\", to operate directly under the chief executive, with Secretary for Social Affairs and Culture as vice chair.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AUAWxeo |title=\u7279\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u63d0\u6607\u5c0d\"\u6b66\u6f22\u4e0d\u660e\u539f\u56e0\u80ba\u708e\"\u7684\u9810\u8b66\u7d1a\u5225\u81f3\u7b2cIII\u7d1a(\u8f03\u91cd) \u885b\u751f\u5c40\u547c\u7c72\u5e02\u6c11\u63d0\u9ad8\u9632\u7bc4\u610f\u8b58 |date=2020-01-21 |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u885b\u751f\u5c40 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207072247/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AUAWxeo;jsessionid=90528C1EE65EC09E19A413B749F04296.app01?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live |access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u5370\u52d9\u5c40 - \u884c\u653f\u9577\u5b98\u6279\u793a |url=https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/03/despce_cn.asp |accessdate=2020-02-01 |work=bo.io.gov.mo |publisher=\u5370\u52d9\u5c40 |language=zh-Hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201091940/https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/03/despce_cn.asp |archivedate=2020-02-01 |url-status=live}}</ref> In response to the city's first imported case, steps were taken, including: border control points implemented health declarations,<ref>{{cite web |title=\u3010\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u3011\u6fb3\u9580\u6240\u6709\u53e3\u5cb8\u5be6\u65bd\u5065\u5eb7\u7533\u5831 \u4e58\u91d1\u5df4\u5165\u5883\u9808\u586b\u8868 |url=https://std.stheadline.com/instant/articles/detail/1186708/ |accessdate=2020-01-23 |date=2020-01-22 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207072444/https://std.stheadline.com/instant/articles/detail/1186708/%E5%8D%B3%E6%99%82-%E9%A6%99%E6%B8%AF-%E6%AD%A6%E6%BC%A2%E8%82%BA%E7%82%8E-%E6%BE%B3%E9%96%80%E6%89%80%E6%9C%89%E5%8F%A3%E5%B2%B8%E5%AF%A6%E6%96%BD%E5%81%A5%E5%BA%B7%E7%94%B3%E5%A0%B1-%E4%B9%98%E9%87%91%E5%B7%B4%E5%85%A5%E5%A2%83%E9%A0%88%E5%A1%AB%E8%A1%A8 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live |website=\u661f\u5cf6\u65e5\u5831}}</ref> resort workers had to wear masks, Macau residents were not encouraged to travel to Wuhan, and tour groups between Wuhan and Macau were suspended.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u653f\u5e9c\u5168\u529b\u61c9\u5c0d\u52a0\u5f37\u9632\u63a7\u75ab\u60c5 |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/314827/ |accessdate=2020-01-23 |date=2020-01-22 |language=zh-hant |url-status=live |author1=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3 |website=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124152435/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/314827/ |archive-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u6fb3\u958011\u65e5\u7121\u78ba\u8a3a \u4f55\u6822\u826f\uff1a\u63a7\u75ab\u52dd\u6e2f \u7a31\u627e\u51fa\u6e56\u5317\u5ba2\u95dc\u9375 \u65e9\u5207\u65b7\u96b1\u5f62\u50b3\u64ad\u93c8|url=https://m.mingpao.com/pns/%E8%A6%81%E8%81%9E/article/20200216/s00001/1581789946951/%E6%BE%B3%E9%96%8011%E6%97%A5%E7%84%A1%E7%A2%BA%E8%A8%BA-%E4%BD%95%E6%A0%A2%E8%89%AF-%E6%8E%A7%E7%96%AB%E5%8B%9D%E6%B8%AF-%E7%A8%B1%E6%89%BE%E5%87%BA%E6%B9%96%E5%8C%97%E5%AE%A2%E9%97%9C%E9%8D%B5-%E6%97%A9%E5%88%87%E6%96%B7%E9%9A%B1%E5%BD%A2%E5%82%B3%E6%92%AD%E9%8F%88|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217151832/https://m.mingpao.com/pns/%E8%A6%81%E8%81%9E/article/20200216/s00001/1581789946951/%E6%BE%B3%E9%96%8011%E6%97%A5%E7%84%A1%E7%A2%BA%E8%A8%BA-%E4%BD%95%E6%A0%A2%E8%89%AF-%E6%8E%A7%E7%96%AB%E5%8B%9D%E6%B8%AF-%E7%A8%B1%E6%89%BE%E5%87%BA%E6%B9%96%E5%8C%97%E5%AE%A2%E9%97%9C%E9%8D%B5-%E6%97%A9%E5%88%87%E6%96%B7%E9%9A%B1%E5%BD%A2%E5%82%B3%E6%92%AD%E9%8F%88|archivedate=2020-02-17|accessdate=2020-02-17|date=2020-02-17|work=\u660e\u5831}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January, Macau confirmed its second imported case, leading the Government Tourism Office to cancel all Chinese New Year celebrations, including the Macau Chinese New Year Parade.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AW8tgPg |title=\u653f\u5e9c\u53d6\u6d88\u65b0\u6625\u5927\u578b\u516c\u773e\u6d3b\u52d5\u3000\u964d\u4f4e\u50b3\u67d3\u75c5\u50b3\u64ad\u98a8\u96aa |date=2020-01-23 |publisher=\u6fb3\u9580\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207073332/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AW8tgPg;jsessionid=66F89CB747B12058FF7648786127368F.app02?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day, Ho Iat Seng announced that anyone with fever symptoms should not leave Macau. On January 23, Ho Iat Seng announced that Macau had ordered 20 million masks to sell to Macau residents and foreign workers at cost.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AWOxBz2 |title=\u884c\u653f\u9577\u5b98\uff1a\u52a0\u5f37\u9632\u63a7 \u5b89\u5ea6\u6625\u7bc0 |date=2020-01-23 |publisher=\u6fb3\u9580\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207073530/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AWOxBz2;jsessionid=DAA9C5B9204BB1D2539118C50E12066B.app03?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref> The Correctional Services Authority announced precautions against the virus.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u61f2\u6559\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40\u5be6\u65bd\u9810\u9632\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u7684\u63aa\u65bd|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/314975/|accessdate=2020-03-28|author=\u61f2\u6559\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40|date=2020-01-23|authorlink=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u61f2\u6559\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328051859/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/314975/|archivedate=2020-03-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January, the [[Education and Youth Affairs Bureau (Macau)|Education and Youth Affairs Bureau]] announced that all non-tertiary schools would extend their Chinese New Year holiday, not resuming classes until February 10 or later. The bureau also asked other private tutoring and continuing education centers to delay the resumption of classes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://hk.news.appledaily.com/local/20200124/K3HGL5C4TWLPPTKT6JEXUYQM5M/ |title=\u3010\u6b66\u6f22\u80ba\u708e\u3011\u6fb3\u9580\u5ba3\u4f48\u4e2d\u5c0f\u5b78\u65b0\u5e74\u5047\u5f8c\u5ef6\u671f\u4e0a\u8ab2 \u7c72\u6821\u5b89\u6392\u5b78\u751f\u7559\u5bb6\u5b78\u7fd2 |date=2020-01-24 |work=\u860b\u679c\u65e5\u5831 |url-status=live}}</ref> On the same day, the Tertiary Education Bureau also announced that ten tertiary institutions would delay classes until February 11.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u6fb3\u9580\u5341\u9ad8\u6821\u5ef6\u5f8c\u81f32\u670811\u65e5\u958b\u5b78-\u9ad8\u7b49\u6559\u80b2\u5c40|url=https://www.dses.gov.mo/news/5162-2020-01-24|accessdate=2020-01-26|author=dses.gov.mo|date=2020-01-24|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126024001/https://www.dses.gov.mo/news/5162-2020-01-24|archive-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> The Sports Bureau later announced that sporting facilities would be closed from that afternoon (24 January) at 4PM.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u9ad4\u80b2\u5c40\u8f44\u4e0b\u9ad4\u80b2\u8a2d\u65bd\u4eca\u5348\u56db\u6642\u8d77\u66ab\u505c\u958b\u653e|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/315058/|accessdate=2020-03-10|author=\u9ad4\u80b2\u5c40|date=2020-01-24|authorlink=\u9ad4\u80b2\u5c40 (\u6fb3\u9580)|format=|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310135821/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/315058/|archivedate=2020-03-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 January, the government of Macau announced that the opening hours at the [[Posto Fronteiri\u00e7o das Portas do Cerco|Portas do Cerco border crossing]] with [[Zhuhai]] would be reduced by three hours, to 6AM\u201310PM, until further notice. Opening hours at other border crossings with Zhuhai and Hong Kong would not be affected for the time being.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/ch/component/k2/1504833-20200125.htm?archive_date=2020-01-25 |title=\u6fb3\u9580\u5ba3\u5e03\u95dc\u9598\u62f1\u5317\u53e3\u5cb8\u4eba\u8eca\u901a\u95dc\u6642\u9593\u7e2e\u77ed3\u5c0f\u6642 |date=2020-01-25 |work=\u9999\u6e2f\u96fb\u53f0 |url-status=live |access-date=2020-01-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125145402/https://news.rthk.hk/rthk/ch/component/k2/1504833-20200125.htm%3Farchive_date%3D2020-01-25 |archive-date=2020-01-25 |language=zh}}</ref> On the same day, the Macau government announced that they would donate 50,000 urgently needed medical masks to the city of Zhuhai, to be used for the prevention and treatment of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u62f1\u5317\u6d77\u5173\u5feb\u901f\u9a8c\u653e\u6fb3\u95e8\u6350\u8d60\u73e0\u6d775\u4e07\u4e2a\u533b\u7528\u53e3\u7f69 |url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/2020-01/25/c_1125501932.htm |url-status=live |agency=\u65b0\u534e\u7f51 |access-date=2020-01-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126113849/http://www.xinhuanet.com/2020-01/25/c_1125501932.htm |archive-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 January, the government announced that starting on the 27th, all non-residents who were from or had been to Hubei in the past 14 days were required to have a doctor's note certifying that they did not have the virus in order to be allowed into Macau. In addition, anyone who had been to Hubei in the past 14 days was prohibited from entering casinos.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AaeveUQ |title=\u9650\u5236\u5165\u5883\u6fb3\u9580\u524d14\u65e5\u5167\u66fe\u5230\u6e56\u5317\u7701\u4eba\u58eb\u9032\u5165\u5a1b\u6a02\u5834 |date=2020-01-27 |publisher=\u535a\u5f69\u76e3\u5bdf\u5354\u8abf\u5c40 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207073832/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20AaeveUQ;jsessionid=6586AFC3DEF51B5F887875E59B51BAC7.app02?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref> That evening the government of Macau announced that starting at 9AM on the 27th, the 1,113 travelers from Hubei who had entered Macau between December 1 and January 26 and remained in the territory would be quarantined.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20Aa8HHeL |title=\u6cbb\u5b89\u8b66\u7a4d\u6975\u914d\u5408\u7279\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u9632\u75ab\u5de5\u4f5c |date=2020-01-27 |publisher=\u6cbb\u5b89\u8b66\u5bdf\u5c40 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207074009/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20Aa8HHeL;jsessionid=ACBA16C393CFB50B3763BD3BD8A14BAD.app01?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 January, [[Secretariat for Administration and Justice (Macau)|Secretary for Administration and Justice]] Zhang Yongchun (\u5f35\u6c38\u6625) said that in accordance with the decision of the central government, endorsements for mainland Chinese visitors to Macau would be suspended.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nia.gov.cn/n741440/n741542/c1214127/content.html |title=\u56fd\u5bb6\u79fb\u6c11\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40\u6682\u505c\u529e\u7406\u5185\u5730\u5c45\u6c11\u5f80\u6765\u6e2f\u6fb3\u5730\u533a\u65c5\u6e38\u7b7e\u6ce8 |work=\u56fd\u5bb6\u79fb\u6c11\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40 |language=zh-hk |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207074151/https://www.nia.gov.cn/n741440/n741542/c1214127/content.html |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 January, the Tertiary Education Bureau accounced that the resumption of classes would be delayed further, and that a schedule for resuming classes would be released one week before classes were to resume.<ref name=\":18\">{{cite web |title=\u672c\u6fb3\u6240\u6709\u5927\u5c08\u3001\u975e\u9ad8\u7b49\u6559\u80b2\u6a5f\u69cb\u53ca\u79c1\u7acb\u88dc\u5145\u6559\u5b78\u8f14\u52a9\u4e2d\u5fc3\u5ef6\u9072\u958b\u8ab2\u81f3\u53e6\u884c\u516c\u4f48 |url=https://www.dses.gov.mo/news/5179-2020-01-30 |accessdate=2020-01-31 |author=dses.gov.mo |date=2020-01-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207074315/https://www.dses.gov.mo/news/5179-2020-01-30 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===February 2020===\nOn 3 February, the government of Macau announced that starting at noon, all bus and taxi passengers were required to wear wear masks; otherwise the driver would have the right to refuse boarding.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u4e58\u5ba2\u9808\u4f69\u6234\u53e3\u7f69\u65b9\u53ef\u4e58\u642d\u5df4\u58eb |url=https://www.dsat.gov.mo/dsat/news_detail.aspx?a_id=5FE497B2F8060898A9BBA44F10244BA6 |accessdate=2020-02-03 |date=2020-02-03 |language=zh-mo |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207074557/https://www.dsat.gov.mo/dsat/news_detail.aspx?a_id=5FE497B2F8060898A9BBA44F10244BA6 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live |author1=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u4ea4\u901a\u4e8b\u52d9\u5c40}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u4e58\u5ba2\u9808\u4f69\u6234\u53e3\u7f69\u65b9\u53ef\u4e58\u642d\u7684\u58eb |url=https://www.dsat.gov.mo/dsat/news_detail.aspx?a_id=074A4495F12B6EFE7C84E7B30431AF15 |accessdate=2020-02-03 |date=2020-02-03 |language=zh-mo |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207074655/https://www.dsat.gov.mo/dsat/news_detail.aspx?a_id=074A4495F12B6EFE7C84E7B30431AF15 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live |author1=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u4ea4\u901a\u4e8b\u52d9\u5c40}}</ref> Starting at 13:00, all light rail passengers were required to wear a mask; otherwise the driver would have the right to refuse boarding.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web |title=NEWS.GOV.MO: \uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u9632\u75ab\u63aa\u65bd\uff09\uff0d |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20BCzi7H3 |accessdate=2020-02-09 |author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |date=2020-02-03 |work=news.gov.mo |publisher=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |language=zh-Hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200209075337/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20BCzi7H3;jsessionid=EA578917F150E31435A7327F15BF9B8B.app01?0 |archivedate=2020-02-09 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 February 2020, all [[casino]]s in Macau were ordered to shut down for 15 days.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stevenson |first=Alexandra |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/04/business/coronavirus-macau-gambling.html |title=Coronavirus Shuts Macau, the World's Gambling Capital |date=4 February 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=4 February 2020 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204121004/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/04/business/coronavirus-macau-gambling.html |archive-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Yang |first=Joyu Wang and Jing |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/deadly-coronavirus-forces-chinas-gambling-hub-to-shut-its-casinos-11580816447 |title=Coronavirus: Bad Luck Hits Macau Casinos With 15-Day Shutdown |date=4 February 2020 |work=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=4 February 2020 |issn=0099-9660 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206113014/https://www.wsj.com/articles/deadly-coronavirus-forces-chinas-gambling-hub-to-shut-its-casinos-11580816447 |archive-date=6 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The following facilities were also required to close: cinemas, theatres, indoor amusement parks, arcades, internet cafes, pool halls, bowling alleys, steam baths, massage parlours, beauty salons, gyms, health clubs, bars, karaoke bars, nightclubs, discos, and dance clubs.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u5370\u52d9\u5c40 - \u884c\u653f\u9577\u5b98\u6279\u793a |url=https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/05/despce_cn.asp |accessdate=2020-02-08 |author=\u884c\u653f\u9577\u5b98 \u8cc0\u4e00\u8aa0 |date=2020-02-04 |work=bo.io.gov.mo |publisher=\u5370\u52d9\u5c40 |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204112701/https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/05/despce_cn.asp |archivedate=2020-02-04 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 7, the government of Macau announced that government workers were to stay home from the 8th to the 16th, except for emergency services.<ref>{{cite web |title=NEWS.GOV.MO: \u516c\u52d9\u4eba\u54e1\u56e0\u9632\u75ab\u9700\u89818\u81f316\u865f\u514d\u9664\u4e0a\u73ed |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20BGROZbm |accessdate=2020-02-07 |author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |date=2020-02-07 |work=news.gov.mo |publisher=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207115559/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20BGROZbm;jsessionid=2ABAEBA2B2217366ECACFAFBEE4717F1.app01?0 |archivedate=2020-02-07 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 February, at the daily press conference, the government announced the third face mask safeguarding plan and provided masks for children for the first time, but due to limited quantities, each child was only permitted to buy five.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite web |title=\u660e\u5929\u8d77\u6709\u5152\u7ae5\u53e3\u7f69\u4f9b\u61c9 |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/317960/ |accessdate=2020-02-11 |author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |date=2020-02-11 |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211135351/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/317960/ |archivedate=2020-02-11 |url-status=live}}</ref> The government also announced that testing would begin for groups at high risk of infection, and that the highest-risk group was tour bus drivers, of which 103 were to be tested that day.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web |title=\uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u64f4\u5927\u6aa2\u6e2c\u7bc4\u570d \u5b89\u6392\u65c5\u904a\u5df4\u53f8\u6a5f\u6aa2\u6e2c\uff09\uff0d |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/317900/ |accessdate=2020-02-11 |author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |date=2020-02-11 |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211135342/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/317900/ |archivedate=2020-02-11 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 February the government announced economic relief measures, including: (1) reduction of taxes and fees to relieve the burden on businesses and residents; (2) assistance to small and medium enterprises and interest subsidies, to support the continued existence of enterprises; (3) measures to enhance people's livelihoods and support vulnerable families; (4) technical training, providing work, and protecting wages; (5) putting out electronic coupons to accelerate economic recovery.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |title=\u7d13\u89e3\u6c11\u56f0\u3001\u5171\u6e21\u6642\u8271 |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/318146/ |accessdate=2020-02-14 |author=\u7d93\u6fdf\u8ca1\u653f\u53f8\u53f8\u9577\u8fa6\u516c\u5ba4 |date=2020-02-13 |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214125602/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/318146/ |archivedate=2020-02-14 |url-status=live}}</ref> The government also announced that it would cooperate with a local research team in Macau to establish production lines in the mainland and safeguard the supply of face masks.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |title=\u7279\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u63a8\u591a\u9805\u7d93\u6fdf\u63f4\u52a9\u63aa\u65bd \u6297\u75ab\u5de5\u4f5c\u521d\u898b\u6210\u6548 \u547c\u7c72\u5e02\u6c11\u5805\u6301\u9632\u75ab\u52ff\u9b06\u61c8 |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/318253/ |accessdate=2020-02-15 |author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3 |date=2020-02-13 |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215114456/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/318253/ |archivedate=2020-02-15 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, the government announced that, after balancing epidemic prevention with citizens' need for public services, starting 17 February, basic public services would be restored.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u516c\u5171\u90e8\u9580\u4e0b\u5468\u4e00\u8d77\u50c5\u7dad\u6301\u57fa\u672c\u670d\u52d9 \u2013 \u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/318287/ |accessdate=2020-02-14 |author=\u884c\u653f\u6cd5\u52d9\u53f8\u53f8\u9577\u8fa6\u516c\u5ba4 |date=2020-02-14 |work=web.archive.org |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214105827/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/318287/ |archivedate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 February, the government announced that effective 20 February, casinos could reopen but other entertainment facilities such as cinemas and bars were to remain closed. The government also announced that migrant workers entering Macau who had been to mainland China in the past 14 days would need to undergo 14 days of medical observation at a designated location in [[Zhuhai]].<ref name=\":16\">{{cite web|title=\u5370\u52d9\u5c40 - \u884c\u653f\u9577\u5b98\u6279\u793a|url=https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/07/despce_cn.asp|accessdate=2020-02-17|author=|date=|format=|work=bo.io.gov.mo|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217090424/https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/07/despce_cn.asp|archivedate=2020-02-17|url-status=live|quote=}}</ref> At a press conference, the [[Secretariat for Economy and Finance (Macau)|Secretary for Economy and Finance]] Lei Wai Nong (\u674e\u5049\u8fb2) mentioned that when casinos reopened, they would have to follow government measures in order to protect employee and guest safety. If casinos were unable to prepare adequately for reopening, they could apply to delay reopening for up to 30 days.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u674e\u5049\u8fb2\uff1a\u614e\u91cd\u8655\u7406\u5a1b\u6a02\u5834\u91cd\u958b\u7684\u5f8c\u7e8c\u5de5\u4f5c|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319128/|accessdate=2020-02-17|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-17|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217130429/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319128/|archivedate=2020-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 February, due to the global face mask shortage, the government began providing masks with ties instead of ear straps.<ref name=\":17\">{{cite web|title=\uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u7d81\u5e36\u5f0f\u6216\u639b\u8033\u5f0f\u53e3\u7f69\u7684\u9632\u8b77\u6548\u80fd\u76f8\u540c\uff09\uff0d|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319228/|accessdate=2020-02-18|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-18|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218112834/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319228/|archivedate=2020-02-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 February, the government announced that effective 20 February, passengers coming from COVID-19 hotspots would need to undergo medical checks upon entering Macau. Medical checks might also be conducted on Macau residents who made multiple trips back and forth to Zhuhai every day. It was also announced that some parks would reopen and government broadcasts would be adjusted.<ref name=\":21\">{{cite web|title=\uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u653f\u5e9c\u8abf\u6574\u9632\u75ab\u63aa\u65bd\uff09\uff0d|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319322/|accessdate=2020-02-19|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-19|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219102214/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319322/|archivedate=2020-02-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAll casinos reopened on 20 February 2020,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/3051571/macau-casinos-reopen-after-coronavirus-shutdown-gamblers-keep-their|title=Gamblers hedge their bets as Macau casinos reopen to small crowds|date=2020-02-20|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref> but visitor numbers remained low due to the pandemic, with hotels at less than 12% occupancy at the end of February.<ref name=\"88 percent\">{{cite news |last1=Sullivan |first1=Lewis |title=Macau\u2019s gaming revenue fell 88 percent in February |url=https://www.casino-review.co/macau-gaming-revenue/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=Casino Review}}</ref> Macau's casinos suffered a year-on-year revenue drop of 88% during February 2020, the worst ever recorded.<ref name=\"88 percent\"/>\n\nStarting on February 20, the government of Macau restricted entry from mainland China.<ref>{{cite news |title=Macau considering easing of entry restrictions from mainland China |url=https://www.asgam.com/index.php/2020/03/12/macau-considering-easing-of-entry-restrictions-from-mainland-china/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=IAG |date=11 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 February, the government announced that the following week, 24\u201328 February, the public sector would still provide basic services.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u516c\u5171\u90e8\u9580\u4e0b\u5468\u7e7c\u7e8c\u7dad\u6301\u57fa\u672c\u670d\u52d9|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319529/|accessdate=2020-02-21|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-21|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221114529/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319529/|archivedate=2020-02-21|url-status=live}}</ref> The fourth face mask safeguarding plan would begin the following day, 22 February.<ref>{{cite web|title=\uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u7b2c\u56db\u8f2a\u4fdd\u969c\u53e3\u7f69\u4f9b\u61c9\u8a08\u5283\u660e\u5c55\u958b\uff09\uff0d|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319573/|accessdate=2020-02-21|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-21|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221115412/http://web.archive.org/screenshot/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/319573/|archivedate=2020-02-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 February, the Health Bureau announced that people entering Macau who had been to South Korea in the past 14 days would be required to undergo 14 days of medical observation.<ref name=\":22\">{{cite web|title=NEWS.GOV.MO: \u81ea\u660e\uff0826\uff09\u65e5\u4e2d\u5348\u8d77\u66fe\u5230\u97d3\u570b\u7684\u4eba\u58eb \u9700\u63a5\u53d714\u5929\u7684\u9694\u96e2\u91ab\u5b78\u89c0\u5bdf|url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20BYhxp2c|accessdate=2020-02-25|author=\u885b\u751f\u5c40|date=2020-02-25|work=news.gov.mo|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225154838/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20BYhxp2c;jsessionid=32474981D8F273844A20ADDCC779360E.app03?0|archivedate=2020-02-25|url-status=live}}</ref> The Maritime and Water Bureau announced that the opening hours of the [[Outer Harbour Ferry Terminal]] and [[Taipa Ferry Terminal]] would be changed to 07:00\u201320:00 until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|title=NEWS.GOV.MO: \u5916\u6e2f\u8207\u6c39\u4ed4\u5ba2\u904b\u78bc\u982d\u8abf\u6574\u958b\u653e\u6642\u9593|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320394/|accessdate=2020-02-25|author=\u6d77\u4e8b\u53ca\u6c34\u52d9\u5c40|date=2020-02-25|work=news.gov.mo|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225154838/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320394/;jsessionid=32474981D8F273844A20ADDCC779360E.app03?0|archivedate=2020-02-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February,<ref>{{cite web|title=\u5370\u52d9\u5c40 - \u884c\u653f\u9577\u5b98\u6279\u793a|url=https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/08/despce_cn.asp#50|accessdate=2020-02-27|author=|date=2020-02-27|work=bo.io.gov.mo|publisher=|language=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227083042/https://bo.io.gov.mo/bo/i/2020/08/despce_cn.asp#50|archivedate=2020-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref> the other venues that had been closed on 5 February along with the casinos were permitted to reopen. However, the government of Macau recommended that they implement epidemic control measures; if an outbreak occurred in such a place, they would require site control measures in accordance with Article 19 of the Infectious Disease Prevention Law.<ref>{{cite web|title=\uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u5c07\u89e3\u9664\u7f8e\u5bb9\u9662\u7b49\u5834\u6240\u7684\u95dc\u9589\u4ee4\uff09\uff0d|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320478/|accessdate=2020-02-27|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-27|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227104957/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320478/|archivedate=2020-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref> The government of Macau announced that effective 2 March, public services would return to normal.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u516c\u5171\u90e8\u9580\u4e0b\u5468\u4e00\u8d77\u6062\u5fa9\u6b63\u5e38\u8fa6\u516c|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320518/|accessdate=2020-02-27|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-27|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227110408/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320518/|archivedate=2020-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref> Private tutoring and continuing education institutions that meet health guidelines could also resume operations.<ref>{{cite web|title=\uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u88dc\u7fd2\u793e\u7b49\u65bc3\u67082\u65e5\u8d77\u5206\u6279\u5206\u968e\u6bb5\u6062\u5fa9\u904b\u4f5c\uff09\uff0d|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320488/|accessdate=2020-02-27|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-27|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227110903/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320488/|archivedate=2020-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref> The Education Bureau announced that, subject to the conditions that Macau and [[Guangdong Province]] had no new confirmed cases for 14 consecutive days and Macau schools did not resume classes before Zhuhai and [[Zhongshan]], it would be possible to announce the resumption of classes at non-tertiary schools.<ref name=\":27\">{{cite web|title=\uff0d\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u8a02\u5b9a\u975e\u9ad8\u7b49\u6559\u80b2\u5fa9\u8ab2\u65e5\u7684\u539f\u5247\uff09\uff0d|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320473/|accessdate=2020-02-27|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-02-27|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227111610/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320473/|archivedate=2020-02-27|url-status=live}}</ref> The Correctional Services Authority announced that visiting services would partially resume on 4 March.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u61f2\u6559\u7ba1\u7406\u5c403\u67084\u65e5\u8d77\u5c40\u90e8\u6062\u5fa9\u63a2\u8a2a\u670d\u52d9|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320757/|accessdate=2020-03-28|author=\u61f2\u6559\u7ba1\u7406\u5c40|date=2020-02-28|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328052149/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320757/|archivedate=2020-03-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 February, it was announced that passengers who had been to Italy or Iran in the past 14 days would need to undergo 14 days of medical observation in isolation. Macau residents would be permitted to undergo medical observation at a home location deemed appropriate by authorities.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u81ea\u4eca\uff0829\uff09\u65e5\u4e2d\u5348\u8d77\u66fe\u5230\u610f\u5927\u5229\u6216\u4f0a\u6717\u7684\u5165\u5883\u4eba\u58eb\u9808\u63a5\u53d714\u5929\u7684\u9694\u96e2\u91ab\u5b78\u89c0\u5bdf|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320881/|accessdate=2020-02-29|author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=2020-02-29|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229112717/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/320881/|archivedate=2020-02-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===March 2020===\n\nOn 8 March it was announced that starting at noon the same day, people entering Macau who had been to Germany, France, Spain, or Japan in the past 14 days would need to undergo a health check. In addition, starting 10 March at noon, passengers coming from those locations would need to undergo 14 days of isolation and medical observation at a designated location. Macau residents would be permitted to undergo medical observation at an approved home location.<ref name=\":29\">{{Cite web|title=\u672c\u6fb3\u5206\u5225\u81ea\u4eca\u65e5\u53ca\u4e0b\u5468\u4e8c\u4e2d\u5348\u8d77\u5c0d\u66fe\u5230\u5fb7\u570b\u3001\u6cd5\u570b\u3001\u897f\u73ed\u7259\u6216\u65e5\u672c\u7684\u5165\u5883\u4eba\u58eb\u63a1\u53d6\u91ab\u5b78\u6aa2\u67e5\u53ca14\u5929\u9694\u96e2\u91ab\u5b78\u89c0\u5bdf|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322218/|accessdate=2020-03-08|author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=2020-03-08|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305125732/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322218/|archivedate=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref> The Tertiary Education Bureau announced measures to help students from Macau studying abroad to purchase face masks.<ref name=\":34\">{{Cite web|title=\u5728\u5916\u5730\u5c31\u8b80\u7684\u6fb3\u9580\u5927\u5b78\u751f\u53ef\u900f\u904e\u53e3\u7f69\u4fdd\u969c\u8a08\u5283\u8cfc\u8cb7\u53e3\u7f69|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322289/|accessdate=2020-03-14|author=\u9ad8\u7b49\u6559\u80b2\u5c40|date=2020-03-08 |format=HTML |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314081930/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322289/|archivedate=2020-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, the Sports Bureau announced that sports facilities under its authority had gradually resumed opening starting March 2, and that other facilities would be able to gradually resume opening starting 11 March. These facilities had been closed since 24 January.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u9ad4\u80b2\u5c40\u201c\u516c\u5171\u9ad4\u80b2\u8a2d\u65bd\u7db2\u7d61\u201d\u5167\u5404\u9ad4\u80b2\u8a2d\u65bd3\u670811\u65e5\u91cd\u65b0\u5c0d\u5916\u958b\u653e\u5b89\u6392|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322409/|accessdate=2020-03-10|author=\u9ad4\u80b2\u5c40|date=2020-03-09|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310140130/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322409/|archivedate=2020-03-10|url-status=live}}</ref> The Blood Donation Center announced the suspension of blood donation by at-risk individuals for 28 days.<ref name=\":33\">{{Cite web|title=\u6350\u8840\u4e2d\u5fc3\u61c9\u5c0d\u201c\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u80ba\u708e\u201d\u7684\u6700\u65b0\u63aa\u65bd|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322374/|accessdate=2020-03-14|author=\u885b\u751f\u5c40|date=2020-03-09|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314074638/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/322374/|archivedate=2020-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, the Education and Youth Affairs Bureau announced a contingency plan for resuming classes in stages, with different grades gradually going back to school on different dates from 30 March and 4 May.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u7279\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u547c\u7c72\u5e02\u6c11\u5982\u975e\u5fc5\u8981\u52ff\u5916\u904a \u516c\u4f48\u975e\u9ad8\u7b49\u6559\u80b2\u7684\u5206\u968e\u6bb5\u5fa9\u8ab2\u9810\u6848|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323058/|accessdate=2020-03-13|author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=2020-03-13|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312140624/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323058/|archivedate=2020-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, it was announced that people entering Macau who had been to the COVID-19 hotspots of the [[Schengen Area]], the United Kingdom, the United States, Canada, Russia, Brazil, Egypt, Australia, or New Zealand in the past 14 days would be required to undergo medical observation at a designated location.<ref name=\"qu0314\">{{Cite web|title=\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u591a\u500b\u570b\u5bb6\u6216\u5730\u5340\u88ab\u65b0\u589e\u5217\u5165\u9ad8\u767c\u5730\u5340\uff09 |url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20CNpLrh0;jsessionid=5F167B7154B9B8F0C2F27F46A70F7A01.app03?0|accessdate=2020-03-14|author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=2020-03-14|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330144608/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20CNpLrh0;jsessionid=E426A6DAB90AA280A2027822FEB77FC1.app02?0 |archivedate=2020-03-30|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=30\u9ad8\u5371\u570b\u5bb6\u8fd4\u6fb3\u9580\u4eba\u58eb\u9808\u9694\u96e214\u5929\u3000\u9ad8\u7b49\u9662\u6821\u4e0b\u67081\u65e5\u5fa9\u8ab2|url=https://hk.on.cc/hk/bkn/cnt/news/20200314/bkn-20200314173508703-0314_00822_001.html?eventsection=hk_cnnews&eventid=71549E518A5CCA45E050007F010049A4 |accessdate=2020-03-14 |author= |date=2020-03-14 |format=|work=on.cc\u4e1c\u7f51|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=|archivedate=|url-status=live}}</ref>The Tertiary Education Bureau announced that some classes meeting certain conditions would be allowed to resume on 1 April.<ref name=\":35\">{{Cite web|title=\u6d77\u5916\u8fd4\u6fb3\u5b78\u751f\u9808\u63a5\u53d7\u5bb6\u5c45\u91ab\u5b78\u89c0\u5bdf \u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3\u547c\u7c72\u56b4\u683c\u9075\u5b88\u885b\u751f\u6307\u5f15|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323152/|accessdate=2020-03-14|author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=2020-03-14 |format=HTML |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314144405/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323152/ |archivedate=2020-03-14 |url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, it was announced that students returning to Macau from abroad would have to undergo 14 days of medical observation at home and a nucleic acid test.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u6d77\u5916\u56de\u6fb3\u5b78\u751f\u9808\u63a5\u53d714\u5929\u5bb6\u5c45\u91ab\u5b78\u89c0\u5bdf\uff09|url=https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20CN3jwSS?3|accessdate=2020-03-14|author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=2020-03-14 |format=HTML |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315021910/https://news.gov.mo/detail/zh-hant/N20CN3jwSS;jsessionid=F2A8C45AD59381824CF5E86248697F54.app01?0 |archivedate=2020-03-15 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, it was announced that New Zealand is not considered a COVID-19 hotspot.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a (,\u65b0\u897f\u862d\u4e0d\u88ab\u5217\u5165\u9ad8\u767c\u5730\u5340)|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323210/|accessdate=2020-03-15|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-03-15|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315021412/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323210/ |archivedate=2020-03-15|url-status=live}}</ref> The Tourism Bureau announced that from 17 March to 22 March the government would arrange transportation from [[Hong Kong International Airport]] for Macau residents and students coming from European countries to bring them to a designated location for 14 days of medical observation.<ref>{{Cite web|title=\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u63a5\u8f09\u5f9e\u6b50\u6d32\u795e\u6839\u5730\u5340\u8fd4\u9999\u6e2f\u7684\u672c\u6fb3\u6b50\u6d32\u7559\u5b78\u751f\u53ca\u5916\u904a\u6b50\u6d32\u7684\u6fb3\u9580\u5c45\u6c11\u5b89\u6392\uff09|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323219/|accessdate=2020-03-15|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40|date=2020-03-15|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315021412/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323219/|archivedate=2020-03-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, it was announced that starting 17 March at midnight (00:00), people arriving in Macau from any countries outside China (meaning mainland China, Hong Kong, Macau, and Taiwan) would have to undergo 14 days of medical observation at a designated location. The Tourism Bureau announced that transportation from Hong Kong International Airport to a designated location would be arranged for Macau residents and students coming from the United States as well as European countries.<ref name=\":37\">{{Cite web|title=\u660e\u65e5\u96f6\u6642\u8d77\u672c\u6fb3\u5c0d\u4e2d\u570b\u4ee5\u5916\u570b\u5bb6\u6216\u5730\u5340\u5165\u5883\u4eba\u58eb\u5be6\u65bd\u91ab\u5b78\u89c0\u5bdf\u63aa\u65bd \u547c\u7c72\u5165\u5883\u4eba\u58eb\u5165\u5883\u5982\u5be6\u7533\u5831 \u5c45\u6c11\u5982\u975e\u5fc5\u8981\u52ff\u5916\u904a|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323430/ |accessdate=2020-03-16 |author=\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u611f\u67d3\u61c9\u8b8a\u5354\u8abf\u4e2d\u5fc3|date=2020-03-16 |format=HTML |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |publisher= |language=zh-hant |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316154242/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323430/ |archivedate=2020-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nEffective March 18, the government banned entry of all non-residents, with exceptions for mainland China, Hong Kong, and Taiwan.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://macaunews.mo/macau-prohibits-non-residents-from-entering-macau-with-the-exception-of-those-from-mainland-china-hong-kong-and-taiwan/|title=Macau Prohibits Non-Residents from Entering Macau with the exception of those from Mainland China, Hong Kong and Taiwan|website=Macau News |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the Tourism Bureau announced that from 19 March to 31 March, transportation from Hong Kong International Airport would take Macau residents and students coming from all countries to designated locations for medical observation.\n\nOn 19 March, the plan for resuming classes in stages was cancelled.<ref name=\":46\">{{Cite web|title=\u975e\u9ad8\u7b49\u6559\u80b2\u5b78\u6821\u5ef6\u671f\u5fa9\u8ab2\u81f3\u53e6\u884c\u518d\u516c\u5e03 |url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323922/|accessdate=2020-03-19|author=\u6559\u80b2\u66a8\u9752\u5e74\u5c40|date=2020-03-19|format=|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9 |publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319114318/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/323922/ |archivedate=2020-03-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, the chief executive announced that starting 25 March, connecting flights would no longer be permitted at [[Macau International Airport]]; any residents of Hong Kong, Taiwan, or mainland China who had been to other countries in the previous 14 days were prohibited from entering Macau; and Macau residents who had been to Hong Kong, Taiwan, or other countries in the past 14 days would be required to undergo 14 days of medical observation at a designated location.<ref name=\":56\">{{Cite web|title=\uff0d\u884c\u653f\u9577\u5b98\u8a18\u8005\u6703\u5feb\u8a0a\uff08\u660e\u8d77\u7981\u6b62\u5165\u5883\u524d14\u5929\u5167\u66fe\u5230\u5916\u570b\u7684\u975e\u6fb3\u9580\u5c45\u6c11\u5165\u5883\uff09\uff0d|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/324556/|accessdate=2020-03-24|author=\u65b0\u805e\u5c40 |date=2020-03-24 |format=HTML |work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200324031513/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/324556/|archivedate=2020-03-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the Health Bureau expanded restrictions on blood donations.<ref name=\":63\">{{Cite web|title=\u6350\u8840\u4e2d\u5fc3\u61c9\u5c0d\u65b0\u578b\u51a0\u72c0\u75c5\u6bd2\u80ba\u708e\u7684\u6700\u65b0\u63aa\u65bd\u548c\u547c\u7c72\u6350\u8840|url=https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/325006/|accessdate=2020-03-25|author=2020-03-25|date=2020-03-25|format=HTML|work=\u6fb3\u9580\u7279\u5225\u884c\u653f\u5340\u653f\u5e9c\u5165\u53e3\u7db2\u7ad9|publisher=|language=zh-hant|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325131008/https://www.gov.mo/zh-hant/news/325006/|archivedate=2020-03-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\n\nOn 4 April, the government of Macau followed the Chinese central government in holding day of mourning throughout Macau. [[Chinese flag]]s and [[Macau flag]]s were to be flown at [[half mast]], and public entertainment and celebrations or festive events were to stop. Starting at 10AM that day, Macau would observe a three-minute moment of silence.<ref>[https://hd.stheadline.com/news/realtime/hk/1739427/%E5%8D%B3%E6%99%82-%E6%B8%AF%E8%81%9E-%E7%96%AB%E6%83%85%E4%B8%8B%E5%85%A7%E5%9C%B0%E6%98%8E%E6%97%A5%E5%85%A8%E5%9C%8B%E5%93%80%E6%82%BC-%E6%BE%B3%E9%96%80%E5%B0%87%E4%B8%8B%E5%8D%8A%E6%97%97%E8%87%B4%E5%93%80 \u75ab\u60c5\u4e0b\u5167\u5730\u660e\u65e5\u5168\u570b\u54c0\u60bc \u6fb3\u9580\u5c07\u4e0b\u534a\u65d7\u81f4\u54c0]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by dependent territory|Macau]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in China by city|Macau]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Macau]]\n[[Category:2020 in Macau]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Macau]]\n", "name_user": "Mx. Granger", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril 2020:copyediting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Macau"}
{"title_page": "Google Test", "text_new": "{{selfref|For Wikipedia's how-to guide on referencing Google search results in deletion, notability or other discussions, see [[Wikipedia:Search engine test]]}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{third-party|date=August 2013}}\n{{tone|date=June 2016}}\n}}\n{{Advert|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = Google Test\n| developer = [[Google]]\n| latest release version = 1.10.0\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2019|10|03}}\n| repo = {{URL|https://github.com/google/googletest/}}\n| operating system = [[Linux]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[macOS]]\n| programming language = [[C++]]\n| genre = [[Unit testing]] tool\n| license = [[BSD licenses|BSD 3-clauses]]\n}}\n\n'''Google Test''' (also known as gtest for e.g. the [[Robot Operating System|ROS]] environment<ref>[http://wiki.ros.org/gtest#Google_Test_.28gtest.29 Google Test (gtest)] in the wiki of ros.org</ref>) is a [[unit testing]] library for the [[C++|C++ programming language]], based on the [[xUnit]] architecture.<ref name=quick_intro>[http://www.ibm.com/developerworks/aix/library/au-googletestingframework.html A quick introduction to the Google C++ Testing Framework], Arpan Sen, IBM DeveloperWorks, 2010-05-11, retrieved 2016-04-12</ref> The library is released under the BSD 3-clause license.<ref>[https://github.com/google/googletest Google Test's repository], retrieved 2016-04-12, cites [http://opensource.org/licenses/BSD-3-Clause New BSD] as license. The license file is at {{URL|https://github.com/google/googletest/blob/master/googletest/LICENSE}}</ref> It can be compiled for a variety of [[POSIX]] and [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] platforms, allowing unit-testing of C sources as well as C++ with minimal source modification.{{vague}} The tests themselves could be run one at a time, or even be called to run all at once. This makes the debugging process very specific.{{clarify}}\n\n\n==Projects using Google Test==\nBesides being developed and used at Google, many other projects implement Google Test as well:\n    \n* [[Chromium (web browser)|Chromium]] projects (behind the Chrome browser and Chrome OS)\n* [[LLVM]] compiler\n* [[Protocol Buffers]] (Google's data interchange format)\n* [[OpenCV]] computer vision library\n* [[Gromacs]] molecular dynamics simulation package<ref>[http://manual.gromacs.org/documentation/5.1/dev-manual/testutils.html#unit-testing-framework Gromacs Testing Framework]</ref>\n\n==Related tools==\n\nGoogle Test UI is test runner that runs one's test binary, allows one to track its progress via a progress bar, and displays a list of test failures. Clicking on one shows failure text. Google Test UI is written in C#.<ref>[https://github.com/ospector/gtest-gbar Google Test UI] retrieved 2016-04-12</ref> Additionally, a feature-complete [[Visual Studio]] extension exists with Google Test Adapter.<ref>[https://github.com/csoltenborn/GoogleTestAdapter]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n*[[List of unit testing frameworks]]\n*[[CppUnit]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Whittaker |first=James |title=How Google Tests Software |date=2012 |publisher=Pearson Education |location=Boston, Massachusetts |isbn=0-321-80302-7}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://github.com/google/googletest Google Test]\n* [https://github.com/google/googletest/blob/master/googletest/docs/primer.md Google Test Primer documentation]\n* [http://www.ibm.com/developerworks/aix/library/au-googletestingframework.html A quick introduction to the Google C++ Testing Framework], Arpan Sen, IBM DeveloperWorks, 2010-05-11\n* [http://googletesting.blogspot.com/2014/01/the-google-test-and-development_21.html The Google Test and Development Environment], Anthony Vallone, 2014-01-21\n\n[[Category:C++ libraries]]\n[[Category:Extreme programming]]\n[[Category:Freedesktop.org]]\n[[Category:Unit testing frameworks]]\n[[Category:Software using the BSD license]]\n", "text_old": "{{selfref|For Wikipedia's how-to guide on referencing Google search results in deletion, notability or other discussions, see [[Wikipedia:Search engine test]]}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{third-party|date=August 2013}}\n{{tone|date=June 2016}}\n}}\n{{Advert|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = Google Test\n| developer = [[Google]]\n| latest release version = 1.10.0\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2019|10|03}}\n| repo = {{URL|https://github.com/google/googletest/}}\n| operating system = [[Linux]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[macOS]]\n| programming language = [[C++]]\n| genre = [[Unit testing]] tool\n| license = [[BSD licenses|BSD 3-clauses]]\n}}\n\n'''Google Test''' (also known as gtest for e.g. the [[Robot Operating System|ROS]] environment<ref>[http://wiki.ros.org/gtest#Google_Test_.28gtest.29 Google Test (gtest)] in the wiki of ros.org</ref>) is a [[unit testing]] library for the [[C++|C++ programming language]], based on the [[xUnit]] architecture.<ref name=quick_intro>[http://www.ibm.com/developerworks/aix/library/au-googletestingframework.html A quick introduction to the Google C++ Testing Framework], Arpan Sen, IBM DeveloperWorks, 2010-05-11, retrieved 2016-04-12</ref> The library is released under the BSD 3-clause license.<ref>[https://github.com/google/googletest Google Test's repository], retrieved 2016-04-12, cites [http://opensource.org/licenses/BSD-3-Clause New BSD] as license. The license file is at {{URL|https://github.com/google/googletest/blob/master/googletest/LICENSE}}</ref> It can be compiled for a variety of [[POSIX]] and [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] platforms, allowing unit-testing of C sources as well as C++ with minimal source modification. The tests themselves could be run one at a time, or even be called to run all at once. This makes the debugging process very specific.\n\n\n==Projects using Google Test==\nBesides being developed and used at Google, many other projects implement Google Test as well:\n    \n* [[Chromium (web browser)|Chromium]] projects (behind the Chrome browser and Chrome OS)\n* [[LLVM]] compiler\n* [[Protocol Buffers]] (Google's data interchange format)\n* [[OpenCV]] computer vision library\n* [[Gromacs]] molecular dynamics simulation package<ref>[http://manual.gromacs.org/documentation/5.1/dev-manual/testutils.html#unit-testing-framework Gromacs Testing Framework]</ref>\n\n==Related tools==\n\nGoogle Test UI is test runner that runs one's test binary, allows one to track its progress via a progress bar, and displays a list of test failures. Clicking on one shows failure text. Google Test UI is written in C#.<ref>[https://github.com/ospector/gtest-gbar Google Test UI] retrieved 2016-04-12</ref> Additionally, a feature-complete [[Visual Studio]] extension exists with Google Test Adapter.<ref>[https://github.com/csoltenborn/GoogleTestAdapter]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n*[[List of unit testing frameworks]]\n*[[CppUnit]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Whittaker |first=James |title=How Google Tests Software |date=2012 |publisher=Pearson Education |location=Boston, Massachusetts |isbn=0-321-80302-7}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://github.com/google/googletest Google Test]\n* [https://github.com/google/googletest/blob/master/googletest/docs/primer.md Google Test Primer documentation]\n* [http://www.ibm.com/developerworks/aix/library/au-googletestingframework.html A quick introduction to the Google C++ Testing Framework], Arpan Sen, IBM DeveloperWorks, 2010-05-11\n* [http://googletesting.blogspot.com/2014/01/the-google-test-and-development_21.html The Google Test and Development Environment], Anthony Vallone, 2014-01-21\n\n[[Category:C++ libraries]]\n[[Category:Extreme programming]]\n[[Category:Freedesktop.org]]\n[[Category:Unit testing frameworks]]\n[[Category:Software using the BSD license]]\n", "name_user": "Wolfbeast", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added clarification requests.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google_Test"}
{"title_page": "No Letting Go (film)", "text_new": "{{For|the Wayne Wonder song|No Letting Go (song)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = No Letting Go\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = Jonathan D. Bucari\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Jonathan D. Bucari\n* Carina Rush\n* Randi Silverman\n}}\n| screenplay     = Jonathan D. Bucari<br>Randi Silverman\n| based on       = {{Based on|''Illness''|Jonathan D. Bucari}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Richard Burgi]]\n*[[Kathy Najimy]]\n*[[Alysia Reiner]]\n*[[Jared Gilman]]\n*[[Noah Fleiss]]\n}}\n| music          = Alain Mayrand\n| cinematography = Oren Soffer\n| editing        = Jonathan D. Bucari\n| studio         = Demian Pictures<br>Illness Productions\n| distributor    = Vision Films \n| released       = {{Film date|2015|9|26|NYC Mental Health Film Festiva}}\n| runtime        = 104 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''No Letting Go''''' is a 2015 American drama film directed by Jonathan D. Bucari.  It is Bucari's directorial debut and is based on his 2013 short film ''Illness''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Scheck|first=Frank|title='No Letting Go': Film Review|date=25 March 2016|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/no-letting-go-film-review-878433|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref>  It is also based on the true story of the producer and co-screenwriter Randi Silverman.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sederer|first=Lloyd I.|title=\u2018No Letting Go\u2019: A Film Review|date=21 March 2016|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/lloyd-i-sederer-md/no-letting-go-a-film-review_b_9508070.html|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\n{{no plot|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Cast==\n*Cheryl Allison as Catherine\n*[[Richard Burgi]] as Henry\n*David Schallipp as Timothy (10 yrs)\n*Noah Silverman as Timothy (14 yrs)\n*[[Seamus Davey-Fitzpatrick]] as Kyle (14 yrs